<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-DebateExcerpts 2Takes 1 10-14 1181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Debate Excerpts, 2 Takes, 1,000-up</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts From Bush-Dukakis Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts of Thursday's presidential
debate between Republican Vice President George Bush and Democrat
Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts.
   Q: ... Governor, if Kitty Dukakis were raped and murdered, would
you favor an irrevocable death penalty for the killer?
   Dukakis: No, I don't ... I've opposed the death penalty during
all of my life. I don't see any evidence that it's a deterrent, and
I think there are better and more effective ways to deal with
violent crime. ... We have work to do to fight a real war and not a
phony war against drugs. ... And I want to call a hemispheric
summit just as soon after the 20th of January as possible to fight
that war.
   Bush: I do believe that some crimes are so heinous, so brutal,
so outrageous _ and I'd say particularly those that result in the
death of a police officer _ those real brutal crimes, I do believe
in the death penalty.
   Q: What have you to say about (Dan Quayle becoming president in
the event of Bush's death)?
   Bush: ... I'd have confidence in him, and I made a good
selection. ... And I've never seen a presidential campaign where
the presidential nominee runs against my vice presidential nominee.
... You know, the American people are fair. They don't like it when
there's an unfair pounding and kind of hooting about people. They
want to judge it on the record itself.
   Dukakis: Mr. Bush picked Dan Quayle and, before he did it, he
said, ``Watch my choice for vice president. It will tell all.'' And
it sure did. It sure did.
   Q: After income tax rates were cut, in each of the last five
years, some federal taxes have gone up ... Isn't the phrase ``no
new taxes'' misleading the voters?
   Bush: ... What I have proposed is something much better. And
it's going to take discipline of the executive branch. It's going
to take discipline of the congressional branch, and that is what I
call a flexible freeze that allows growth _ about 4 percent or the
rate of inflation _ but does not permit the Congress just to add on
spending.
   Dukakis: The vice president made that pledge; he's broken it
three times in the past year already, so it isn't worth the paper
it's printed on. ... And what I'm concerned about is that if we
continue with the policies that Mr. Bush is talking about here this
evening _ flexible freeze _ somebody described it the other day as
a kind of economic Slurpee.
   Q: ... Do you think that a president has to be likable to be an
effective leader?
   Dukakis: ... I think I'm a reasonably likeable guy. I'm serious,
though I think I'm a little more lovable these days than I used to
be back in my youth when I began in my state legislature. But, I'm
also a serious guy. I think the presidency of the United States is
a very serious office. ...
   Q: The tenor of the campaign you've been running in terms of
both the issues and your rhetoric has surprised even some of your
friends. ...
   Bush: ... What I've had to do is to define not just my position,
but to define his (Dukakis'). And I hope I've done it fairly. ...
I'm not the one that compared the president of the United States of
rotting like a dead fish from the head down; I didn't do that. But
I have defined the issues and I am not going to let Gov. Dukakis go
through this election without explaining some of these very liberal
positions.
   Dukakis: ... I don't think these labels mean a thing, and I
would hope that tonight, and in the course of the rest of this
campaign, we can have our good, solid disagreements on issues;
there's nothing the matter with that. But let's stop labeling each
other and let's get to the heart of the matter, which is the future
of this country.
   Q: ... There has been a bipartisan consensus in favor of
modernizing the land-based missiles. Now, you have ruled out the MX
and the Midgetman. ... what type of land-based missile would you
consider?
   Dukakis: There are limits to this nation's ability to finance
these weapons systems. ... How can we build a strong America
militarily that's teeter-tottering on a mountain of debt? ... We
cannot continue to tell the American people that we're going to
build all of these systems, and at the same time invest in
important things here at home ...
   Bush: You just don't make unilateral cuts in the naive hope that
the Soviets are going to behave themselves. ... We have enhanced
the peace. And I'm proud to have been a part of an administration
that has done exactly that. Peace through strength works.
   Q: ... Who are the heroes ... you would point out to young
Americans as figures who should inspire this country?
   Bush: I think of a teacher right here _ largely Hispanic school
_ Jamie Escalante, teaching calculus to young kids, 80 percent of
them going on to college. ... I think of those people that took us
back into space again _ Rick Hauck and that crew ... I also think
we ought to give a little credit to the President of the United
States. ... because American people say, he is our hero.
   Q: Is there anything nice you can say about (Dukakis)?
   Bush: ... The concept of the Dukakis family has my great
respect. And I'd say, I don't know whether that's kind or not, it's
just an objective statement.
   Dukakis: .... We may have different approaches, we may think
that you deal with them in different days, but they're basically
American. I believe in them, George Bush believes in them, I think
the vast majority of Americans believe in them ...
   Q: Why should a woman who discovers .... the baby will live at
most two years, and those two years in incredible pain, be forced
to carry the fetus to term, and yet a woman who becomes pregnant
through incest would be allowed to abort her fetus?
   Bush: ... Bar and I lost a child ... We lost a daughter If that
child were here today, and I was told this same thing ... that
child could stay alive for 10 or 15 years, or maybe for the rest of
her life. And so, I don't think that you make an exception based on
medical knowledge at the time. ... It is personal. And I don't
assail him on that issue or others on that issue. But, that's the
way I, George Bush, feel about it.
   Dukakis: We lost a baby -- lived about 20 minutes after it was
born. But, isn't the real question that we have to answer, not how
many exceptions we make ... it's who makes the decision, who makes
this very difficult, very wrenching decision.
</TEXT>
