<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines-Blackout 1stLd-Writethru a0741 10-14 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Blackout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blackout Affects Manila, Luzon Island</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator. LEADS with three
grafs to update with power restored; picks up 5th pvs: The cause...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power outage hit Manila and the
rest of the main Philippine island of Luzon Thursday evening,
causing huge traffic jams and shutting down the capital's rail
system.
   Power was restored to all but a few isolated places by Friday
morning, including some districts in the capital, a spokeswoman for
the National Power Corp. said.
   But sporadic blackouts still plagued scattered neighborhoods in
metropolitan Manila. Public schools were closed Friday in the
capital because of power problems and heavy rains.
   The cause of the outage was not immediately known. It affected
the 40,420-square-mile island of Luzon, the largest of the nation's
7,100 islands. Manila, which has about 7 million residents, is on
Luzon.
   Armando Plata, senior vice president of the Power Corporation,
said a series of malfunctions at power plants triggered the
blackout. But Patria Gutierrez, a corporation spokeswoman, said
``we think it is weather-related.''
   Officials said heavy rains over the island may have caused a
``domino effect'' that overloaded the island's power system.
   The private ABS-CBN television station in Manila said troops
were placed on alert as a precaution and checkpoints were
established along strategic areas of the sprawling metropolis.
   Operations at Manila's Ninoy Aquino International Airport were
unaffected because it has emergency generators.
   In the capital, power was restored first in suburban Quezon
City, where most military camps are located, and at Malacanang
Palace, President Corazon Aquino's office compound, radio stations
reported.
   The military dispatched a dozen army trucks to ferry stranded
commuters to various points in the capital, radio stations reported.
</TEXT>
