<DOCNO> AP881014-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thatcher     10-14 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thatcher,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Shows Thatcher Unassailable, But Some Tories Uneasy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presiding over her Conservative Party's
convention this week, Margaret Thatcher is looking unassailable.
   But 10 years into her administration, her complete control of
the party, government and political agenda is beginning to stir
unease among some Tories.
   What little dissent exists at the convention in this English
seaside resort comes across carefully coded, and its recurrent
theme is a feeling that after a decade of tough economic
management, the time has come to look at the problems of the
Thatcherite revolution.
   Peter Walker, secretary of state for Wales and one of the few
remaining liberals in Mrs. Thatcher's Cabinet, came closest to
spelling it out.
   ``If we ignore the problems of the economy we will fail,'' he
said at a fringe meeting off the convention floor. ``If we ignore
social problems we will fail ... The present political climate
could create complacency and even arrogance. We must see that our
party is seen to be determined and understanding.''
   Walker's remarks reflected the nervousness of some
Conservatives, that, having won office in 1979 and apparently
heading for a fourth consecutive term in the 1990s, their party is
in danger of becoming arrogant.
   ``It is very, very hard to explain, even to our own supporters,
that the Conservatives don't hate Sheffield,'' said Irvine Patnick,
a rank-and-file Tory legislator from the economically depressed
northern steel city.
   ``They blame everything on her, they don't like her. But then
they just see her with her handbag _ that sort of thing. They don't
know her,'' said Patnick, speaking in an interview.
   A 59-year-old former builder whose north England accent
contrasts with the plummy voices of many of the middle-class or
newly rich Tories from the prosperous south, Patnick was referring
to a continuing paradox: most Britons dislike Mrs. Thatcher as a
person but like her as a leader.
   In Gallup's latest sounding, just 8 percent of voters questioned
rated Mrs. Thatcher likeable, compared with a 44 percent rating for
Neil Kinnock, leader of the opposition Labor Party. But 61 percent
saw her as the most suitable leader.
   Sheffield, battered by the closure of steel plants and coal
mines, has one Conservative legislator and six Laborites.
   In other great cities of northern England and Scotland,
including Manchester, Liverpool and Glasgow, the Conservatives won
not a single seat in the 1987 election which gave Mrs. Thatcher a
third five-year term.
   The party liberals are increasingly concerned that while the
traditional class structure is fracturing under the impact of the
new Thatcherite Tories, the north-south divide is widening.
   The nation's nurses present a typical dilemma. Their pay demands
enjoy popular support, but clash with the imperatives of
Thatcherite curbs on public spending. Thus, when Health Minister
Kenneth Clarke announced a $235 million boost for nurses' pay, he
was cheered by delegates who ordinarily have little time for
generosity at the taxpayers' expense.
   But otherwise, the liberals are a minority. ``There is no
challenge here to Mrs. Thatcher's ascendancy _ she continues to
look imperishable,'' said the liberal Guardian. And much of the
convention has been spent lining up new targets for the Thatcher
treatment.
   They range from plans to sell off British Coal, one of the last
major industries to survive Mrs. Thatcher's privatization drive, to
handing the construction of highways to independent entrepreneurs.
   Economic danger signals _ a record trade deficit and inflation
up to 5.7 percent and rising _ scarcely ruffled the atmosphere of
well-being in the convention center adorned with the slogan
``Leading Britain Into The 1990s.''
   But amid the series of congratulatory convention resolutions
were occasional signs of unease that while Mrs. Thatcher's Britain
has gotten richer, it is also more violent; its industries are more
efficient, but its cities are more littered.
   Socialist opponents blame this on a greedy, get-rich-quick
mentality they say is fostered by Thatcherism. The Thatcher remedy
is not money but what her aides call ``active citizenship'' _ a
stress on giving to charity, joining neighborhood anti-crime groups
and curbing anti-social behavior.
   But the respected conservative Economist commented that while
``active citizenship'' would do as a theme for a party convention,
it would not be seen as a solution.
   ``Enough Britons knew that they needed Nurse Thatcher's economic
medicine,'' said the weekly. ``Nanny Thatcher telling everybody to
wash their hands before tea will be ignored.''
</TEXT>
