<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shroud-Chronology     10-14 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shroud-Chronology,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cloth Revered For Centuries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shroud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Key events relating to the Shroud of Turin:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1171-1203 _ Witnesses including William of Tyre in 1171 and
Robert of Clari of the fourth crusade in 1203 report seeing the
shroud in the imperial palace at Constantinople. The trail is lost
until more than a hundred years later.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1354 _ The shroud is traced to Lirey, France.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1389 _ In the earliest known challenge to the shroud, Pierre
d'Arcis, bishop of Troyes, tells Clement VII, the papal claimant in
Avignon, France, that the shroud is a fraud and the bishop who
preceded him in Troyes knows who painted it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1453-1532 _ The shroud is kept by the royal family of Savoy at
the castle of Chambery. Fire damages it in 1532.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1578 _ The shroud begins its permanent stay at the cathedral in
Turin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1898 _ In a rare event, the silver chest containing the shroud
is opened so a man named Secundo Pia can photograph it. The result:
the image on the shroud is similar to a photographic negative, so
the negative on Pia's photographic plate gives the world its first
positive image of the man on the shroud.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1978 _ On the 400th anniversary of its arrival in Turin, the
shroud is exhibited for the first time in 45 years. An estimated 3
million people view it as it hangs suspended over an altar in a
lighted, bulletproof frame. Scientists study the shroud but say its
authenticity will remain unproven until the Vatican grants approval
for scientific dating tests.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   October 1980 _ The 32 American scientists who studied the shroud
say the image on the shroud was not painted on. The scientists,
called the Shroud of Turin Research Group, say the cloth has too
many subtle properties to be the work of a human hand.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   September 1981 _ A researcher from the U.S. group suggests in a
book there is strong evidence that the shroud was the burial cloth
of Christ. Other group members disagree.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 28, 1982 _ Alan Whanger, a Duke University professor,
compares images of Jesus on a 6th century Byzantine icon and a 7th
century coin with that on the shroud and says there are
``astonishing'' similarities.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 30, 1982 _ Dr. Luigi Malantrucco, an Italian physician,
says after studying the shroud that Christ died on the cross of a
heart attack, not of suffocation as previously believed. He says a
spot on the shroud was of blood and serum that spurted out when
Christ was stabbed. If Christ suffocated, he says, the blood would
have coagulated.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1983 _ King Umberto II of Italy dies and bequeathes the shroud
to the pope.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   October 1986 _ The pope authorizes scientific dating tests on
the shroud.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 13, 1988 _ After widespread news leaks, the archbishop of
Turin announces that lab tests indicate the shroud is no more than
728 years old and cannot be the burial cloth of Christ.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shroud-Dating     10-14 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shroud-Dating,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dating Of Shroud Based On Carbon In All Living Things</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shroud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests that found the Shroud of Turin to be no more than 728
years old required less than a square inch of the linen cloth, and
were based on the fact that carbon is the basis for all living or
formerly living things.
   Laboratories at the University of Arizona, the University of
Zurich and Oxford University each received a 0.3-square-inch sample
of the shroud and two dummy cloth samples, one carbon-dated and the
other dated historically but not scientifically to see if they get
consistent results for all three samples.
   The labs were not told which sample was from the 14-foot, 3-inch
by 3-foot, 7-inch shroud, the Vatican said. The cutting was
photographed and videotaped.
   Here, briefly, is how radiocarbon dating works:
   Carbon-12, carbon-13 and carbon-14 are the isotopes of carbon,
different only in the number of neutrons in their atomic nuclei.
The first two are stable but carbon-14 is radioactive and decays at
a known rate. Its half-life is 5,730 years _ the time it takes half
of the isotope in a material to decay.
   All living things absorb carbon, and stop absorbing it when they
die. By measuring the proportion of carbon-14 left in a sample,
scientists can tell how long ago the plant or animal it came from
died.
   To count the atoms, a sample must be converted into carbon
dioxide. This is done by burning.
   To study the shround, a technique was used that is more advanced
than original procedures used in the 1940s, when carbon-dating was
first applied. The modern technique uses a nuclear atom-counting
machine called an accelerator mass spectrometer. It propels carbon
dioxide through a tube at tremendous speed, causing the various
atomic particles to separate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0013 </DOCNO>
