<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0691 10-14 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Walk and Raisin Bran Part of Dukakis Debate Prep</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 13 grafs new with Dukakis comment at rally; picks up 6th
graf pvs, bgng, `Dukakis has.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis claimed victory over
Republican George Bush in their second and final debate, telling
partisan supporters that the race for the White House is ``going to
get even closer after tonight.''
   ``A clean sweep?'' the Democratic presidential nominee,
referring to his first debate with Bush and the vice presidential
clash, asked the crowd gathered for a post-debate rally at the
Beverly Hills Hilton. They roared with approval.
   ``I think we ought to have that third debate, don't you,''
Dukakis said.
   ``We've gotten the Republicans out from behind the flag factory
and the balloons and discussing the issues. That's why debates are
so important. That's why we ought to have a third debate as was
originally planned.''
   Asked during the debate if he would take part in a third debate,
Bush replied ``no'' and said the American people had seen enough
debates through the primary and presidential campaigns.
   Recent polls have shown that Dukakis faces an uphill climb in
overcoming an apparent Bush lead. The Democratic nominee said the
race is ``very, very close.''
   ``And it's going to get even closer after tonight and it's going
to get closer still in the days ahead,'' he said.
   Aides viewed the debate as vital to Dukakis' chances of winning
the support of a majority of undecided voters while persuading some
Bush supporters to reconsider their choice.
   After the debate, Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich said
they ``didn't expect a knockout. What we expected was a strong
effort ... the governor spoke to people about the future tonight.''
   He showed he was ``ready to make the tough choices, not to blame
Congress, blame the press...'' like Bush.
   Dukakis, joined by his wife, Kitty, mother, Euterpe, and his two
daughters, was attending two private functions with prominent
fund-raisers and Democratic Party officials.
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis, keeping with his campaign ritual,
began his day with a ``power walk,'' a brisk stroll during which
the Massachusetts governor carries hand weights.
   He then had his favorite breakfast of raisin bran cereal before
resuming briefings with aides and advisers.
   Dukakis has been in Los Angeles since Tuesday night and has
spent much of that time in briefings on issues and in
question-and-answer sessions with his entourage, which includes
Washington attorney Robert Barnett, who plays the role of Bush in
mock debates with the candidate.
   He planned to campaign in California and Washington on Friday,
including a joint appearance with his running mate, Texas Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, at a noon rally in Sacramento.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0654 10-14 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Dukakis ``Won Big''</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with six new grafs to update with Bentsen debate
comments; pkup 2nd graf pvs: What we're seeing ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen emerged from watching the
presidential debate Thursday night and declared that Michael
Dukakis ``not only won, he won big.''
   ``With all that pressure on him, he stood up and delivered and
he put the Democratic Party on the road to victory in November,''
Bentsen told reporters at a Houston hotel where he viewed the
proceedings on television.
   The Democratic vice presidential candidate said he and Dukakis
emerged the victors in two other debates with their Republican
opponents ``and now it's three-zip and on to Nov. 8.''
   Texas state Treasurer Ann Richards, also on hand, watched the
debate as Republican presidential candidate was critical of her
comments about him in a speech she delivered to the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta.
   ``You think George's skin's a little thin?'' she said afterward.
   Earlier, Bentsen was on Capitol Hill to fire up congressional
Democrats, telling them the party can still win the White House.
   ``What we're seeing is an all-out effort on the part of
senators, the House members, Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen,'' the
vice presidential nominee told reporters after his closed-door
sessions.
   ``I was asking for their suppport and commitment and their
leadership in their own states and we had a very enthusiastic
response,'' said Bentsen, speaking after his Senate meeting.
   ``I met with the House members over there, and they're ready to
go to work and go flat out for the next 26 days.''
   Later Thursday, Bentsen was flying to Houston to watch the
presidential debate on television and to attend a post-debate rally.
   The Dukakis-Bentsen ticket is trailing George Bush and Dan
Quayle according to most polls. But Democrats hope campaigning by
their majority in both the House and Senate can help turn that
around.
   Asked by reporters if there is enough time for the Democrats to
catch Bush, Bentsen recalled the 1968 campaign.
   ``I can't help but remember my friend Hubert Humphrey, running
about 10 points behind at this point and coming within seven-tenths
of 1 percent of winning,'' he said. ``And most political pundits
said if he had two or three more days, he'd have won it.''
   After Bentsen spoke with Senate Democrats, Dale Bumpers of
Arkansas said, ``Sen. Bentsen made one of the most compelling
persuasive speeches about what the Democratic members of the United
States Senate can do. I can tell you that everybody that came out
of that room had an entirely different idea about the winnability
of this campaign.''
   ``I think there were some doubters there'' before the speech, he
said, but ``I have never seen a response from a bunch of salty old
senators that he got this morning.''
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., said Bentsen told them ``Bush-Quayle
is totally inadequate. He talked aobut the winnability of the
election, and the role that members of the Senate can play.''
   Bentsen was introduced by Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd,
D-W.Va., who, with a slip of the tongue, seemed to express the
feelings of many senators.
   ``My colleagues, it's my pleasure to present to you the next
president _ the next vice president,'' Byrd said to roars from his
fellow Democrats.
   In the House, Bentsen met with House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, and then spoke at a meeting of House Democrats. He
received loud applause several times in what attendees described as
a ``fire-'em-up'' address.
   Before he left, Rep. Dennis Eckart, D-Ohio, who played the role
of Quayle to help Bentsen prepare for the vice presidential debate,
took the other lectern in the House chamber, according to lawmakers
and others who attended.
   Eckart went into his Quayle imitation and when he demanded,
``Senator, what are your qualifications,'' Bentsen pounced.
   ``Congressman, I know Dan Quayle. I've served with Dan Quayle.
And you're no Dan Quayle,'' he said, recalling his scolding of
Quayle in their debate after the Indiana senator compared his
experience with that of John Kennedy in 1960.
   ``It brought down the House,'' said one lawmaker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
