<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-DebateExcerpts Add   10-14 1270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Debate Excerpts, Add,1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LOS ANGELES: wrenching decision.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q: Let's assume now (you are president). You are now facing that
dreaded last resort -- increase taxes. Which tax do you decide is
the least onerous?
   Dukakis: ... We have had not one but two detailed studies which
indicate that there are billions and billions of dollars to be
collected that are not being paid in. ... And that is just
absolutely unfair to the vast majority of Americans who pay their
taxes and pay them on time.
   Q: ... Can you stand here tonight and look a whole generation
... in the eye ... and tell them that they should be financing the
retirement of people like yourself, like Governor Dukakis ...
   Bush: ... We came into office and the Social Security Trust Fund
was in great jeopardy. And the President took the leadership,
working with the Democrats and the Republicans in Congress. ... The
Social Security Trust Fund was put back into sound, solvent
condition. ... So I don't want to fool around with it. ... And I
will not go in there and suggest changes in Social Security. I
learned that the hard way. ...
   Dukakis: ... George Bush, a few years ago, said that Social
Security was basically a welfare system. And in 1985 he flew back
from the West Coast to cut that COLA. ...
   Q: ... Would your nominees to the Supreme Court have to pass
something that has been called a kind of conservative ideological
litmus test, and would you give us an idea of perhaps who two or
three people on your short list are for the court?
   Bush: Well one, I don't have a list yet. ... And secondly ... I
don't have any litmus test. But, what I would do is appoint people
to the federal bench that will not legislate from the bench, who
will interpret the Constitution....
   Dukakis: If the vice president of the United States thinks that
Robert Bork was an outstanding appointment, that is a very good
reason for voting for Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen on the 8th of
November. ...
   Q: Would you commit yourself to any of those hard choices, such
as which ... entitlements ought to be redrawn?
   Dukakis: ... Why do people who want to balance budgets, or bring
the deficit down, always go to those programs which tend to benefit
people of very modest means? ... I'm not going to go to
entitlements as a means for cutting that deficit ...
   Bush: ... Let me simply say for the record, I did not vote to
cut COLAs. ... I'm going to keep the Social Security entitlement,
to keep that trust fund sound.
   Q: Governor ... originally you sought an exemption for Social
Security COLAs in this National Governors Association vote. ...
But, when you lost that vote, you, then, endorsed the over-all
freeze proposal. ...
   Dukakis: That is absolutely not true ...
   Q: ... aren't you demagoguing the Social Security issue?
   Dukakis: No ... I just have to correct the record. That simply
isn't true. ... everybody knew that those of us who voted against
the freezing of COLAs did so, we did so emphatically ...
   Q: ... How do you square your campaign rhetoric with
(environental) record?
   Bush: ... I refuse to measure one's commitment as to whether
you're going to double the spending. That is the same old argument
that'd gotten us into the trouble on the deficit side. ... I'm not
going to go down there and try to dump the sludge from
Massachussetts off the beaches off of New Jersey ... I am an
evironmentalist.
   Dukakis: ... I don't know which George Bush I'm talking about
here, or looking at -- the George Bush who was a charter member of
the environmental wrecking crew that went to Washington in the
early '80s and did a job on the EPA, or the one we've been seeing
and listening to the past two or three months. ...
   Q: ... would you agree to another debate ... ?
   Bush: No, I will not agree to another debate. The American
people are up to here with debates. ... I think we can all share
... in the fact that maybe the message is not getting out. But,
it's not getting out because they're too few debates. There will be
no more debates.
   Dukakis: ... I think if we get rid of the labels and _ I'm not
keeping count, but I think Mr. Bush has used the label ``liberal''
at least 10 times. If I had a dollar, George, for every time you
used that label, I'd qualify for one of those tax breaks for the
rich that you want to give away. ...
   Q: Is (nuclear weapons plant maintenance) a priority that you
feel has been ignored by this administration?
   Dukakis: ... What's been going on? Who's been in charge? Who's
been managing this system? Why have there been these safety
violations? ... Now, somebody has to bear the responsibility for
this ...
   Bush: That is the closest I've ever heard the governor of
Massachusetts come to support anything having to do with nuclear.
That's about as close as I've ever heard him. ... Will he join me
in suggesting that we may need another plant, maybe in Idaho, to
take care of the requirements -- nuclear material requirements for
our Defense Department. I hope he will. ...
   Q: ... If you become president, will you lock that revolving
door that has allowed some men and women in the government to come
back and lobby the very departments they once managed?
   Bush: Yes, and I'll apply it to Congress too. ... I get kidded
by being a little old fashioned on these things, but I do believe
in public service. ... I will have an ethical office in the White
House that will be under the president's personal concern. ...
   Dukakis: ... Wasn't this the Mr. Bush that supported Mr. Meese?
Called James Watt an excellent secretary of the Interior? Provided
support for some of these people ... We've had dozens, we've had
dozens and dozens of officials in this administration, who have
left under a cloud, who have left with a special prosecutor on
their arm. They've been indicted, convicted. ...
   Closing remarks:
   Dukakis: ... Our opponents say, ``Things are okay. ... '' But I
don't think we can be satisfied when we're spending $150 billion a
year in interest alone on the national debt, much of it going to
foreign bankers ... or when we have two and a half million of our
fellow citizens, a third of them veterans, who are homeless and
living on streets and in doorways in this country, or when Mr.
Bush's prescription for our economic future is another tax giveaway
to the rich. We can do better than that. ...
   Bush: ... I do have respect for my opponent, for his family, for
the justifiable pride he takes in his heritage. But we have
enormous differences. I want to hold the line on taxes and keep
this, the longest expansion in modern history, going until
everybody in America benefits. I want to invest in our children,
because I mean it when I say I want a kinder and gentler nation.
... This election is about big things, and perhaps the biggest is
world peace. And I ask you to consider the experience I have had in
working with a president who has revolutionized the situation
around the world. ... I want to build on that.
</TEXT>
