<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     10-14 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Won Debates ``Three-Zip,'' Says Bentsen</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen says Michael Dukakis ``won big'' in his final matchup with
George Bush. He says the debate score is ``three-zip,'' favor of
the Democrats.
   The Texas senator, who watched the debate on television in a
Houston hotel, is flying out to Sacramento today to introduce
Dukakis at a post-debate celebration at the California state
capitol. But he didn't wait to proclaim victory.
   He gave reporters a thumbs-up as he left his hotel after the
debate for a late-night rally nearby.
   ``Before tonight we were two-zero on the debates and now it's
three-zip and now to November 8,'' he told a Democratic crowd of
about 500 who gathered at Houston's convention center to watch
Dukakis battle Bush on a big screen television.
   ``He not only won, he won big,'' Bentsen said.
   Bentsen was introduced at the rally by Texas state treasurer Ann
Richards, the keynote speaker at the Democratic National Convention
in Atlanta. Although he didn't name her, Richards was one of those
who Bush during the debate accused of launching a dirty campaign by
besmirching his name at the Democratic convention.
   ``Well, I'm that lady from Texas with all that hair,'' she said.
``You think George's skins a little thin?''
   Richards denied Democrats did anything like the Republican
attacks that she said have tried to impugn the integrity and
patriotism of Dukakis.
   ``All I heard in Atlanta was that George Bush will not make a
good president of the United States,'' she said.
   ``And then George proved it himself by nominating Dan Quayle,''
she said.
   Bentsen, who before the debate was saying that Dukakis did not
have any more pressure on him than Bush did, credited the
Democratic nominee afterward for succeeding despite the odds.
   ``With all that pressure on him, he stood up and he delivered
and he put the Democratic party on the road to victory in
November,'' he said at the rally. ``He won because he gave honest
answers to the problems and concerns facing America.''
</TEXT>
