<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Homeless     10-14 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Scold Agencies For Ignoring Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeless groups trying to obtain surplus
government property are running up against reluctant federal
officials despite a court order stopping the sale of real estate
that otherwise might provide shelter.
   Witnesses before a congressional subcommittee testified Thursday
that efforts to gain 10 acres of surplus property in New Jersey met
with a string of refusals. They said a crisis is brewing with
``working homeless'' camping in regional parks outside the nation's
capital.
   Members of the House Government Operations subcommittee on
government activities and transportation scolded administration
officials for failing to make surplus real estate and buildings
available to the homeless and called for an investigation of the
Inter-Agency Council on the Homeless, which was set up to lead the
effort against homelessness.
   The hearing followed an order Sept. 30 by U.S. District Judge
Oliver Gasch barring the sale of surplus federal buildings covered
by the 1987 McKinney Act until Housing and Urban Development
officials determine which ones can be used for programs to help the
homeless.
   Maria Fascarinis, attorney for the National Coalition for the
Homeless, which filed the federal suit, said homelessness has
exploded around the country, with the number increasing 25 percent
to 3 million last year.
   ``While pursuing policies that cause and exacerbate
homelessness, the current administration has refused to take any
remedial action to address what is now clearly a national
catastrophe,'' Ms. Fascarinis told the subcommittee.
   Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., subcommittee chairwoman, told
General Services Agency acting administrator Richard G. Austin:
``It seems to me that your results have been awfully, awfully
small.''
   The agency has identified only 12 properties that might be used
by the homeless, and some of those have since been withdrawn by the
agencies controlling them, Austin acknowledged.
   He said 335 properties, making up 28,936 acres, are in the GSA's
excess and surplus property inventory, and since the court order
the agency has been reviewing them with HUD to determine which
might be suitable for the homeless. The order requires that HUD,
rather than agencies owning the surplus properties, determine which
might be used.
   Austin said a useable property would require available
electricity, plumbing, heating and day and night access.
   He acknowledged that some GSA officials had been
``overenthusiastic'' in turning down a homeless group's application
for the 10-acre plot in Edison, N.J., and said the issue would be
taken up again with local officials who want the property for other
uses.
   Robert Nasdor, spokesman for the Middlesex Interfaith Partners
with the Homeless, said about 90 families are being put up by the
government in motels in the Edison area at a cost of up to $2,400 a
month for room rent.
   ``The effect of living in these facilities on families is
devastating,'' Nasdor said.
   GSA has scheduled a public meeting next Tuesday in Edison to
consider proposals by the city and others for use of the property
which has been declared surplus and is under GSA jurisdiction.
   Rep. Howard Nielson, R-Utah, challenged Austin to be more
aggressive in seeking federal property for the homeless.
   Nielson said Congress, in passing the McKinney Act last year,
clearly intended that the homeless problem be given high priority.
``I would suggest that you be much more aggressive with other
agencies, put a little pressure on them to set some property
aside,'' Nielsen told Austin.
   Victoria Luna, of the Metropolitan Washington Union of the
Homeless, testified that scores of working homeless are living in
parks in Washington's Virginia suburbs. She said many are
construction workers from West Virginia, Kentucky and Ohio who make
good money but not good enough to pay the Washington area's
inflated rents.
   ``We have a crisis here. The regional parks will be closing this
month, and winter is coming,'' said Mrs. Luna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
