<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Campuses     10-14 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campuses,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Tallies Colleges And University Repair Needs: $70 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Classrooms, libraries and laboratories at the
nation's colleges and universities are deteriorating and it could
take $70 billion to shape up America's campuses, a report says.
   Schools are facing repairs not just to older buildings, but also
to newer buildings that were not as well constructed, said
consultant Sean Rush, who worked on the survey released Thursday by
two associations of school officials.
   ``We know now that the cost of modernizing and maintaining
higher education facilities is grossly misunderstood,
underestimated and underfunded,'' said Walter A. Schaw, executive
vice president of the Association of Physical Plant Administrators,
which co-sponsored the study with the National Association of
College and University Business Officers.
   Schaw said in an interview that ordinary repairs in masonry,
electrical systems, plumbing, roofing and other parts of buildings
urgently need attention on most campuses, while some schools have
outdated classrooms and laboratories that need to be replaced.
Others have buildings with serious hidden problems such as
termites, he said.
   The report, ``The Decaying American Campus: A Ticking Time
Bomb,'' was prepared by the accounting firm Coopers & Lybrand,
based on responses to a 16-page survey sent to 702 institutions.
Estimates of the total problem were extrapolated from 217 responses
to the survey.
   ``We are not allocating enough funds to properly maintain
existing structures, let alone renew the laboratories, libraries
and classrooms necessary to provide a quality education for our
young people,'' said Schaw.
   In some cases cost cutting has made problems worse, he said.
   As an example, he cited Doric columns at the University of
Maryland at College Park which for want of $8,000 worth of painting
through the years will have to be replaced at a cost of $350,000.
On the other hand, he said, the same university has paid for recent
dormitory renovation with energy-saving measures.
   ``Just like a car and house, it costs more to repair if you put
it off. The longer you wait, the worse the problem is,'' he said.
   The survey concluded that the policy of deferring expenses for
needed repairs and maintenance has led to an estimated $20 billion
backlog of urgently needed work.
   Potential need could reach between $60 billion and $70 billion,
the report said.
   Schaw said the survey estimates that, based on $100 per square
foot in replacement value, facilities on the nation's more than
3,300 institutions of higher education are worth $300 billion.
   ``The capital renewal and replacement needs of our colleges and
universities are a ticking time bomb,'' said Caspa L. Harris Jr.,
executive vice president of the business officers group. ``The
problem is here and now, and it has to be addressed.''
   The study estimates that institutions budgeted $1.2 billion for
repair and maintenance this year _ one-fourth of the need.
   It says that although the number of square feet of campus
facility space has increased by more than 50 percent since 1970,
the share of university and college budgets given to the physical
plant has remained almost constant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfShipping Bjt   10-14 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Shipping, Bjt,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoother Sailing Reported For Gulf Merchant Vessels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has not stopped and searched a
merchant ship in the Persian Gulf since its Aug. 20 cease-fire with
Iraq, shipping sources say, a sign of easing tensions in the gulf
after eight years of war.
   ``It seems peace has finally come to the waters of the gulf,''
said one official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Iranian warships have continued interrogating vessels by radio,
demanding to know their cargoes and destinations, but even those
symbolic interceptions are now down to one-third of what they were
immediately after the cease-fire took hold, said the shipping
monitors, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Both countries have reported efforts to reopen ports closed by
the Iran-Iraq war, and Iraq said about a dozen of the 18 vessels
trapped in the the ports of Umm Qasr and Khor al-Zubair since the
start of the war have been able to sail out.
   The shipping monitors said the Iranians have not harassed any
vessel in the Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the gulf, since they
claimed to have intercepted the Iraqi freighter Khawla as it
entered the waterway hours after cease-fire took effect Aug. 20.
   After docking at Umm Qasr, the freighter sailed out through
Hormuz without hindrance last month, carrying a cargo of fertilizer.
   Several Iraqi ships have sailed the gulf without interference
since the cease-fire, the official Iraqi News Agency has reported.
   Gulf-based officials of two shipping companies said their
vessels have not encountered any Iranian gunboats in recent weeks
and believe that Tehran has halted the stop-and-search
interceptions.
   Shipping officials reported that traffic in the gulf has not
noticably increased since the cease-fire, while shippers wait to
see what happens.
   During the fighting, Iranian warships and gunboats intercepted
hundreds of vessels entering the gulf through Hormuz to determine
if they were carrying war-related materiel to Iraq. Several were
seized and inspected.
   Iran's Foreign Minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, said Oct. 8 that in
an effort to break the deadlock in the peace negotiations Iran has
agreed to drop its ``right to search ships in the Strait of
Hormuz.''
   Officials at the United Nations said that was part of a
compromise proposed by U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar, who has said he expects the talks to resume in Geneva
sometime during the last week of this month.
   The earlier negotiations in Geneva and New York stalled over
Iraq's demand the Iranians halt ship searches and Iraq's insistence
the Shatt Al-Arab, which forms the southern boundary between the
two countries, be reopened.
   Iran has refused to agree to unblock the waterway, Iraq's
primary outlet to the gulf, until Baghdad concedes that a 1975
treaty drawing the border down the middle of the Shatt Al-Arab,
instead of along the eastern Iranian bank, is still valid.
   Iraqi officials have denied Baghdad has agreed in principle to a
compromise, under which troops would be withdrawn to the pre-war
border and prisoners exchanged within 15 days.
   The Iranians' recent actions have helped make the gulf, through
which one-fifth of the non-communist world's oil supplies pass, a
safer place.
   The two sides attacked nearly 550 merchant vessels in the gulf
during the so-called ``tanker war,'' killing more than 300 seamen.
   U.S., British and other Western warships still patrol the gulf.
But the Americans have halted close-in escorts of convoys of
U.S.-flagged vessels as the danger of Iranian attack has receded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
