<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     10-14 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burmese Rebels Claim Victories, Political Ranks Grow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic rebels claimed battlefield
victories and two more political parties came forward in new
challenges to the military government.
   A rebel official said Thursday that ethnic minority Karens
captured several hills the day before on the western bank of the
Moei River that separates Burma and Thailand.
   The latest fighting for the hills began Sept. 26. The Karens,
the strongest armed opponents of the Rangoon government, lost the
area in April 1984 to the Burmese army.
   Several thousand students have fled Rangoon and other cities
seeking refuge and military training from the guerrillas after a
bloody government crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrations.
   Though it has killed at least 450 persons since Gen. Saw Maung
took power Sept. 18, the government has also announced it would
hold general elections in about three months and opened a registry
of political groups.
   Two more political parties registered with the government
Thursday, bringing to 16 the number of officially recognized
groups. Most of the groups oppose the government, but none has said
if it will take part in government-sponsored general elections.
   A retired Burmese ambassador leads the newly registered
Democracy Development Organization, state-owned radio said.
   The Arakan League for Democracy also signed up Thursday. It was
the second ethnic minority group to form an official party after
the Karens announced a Union Karen League on Wednesday.
   Most of the parties are local or regional ones aimed at putting
forward candidates from their own areas.
   Only three movements have nationwide followings: the opposition
National League for Democracy; the Communist-led Democratic Front
for National Reconstruction; and the powerful and still
unregistered National Unity Party, which has wielded authoritarian
power for the past 26 years.
   New political parties have surfaced almost daily. One Western
diplomat suggested this week that the government ``may be
encouraging the formation of these groups in a divide-and-conquer
tactic.''
</TEXT>
