<HEAD>Congress Hails Discovery Astronauts for Giving America a Boost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five astronauts who flew the space shuttle
Discovery mission earlier this month have received official heroes'
welcomes and congratulations on Capitol Hill.
   Congress on Thursday also thanked the Discovery crew for the
``great feeling you have given all Americans.''
   In response, flight commander Frederick H. Hauck said the
successful four-day mission was ``tremendous testimony to a very
large team throughout the country.''
   Hauck and his crew _ pilot Richard O. Covey and mission
specialists John M. Lounge, David C. Hilmers and George D. Nelson _
were first greeted by applause from members on the floor of the
House gallery and again before space committees of the House and
Senate.
   The Discovery flight, which began on Sept. 29, was the first
shuttle mission since the shuttle Challenger blew up on liftoff,
killing all seven crew members on Jan. 28, 1986. Extensive
revisions were made in the shuttle program before the Discovery
flight.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japanese Influence from Investment Scrutinized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan clearly has become a major investor in
foreign countries but it is not clear how much this has increased
its influence in those countries, Congress was told.
   The Japanese are ``well behind'' Britain and the Netherlands as
direct investors in U.S. real estate, buildings and factories,
Deputy Assistant Secretary of State William Clark told a
Congressional panel Thursday.
   Japanese hold $31 billion worth of such investments in the
United States compared to similar U.S. investments in Japan of
about $18 billion. Clark did not have the figures for British and
Dutch investments in the United States but noted that the total of
U.S. worldwide foreign investments far exceeds those of any other
country.
   Potentially ``more worrisome'' than Japanese direct investments,
Clark said, are Japanese holdings of U.S. Treasury debt, but
``actually one looks at that as a vote of confidence in a safe
place to put your money,'' he added.
   Asked by Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-NY, chairman of the House of
Representatives Asia-Pacific subcommittee if Japan has or might use
its U.S. debt holdings for political influence, Clark replied,
``there hasn't been any movement in or out to try to influence
policy.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Organization of American States Sees Danger to Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security and democracy in the western
hemisphere will be weakened unless action is taken against the
increase in poverty, according to a report prepared for Secretary
of State George P. Shultz and other diplomatic leaders of the
Americas.
   A draft of the report from the Economic and Social Council of
the Organization of American States, made available to reporters
this week in advance of the OAS General Assembly meeting scheduled
in San Salvador on Nov. 14, blamed increased poverty on
``adjustment policies'' adopted in many countries to deal with
Latin America's $415 billion foreign debt.
   It said efforts by Latin American governments to earn hard
currency, which is needed for interest on the debt, and to reduce
government spending ``has resulted in a sudden reduction of a
series of social services which had benefited the poorest sectors,
and a dramatic reduction in public investment to ease the extreme
poverty of the region in the medium term.''
   The report saw encouragement in a recent tendency of some
financial institutions to make distinctions for the benfit of the
poorest people. It did not name the institutions. The statement may
refer to the International Monetary Fund and to the ``Paris club''
of creditor governments which have been taking measures to ease the
debt of the poorest countries.
</TEXT>
