<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Tuition     10-14 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Tuition,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Mentions Longview Couple's College Dilemma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The couple whose troubles raising college
money for their daughter were mentioned by Michael Dukakis in the
presidential debate are ``white middle-class Americans who have
been left out,'' says the mother of that 18-year-old student.
   In Thursday night's presidential debate with George Bush,
Dukakis mentioned an unnamed family ``from Longview, Texas _ two
teachers, a mother and a father who have a child that's a freshman
in college, who's an electrical engineering major, a very bright
student _ and they can't afford to keep that child in college.''
   Having been alerted by Dukakis aides that they might be
mentioned, Bea and Bill Scantlin watched and waited to be
mentioned. Daughter Tracy had the event taped because she was
pledging a sorority.
   A first-year student at Tyler Junior College, Tracy has been
told repeatedly she does not qualify for financial aid. ``My
parents made too much money to get loans,'' she said.
   ``In fact, last week she had an interview with a counselor,''
Mrs. Scantlin said. ``He told her again there was no avenue open
for the middle class.''
   ``There are scholarships available for straight-A students,''
she said. ``She's a B-plus student. We're not low income and we're
not minority. So we're going to just wing it.''
   Eventually Tracy wants to go to Texas A&M, said Mrs. Scantlin,
but ``we're saving money by going to Tyler right now.''
   She estimated that the final cost for Tracy's college education
would be about $25,000 for five years.
   She said the junior college was costing the family about $2,000
per semester, a total that Tracy's part-time job as a secretarial
assistant in the campus' police department won't do much to defray.
   ``I think it's a reflection of the disregard of the needs of the
middle class,'' Mrs. Scantlin said of her family's financial aid
dilemma. ``We found that we were not low income. We were not black,
not Hispanic. We're white middle-class Americans who have been left
out.
   ``Basically, that's what I told Gov. Dukakis because I felt
middle-income America had been callously disregarded,'' Mrs.
Scantlin said, describing the letter she wrote him two weeks ago
praising his student loan repayment program.
   The Dukakis plan that impressed Mrs. Scantlin, called the
Student Tuition and Repayment System, allows students to pay back
college loans through payroll deductions in their working years.
The plan would supplement, not replace, existing federal grants and
loans, at least at the start, Dukakis says. Students would get
STARS loans from banks.
   Bush proposes a tax-free U.S. Savings Bonds program to help
families pay soaring college costs. This would eventually cost the
Treasury $200 million a year. The tax break would be phased out for
families earning $60,000 to $80,000 or above.
   The Scantlins have three other daughters, all of them older than
Tracy. Two went to college, one with federal assistance.
</TEXT>
