<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     10-14 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Visit Postponed Because of Hirohito's Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state visit today by President Roh Tae-woo of
South Korea was postponed because of the illness of Emperor
Hirohito, officials said.
   However, the 87-year-old emperor remained in stable condition,
officials at the Imperial Palace said.
   Hirohito, the world's longest-reigning monarch, has been
bedridden since Sept. 19, when he vomited blood from internal
hemorrhaging. He has suffered since then from repeated bleeding,
and doctors have given him more than 15 pints of blood in
transfusions.
   Domestic news media have said he has cancer, but palace
officials have refused to comment on those reports.
   New media, quoting sources close to palace physicians, said
today his doctors are worried about progressing jaundice and
continued bleeding.
   The foreign ministries of Japan and South Korea announced
separately today that South Korea's president was postponing a
visit scheduled for mid-November in deference to Hirohito's
condition. Talks will be held later to reschedule the visit.
   Hirohito, who has reigned since 1926, remains a symbol of the
state, but he holds no real political power.
</TEXT>
