<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-14 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rebounds Slightly, Stocks Also Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the yen Friday,
reversing its overnight decline on overseas markets following the
release of worse-than-expected U.S. trade figures. Stock prices
gained slightly.
   The dollar closed at 128.25 yen, up 0.27 yen from Thursday's
close of 127.98 yen. After opening at 127.66 yen, the U.S. currency
moved in a range of 127.60-128.33 yen during the day's trading.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 136.07 points Thursday, closed at
27,306.57, recouping 33.27 points or 0.12 percent.
   The dollar fell at the opening in the wake of the U.S. Commerce
Department's report Thursday that the nation's trade deficit
swelled to $12.2 billion in August, compared with $9.5 billion in
July.
   The dollar's opening was its lowest in Tokyo since June 22, when
it started trading at 126.70 yen.
   But the dollar recovered after market participants covered
short-dollar positions _ the repayment of borrowed dollars that
were bought in speculation the currency would decline further _
ahead of the weekend, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   The dealer also said traders were reluctant to dump more dollars
due to fears the Bank of Japan will intervene in the market.
   The dollar has fallen a total of 5.52 yen since Tuesday and
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, speaking during a regularly
scheduled press conference, said Japanese monetary authorities
would intervene in the market whenever there are ``violent one-day
movements.''
   But traders said there had been no intervention by the Bank of
Japan so far Friday. The central bank does not publicly comment on
its activities.
</TEXT>
