<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Issues     10-14 0903</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Issues,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neither Bush Nor Dukakis Broke Any New Ground on Major Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis jousted anew
over the death penalty, Social Security, defense, environment and
the merits of Robert Bork in their final debate of the presidential
campaign.
   Neither gave ground, or broke any, on major issues.
   From Thursday night's first debate question, when Dukakis
reiterated his opposition to the death penalty, even if his wife
Kitty were raped and murdered, to the close when Bush said Dukakis
had his own sleaze to deal with in Massachusetts, both stuck
closely to their standard campaign lines.
   For the Democrat, that meant reiterating his allegation that the
only way Bush can pay for new Pentagon weapons, cutting the capital
gains tax and keeping other promises is to ``raid the Social
Security trust fund.''
   But Bush insisted he ``learned the hard way'' the political
peril of advocating any cuts or changes in Social Security, and ``I
don't want to fool around with it.''
   ``Maybe down the line ... you're going to have to look at it''
in the first or second decade of the next century, he said, but not
on his watch.
   Bush accused Dukakis of raiding his own state's pension fund for
$29 million to balance Massachusetts' 1988 budget. Dukakis denied
the charge and said he was the first governor to move to fully fund
the state's pensions. However, he did recently use that much in
surplus pension funds to help balance the state's accounts.
   On the death penalty, Dukakis said he is convinced there are
better deterrents, and he said his state of Massachusetts boasts
the biggest drop in crime and the lowest homocide rate of any
industrial state.
   But Bush said the death penalty was one of the ``questions of
values'' that separates him from Dukakis. He said capital
punishment is especially needed for cop-killers.
   On taxes, Bush denied that he was misleading the public with his
pledge never to raise taxes. ``I want to keep this expansion going.
I don't want to kill it off,'' he said.
   Dukakis accused Bush of breaking his no-tax pledge ``three times
in the past year.'' He derided Bush's flexible freeze proposal as
an ``economic slurpee,'' but refused to discuss what taxes he would
raise in a bind.
   Dukakis, who has said he would entertain tax increases only as a
last resort, claimed tougher tax collection could bring in up to
$50 billion a year from cheats and scofflaws without overburdening
honest taxpayers.
   Bush, asked to name a single military program he would scrap,
singled out an $850 million heavy truck program that he said had
been forced upon the Pentagon by an influential congressman.
   Bush again depicted Dukakis as a liberal and said ``he ran on
the left in the Democratic primary.'' He also charged the Democrats
started the mud-slinging with their ``personal attacks on me'' at
the Democratic convention.
   Dukakis said he would not rule out modernizing the U.S.
land-based missiles. But he defended his opposition to the
Strategic Defense Initiative and the mobile MX missile. ``There are
limits to what we can spend,'' he said.
   Asked about his links to a Boston group, ``Jobs with Peace,''
that supposedly favors shifting 25 percent of the military budget
to domestic programs, Dukakis at first said ``I don't happen to
share that goal,'' but then added that down the road, after
negotiations with the Soviets, it may be possible to reduce
military outlays.
   Bush defended his support of a Constitutional amendment to
outlaw nearly all abortions, saying adoption, not abortion, is the
alternative for mothers of handicapped children. Dukakis said the
woman ``in the exercise of her own conscience'' should make that
decision.
   Asked if he had a litmus test for who he would appoint to the
Supreme Court, Bush said he would not appoint judges who would
``legislate'' or give the high court a liberal majority. When he
praised President Reagan's appointees as outstanding, Dukakis cited
Robert Bork, the controversial jurist whom the Senate rejected last
fall.
   Bush accused Dukakis of supporting ``supply maintenance or
production controls'' on farmers, and implied Dukakis might impose
a grain embargo on the Soviets as Jimmy Carter once did. Dukakis
said he opposed both that grain embargo and the Reagan
administration's pipeline embargo, and he said the government
already has supply management in the form of crop set-asides.
   Dukakis denied that he regards stronger conventional military
forces as a substitute for the nuclear triad of land-sea-and-air
missiles.
   Asked about the serious production problems at the nucler
weapons plant in Savannah River, S.C., Dukakis said it was
``another example of misplaced priorities'' under the Reagan
administration. It could cost $25 billion to $100 billion to remedy
and ``somebody has to bear the responsibility for this,'' he said.
   Bush shot back that that was the closest Dukakis had ever come
to supporting anything nuclear. He challenged the Democrat to
support construction of a second weapons plant in Idaho, and to
back civilian nuclear generating plants.
   On the so-called ``sleaze'' factor in the Reagan administration,
Bush said Dukakis' own former education secretary is in jail in
Massachusetts on corruption charges, and some scandal-plagued
college presidents ``aren't exactly holier than thou.'' He said
ethics in government isn't a partisan issue, and he promised to
seek tougher laws for both the executive and legislative branches.
</TEXT>
