<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Algeria     10-14 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Algeria,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Country Recovering From Riots, But Fundamentalist Group Promises
More Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shop owners covered shattered windows
with plywood and schools prepared to reopen Saturday as calm
settled on Algeria after a week of bloody rioting.
   Armored vehicles remained on guard at major points throughout
the capital, but other military personnel were pulled off the
streets Thursday to signal the end of a six-day state of emergency
called after unrest left hundreds dead and injured.
   But Islamic fundamentalists, who attempted to gain control of
the riots that began Oct. 4 against a government austerity program,
warned Thursday that demonstrations will resume following prayers
today, the Moslem holy day.
   The government announced schools will re-open Saturday after
having been closed a week. Soccer matches, a popular sport with
Algerian youth, were to resume next week after a two-week
suspension, officials said.
   Government offices, national organizations and state-owned
shops, which suffered heavy damage during the violence, began to
re-open. Some stores, where plywood replaced shattered windows, let
small groups of shoppers in.
   Basic food and consumer goods, previously scarce, re-appeared in
Algerian stores and lines for bread disappeared. People wheeled
home sacks of semolina, recently unobtainable except through the
black market and used to make the North African staple of couscous.
   Butter re-appeared at the subsidized price of about $1.95 a
pound, much lower than its regular price before the revolt.
   The return to near-normalcy followed a quick response by
President Chadli Bendjedid to the demands of youthful rioters
protesting the shortage of goods, the high cost of living and a
government austerity plan.
   On Wednesday, Bendjedid announced Algerians will be asked to
vote Nov. 3 in a referendum to make the prime minister responsible
to the People's National Assembly, Algeria's parliament.
   The president said a second referendum would be held at an
unnamed date on additional political changes ``with a view to
greater democratization of political action'' in Algeria. No
details were provided.
   Bendjedid's proposals were the subject of lively debate
Thursday, with many people saying such reforms would not solve
Algeria's profound economic problems. Others welcomed the proposed
reforms as a chance for Algerians to participate more directly in
the government.
   In a related development, Amnesty International on Thursday
urged Bendjedid to launch an inquiry into the shooting by security
forces of unarmed demonstrators.
   The London-based human rights group said the number of people
killed during the clashes, including children, far exceeded the 176
dead officially listed by the government.
   While no final official total has been released on the number of
deaths, most of which were blamed on inexperienced soldiers firing
into crowds, doctors and police sources say there were about 500
deaths.
   In Paris, exiled Algerian opposition leader Ahmed Ben Bella
estimated 1,000 people have died. Ben Bella, first president of
independent Algeria, was ousted in a 1965 coup.
   Miloud Brahimi, president of Algeria's Human Rights League,
asked the government to release 3,000 demonstrators and agitators
rounded up during the riots who remain in temporary detention
centers.
</TEXT>
