<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ShroudofTurin     10-14 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shroud of Turin,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Scientist Says Some Will Still Believe In Shroud of Turin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the scientists who determined the Shroud of
Turin is not Christ's burial cloth predicted there will still be
believers. Church officials said the cloth remains a symbol of
faith.
   Cardinal Anastasio Ballestrero announced in Turin on Thursday
that he accepted the results of radiocarbon-dating tests by three
laboratories that determined the shroud was made between 1260 and
1390, not at Christ's death in about 33 A.D.
   What remains a mystery is how the shroud came to bear the image
of what scientists have called a real human form of a whipped and
crucified man.
   Professor Edward Hall, who directed the tests at Oxford
University, called the cloth a forgery.
   ``All we were doing was simply dating it and once you've dated
it you know that it's a forgery,'' he told a news conference
Thursday. ``Undoubtedly there will be some people who will fight
for its genuine nature still, as indeed there are still members of
the Flat Earth Society.''
   Luigi Gonella, scientific adviser to the cardinal, said the
church was particularly angered by claims that since the shroud
dates to medieval times it must be a fake.
   ``Believers will be hurt much more by the comments about the
results than by the results themselves,'' Gonella said.
   ``A forgery means it was made for the specific purpose of
deceiving people. This is possible but there is no proof of that,''
he said. ``It could be a medieval icon. We don't even know how it
was made.''
   Ballestrero stressed that for the Roman Catholic church, the
linen cloth remains a venerated object and a powerful symbol of
faith.
   ``The church believes in the image and not in the history,
because this image of Jesus Christ is very interesting and the
people believe very much in Jesus,'' he told a news conference at
the headquarters of his archdiocese.
   The sheet _ 14 feet, 3 inches long and 3 feet, 7 inches wide _
bears a faint, yellowish negative image of the front and back of a
man with a thorn mark on the head, lacerations from flogging on the
back, and bruises on the shoulders.
   U.S. scientists who subjected it to rigorous chemical, computer
and photographic analysis in 1981 concluded that it was ``a real
human form of a whipped and crucified man and not the product of an
artist.''
</TEXT>
