<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Tyson'sFather     10-14 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Tyson's Father,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estranged Father Wants To See Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Kirkpatrick says he is hoping his son,
world heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson, will agree to see him
for the first time in seven years so that he can ``explain about
me.''
   Kirkpatrick, 64, who lives in a Brooklyn housing project with
his wife and three adopted children, said in today's New York Post
that he left Tyson's mother, Lorna Tyson, about 20 years ago, after
he had a heart attack.
   ``When I went into the hospital, things changed,'' he said. ``I
wasn't able to support them. I wasn't able to do the things I
should've. And I couldn't marry her. ... All I remember about Mike
then was that he was a husky baby.''
   He admits that he ``was a little wild back then,'' but says he
became a born-again Christian eight years ago.
   Kirkpatrick says he hasn't seen Tyson, now 22, since his mother
died in 1981.
   ``I'm not going to Mike with my hands out,'' he said. ``I don't
want Mike's money. ... It's not that I wouldn't take it, that I
couldn't use it. But I'd take it only if Mike wanted to give it
out.''
