<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0503 10-14 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Bush Camp Rejoices in the Debate Reviews</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf to correct ABC poll results; First event is
rally in Cerritos at 3:30 p.m. EDT. Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A buoyant Republican George Bush says he's
ready for ``the home stretch'' after a debate performance his camp
is rating as a decisive win.
   ``The vice president cleaned his (Dukakis') clock,'' declared
Bush's campaign chairman, James A. Baker III.
   ``You hit it out of the park,'' running mate Sen. Dan Quayle
told Bush by phone.
   The Republican presidential nominee was more restrained in
words, telling reporters only ``I'm happy with the way it came
out.''
   But that restraint did not extend to gestures as he grinned
broadly and repeatedly poked the air with a double thumbs-up as he
boarded his motorcade to leave the debate site at the University of
California at Los Angeles Thursday night.
   ``I feel good about it,'' Bush added.
   His aides rejoiced in the generally favorable reviews Bush's
second debate had received, including a quick ABC poll that showed
Americans who were surveyed thought he had won by a 49-33 margin. A
Los Angeles Times poll gave Bush the win, 47-27.
   Bush told more than 3,000 cheering supporters at a post-debate
rally: ``Tomorrow, we start the home stretch of this campaign ...
And I believe we can do anything we set our sights on.''
   For the next few days, at least, the campaign's sights will stay
on California _ with its harvest of 47 electoral votes and where
the race is viewed as especially close by both sides.
   Bush was to speak at a mid-day rally in the Los Angeles suburb
of Cerritos, then fly to San Diego for a speech at the University
of California's Scripps Institute.
   On Saturday, he will visit a string of agricultural communities
in the state's Central Valley, a bus motorcade campaign that will
take him to Stockton, Modesto, Merced and Fresno.
   At Thursday's post-debate rally at Loyola Marymount University,
Bush vowed to ``work hard and win'' in California.
   And he asserted that, with a California victory, ``I will be the
next president of the United States.''
   Bush did not comment on his debate performance at the rally,
other than to note that it gave him more of a chance to discuss
``world peace'' issues than did the first debate and to say that he
had continued to stress differences with his opponent.
   However, California Gov. George Deukmejian introduced Bush as
``the heavyweight debate champion of the world.''
   The audience, which included entertainer Zsa Zsa Gabor, actors
Chuck Norris, Jaime Farr, Gabe Kaplan, singer Andy Williams and
tennis player Tracy Austin, roared its support for Bush and saluted
him with a blizzard of confetti.
   Shortly after the debate, Bush received phone calls from both
Quayle and President Reagan, according to Bush spokeswoman Sheila
Tate.
   Reagan told Bush ``you done good,'' Ms. Tate said.
   Baker, Bush's campaign chairman, said Bush came across as
presidential, in control, relaxed and likable in the debate.
   ``It's a clear win for the vice president,'' Baker said. ``The
bottom line is he reinforced his position with voters already
committed to him and he closed the sale with those undecided.''
   Dukakis, by contrast, ``projected a pessimistic view of the
future of this country,'' Baker said.
   As in the first presidential debate, the Bush campaign was quick
to parade officials _ such as Baker _ before reporters to put a
positive ``spin'' on their candidate's performance, just as the
Dukakis camp was doing.
   Former Deputy Treasury Secretary Richard Darman, another member
of the Bush spin patrol, said that ``on the issue of personality,
on the question of likability, he (Dukakis) didn't help himself and
probably, he hurt himself.''
   ``We're very encouraged,'' Darman said.
</TEXT>
