<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SecretClient     10-14 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Secret Client,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Lawyer Doesn't Have To Release Name Of Hit-And-Run
Driver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for parents of a man
killed in a hit-and-run accident said there is a ``fleeing felon
out there who is laughing'' because a judge refused to force the
driver's attorney to reveal his client's identity.
   Palm Beach Circuit Judge Timothy Poulton on Thursday denied a
motion to force defense attorney Barry Krischer to give the name of
his client on grounds the attorney-client privilege of
confidentiality blocked the disclosure.
   ``The plaintiffs' case has tremendous emotional appeal and it is
difficult to rule against the plaintiffs,'' Poulton said, who
delivered the ruling after weeks of review. ``But I am convinced
the law requires it.''
   Joseph Farish Jr., an attorney for the parents of Mark Baltes,
described the driver as a cat with ``feathers hanging off his
mouth'' following the ruling.
   ``I respect (the judge's) decision,'' Farish said, but he
maintained the attorney-client privilege of confidentiality was
abused when the judge denied his motion to have the driver's
identity revealed.
   ``We have a fleeing felon out there who is laughing at all of
us,'' Farish said.
   The victim's mother, Mildred Baltes, said the family ``will
appeal if we have to to the Supreme Court.''
   ``I feel I must do it, not only for my son, but for victims and
families of victims in the future,'' she said.
   Krischer was approached by the driver the day after the March 9,
1986, accident and was asked to seek a plea bargain arrangement
without revealing his client's name.
   No deal was struck with prosecutors and Baltes' parents, Mildred
and her ex-husband Joseph, filed a $6 million wrongful death civil
suit in February against the unknown driver.
   ``The public has gained from this litigation a greater insight
into, and appreciation of, the importance of the attorney-client
privilege,'' Krischer said on Thursday.
   ``The public can be assured that they can meet with an attorney
and confide in him openly and frankly without fear that their
conversations will be repeated in open court.''
   According to police, Baltes, a 28-year-old electrician, was
intoxicated and quarreled with his fiancee as she drove home from a
night out. Baltes got out of the car and staggered down the road,
and was hit by a car and dragged nearly 60 feet.
   He was pronounced dead at the scene.
   Detectives, using car fragments at the scene and paint chips
found on Baltes' skull, theorized the vehicle was a 1984 or 1985
white Buick Riviera. But hundreds of police interviews and a reward
failed to yield any firm suspects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
