<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SKorea-USProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0513 10-14 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-US Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Attack U.S. Cultural Center In Kwangju</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with additional injuries,
comment from U.S. embassy, other details; picks up 9th pvs: In
recent...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students shouting ``Drive out
Yankees'' firebombed a police bus today and wounded 13 officers in
an attack on a U.S. government office in the southern city of
Kwangju, police and U.S. officials said.
   Two of the wounded officers were hurt seriously during the
attack near the U.S. Information Service building in downtown
Kwangju, the U.S. Embassy said in a statement. Police said four
students were arrested.
   The embassy statement said fighting broke out in the
mid-afternoon when about 100 protesters began hurling firebombs at
the building, hitting the police bus which had about 30 people
aboard.
   There were no injuries in the center, but a car inside the
compound was destroyed by fire and another was slightly damaged,
the statement said. About 10 windows at the center's library also
were damaged, it said.
   U.S. Embassy officials said seven assailants scaled the center's
roof from inns nearby while police outside fought back protesters.
   ``From there, they hurled Molotov cocktails, steel pipes and
tiles which they ripped from the center roof,'' the officials said.
The protesters also wielded stones.
   The students on the roof also carried a placard that read
``Repeal armistice agreement, conclude peace treaty,'' according to
Yonhap, the South Korean news agency. South Korea and North Korea
fought a bloody war in 1950-53, and both sides technically are
still at war, with no peace treaty signed.
   In leaflets and slogans, Yonhap said the students strongly
denounced the United States and demanded the arrest of former
President Chun Doo-hwan.
   On Thursday, hundreds of students staged scattered protests in
downtown Kwangju when police blocked the protesters from
approaching the Information Service after they firebombed a local
chapter of the governing Democratic Justice Party.
   The U.S. Information Center in Kwangju has been the target of
frequent attacks by radical students, who demand the withdrawal of
U.S. forces stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
Radicals contend the United States enforced division of the Korean
peninsula.
   In recent weeks, dissidents and radical students have stepped up
an anti-U.S. campaign and called for punishment of the former
president and his family for alleged corruption and brutality.
   Chun has been under parliamentary investigations since he left
office in February at the end of a seven-year term.
   Also today, about 300 students battled riot police after burning
effigies of President Reagan and South Korean President Roh Tae-woo
at Hankook University of Foreign Studies in eastern Seoul.
   The students in Seoul called for removal of U.S. influence on
the Korean peninsula and pelted riot police with scores of
firebombs and rocks. Police responded with barrages of tear gas.
   Several students were seen bleeding in clashes along the gate of
the school, but it was not known immediately how many people were
injured or arrested.
</TEXT>
