<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--ArchofTriumph     10-14 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Arch of Triumph,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parisian Monument To Close For Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arch of Triumph, the French capital's beloved
monument on the famous Champs Elysees, will be closed for two
months of repairs beginning Monday, officials said today.
   Work on the Arc de Triomphe already is under way to repair
damage from water and pollution. The arch is to be closed to permit
work on its foundation, and it will reopen to the public Dec. 15,
officials said.
   The $5.6 million project is paid for by the government and by
private contributions.
   The arch, 164 feet by 148 feet, is one of Paris' most famous
landmarks and was commissioned in 1806 by the Emperor Napoleon to
commemorate his military victories. The tomb of the unknown soldier
lies beneath it.
</TEXT>
