<DOCNO> AP881014-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Farms     10-14 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Farms,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Centrally Planned Collective Farms to be Leased Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced that
government collective farms will be leased to private individuals
to expand production and curtail massive subsidies.
   Gorbachev said late Thursday that the Soviet leadership will
extend ``to the whole of agriculture'' an experiment that leased
collective farmland to small groups and families who choose their
own crops and keep most of the profits.
   The nation needs ``solid, dependable results, already in the
near future'' for the food supply problem to be eliminated, not
just blunted, he said.
   For decades, the large collective and state farms have been run
like factories, with detailed orders from Moscow on what and when
to plant handed down to the workers on the fields.
   ``We have made them from masters of their land into day
laborers,'' Gorbachev complained in his speech.
   He said farmers must be restored as ``complete masters'' of the
land and paid only for what they can produce to ease the Soviet
Union's decades-long food shortages.
   The Soviet leader's speech to a partial session Wednesday of the
Central Committee and farmers was the first broadcast of any such
meeting. It was edited and broadcast a day late.
   The move was another step to dismantle a 50-year-old system of
centrally controlled farming. Gorbachev did not say if collective
and state farms would be eliminated, but said the continuing
practice of paying them ``unearned money'' was hindering the
leasing program.
   Gorbachev said farm leasing is critical because it offers solid
improvements in productivity.
   By contrast, the Soviet Union has poured much money into
collective and state farms in the past 20 years, with only a
minimal level of production. Capital investment rose 140 percent
during that time but production rose just 41 percent, Gorbachev
said.
   The newspaper Pravda said on the day of the conference that
Soviet agriculture now wastes nearly $100 billion a year.
   Gorbachev, who is also head of the Communist Party, said further
``far-reaching plans'' will be considered at a special meeting on
agriculture to be held by the party's policy-making Central
Committee in February. A new land-use law is being prepared.
   Notably absent from the meeting Wednesday was Yegor Ligachev.
The former ideology chief was bumped to head agriculture in a
Kremlin shake-up two weeks ago in what was widely seen as a
demotion.
   Asked about Ligachev's absence at a news briefing, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said Ligachev was on vacation
_ for how long, he did not know.
   ``But that does not mean that when Comrade Ligachev is on leave,
we should not handle agriculture issues,'' Gerasimov said. The
official news agency Tass carried Gerasimov's reply as a separate
story.
   Gorbachev also admitted that he underestimated the difficulties
involved in his drive for perestroika, or restructuring.
   ``We should honestly admit to ourselves that when launching
perestroika, we did not apparently realize all that it entails.''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
