<DOCNO> AP881014-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan     10-14 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Funded Airlift Begins Relief Flights in Sudan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relief groups have begun flying tons of
U.S.-funded food and medicine into southern towns where thousands
of war refugees, some with no food at all, face starvation,
officials said.
   U.S. officials say anti-government rebels have in the past
attacked civilian planes and truck convoys bringing such supplies.
However, government and U.S. officials hinted that guerrillas had
agreed to let the material pass without interference.
   Asked if organizers of the airlift, which began Thursday, had
contacted the People's Liberation Army about safe conduct for the
flights, a U.N. official said: ``We'd rather not comment on the
issue.''
   When reminded that rebels threatened three weeks ago to shoot
any plane flying in the south, the U.N. official said on condition
of anonymity: ``That was another time. Now it is something else.''
   The government has also resisted past efforts to send supplies
into rebel-held areas. However, it agreed after a meeting between
Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi and U.S. officials.
   The U.N. official said this airlift aimed to send 12 planes
daily with supplies to the towns of Mairam, Kadugli, Muglad and
Abyei, where food was reported to have run out Wednesday.
   ``The situation in Abyei is very bad. It's now the rainy season,
and the airport is only a strip of sand and stones. We don't give a
time limit, but we would like to carry out the relief operation as
quickly as possible,'' the U.N. official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told The Associated Press.
   The operation is paid for by the U.S. Agency for International
Development, and it also involves U.N. and private relief groups.
   Abyei's population of 10,000 shot up to 40,000 as people in
rural areas fled the fierce fighting to the town's relative safety.
   An AP reporter saw a government report covering the last few
months, which indicates that dozens of people in Abyei have been
dying each week.
   The southern revolt began five years ago, with the mainly
Christian and animist rebels demanding autonomy and administrative
and economic reforms from the Moslem-dominated government in the
north.
   The rebels claim to control 90 percent of the southern
countryside. Fighting has forced more than 820,000 southerners to
flee to army protection in southern towns, northern cities and also
into neighboring Ethiopia.
   The new airlift is the first major foreign civilian relief
effort in two years, since Operation Rainbow, a problem-plagued
U.N. program that finally got off the ground in October 1986.
   A major stumbling block to those efforts was a threat from the
rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army to shoot down relief planes,
claiming the government would use them for military purposes. More
than 70 people died when rebel gunners shot down two planes at that
time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
