<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-14 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catfish have won the battle of Hyatt Lake,
and one fisherman wants to call out the National Guard.
   After hauling an estimated 32,000 catfish out of the lake,
volunteers on Thursday gave up their plan to use traps and nets to
purge the southwest Oregon lake of the pesky fish.
   ``We just don't have the manpower,'' said Medford angler Jim
Summers. ``We need the National Guard for this.''
   Biologists had warned Summers and others their effort would be
an exercise in futility. But the volunteers said they wanted to do
what they could to reduce the booming brown bullhead catfish
population in the lake about 20 miles east of Ashland.
   Earlier this year, local opposition caused the state Fish and
Wildlife Commission to back off a plan to treat the lake with
poison.
   Summers and several other poison opponents said they would haul
the fish out of the lake themselves using live traps and seine nets.
   The volunteers decided to rethink their plans after working 16
hours Wednesday hauling 5 tons of catfish out of the lake, Summers
said.
   The fish were hauled into the woods by the pickup truckload and
buried, said state fishery biologist Al Smith.
   Smith estimated there are 7.5 million catfish in the lake, so
many that the fish's growth has been stunted, they are feeding on
their young and are crowding out most other fish.
   ``I'm not ready to admit defeat, but I am ready to apologize to
the department,'' said Jim Ross, a Medford angler who joined the
effort. ``They told me it wouldn't work, and I said it would.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKARCHE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beau Mueggenborg, 2, is looking forward to
a parade here Saturday _ but not because he's the grand marshal.
   ``He knows he gets to ride in a convertible in a parade,'' band
booster Regina Alig said Thursday. ``I don't know that he knows he
is being honored.''
   The elementary school teacher said she and other band boosters
had been trying to decide what older, prominent resident should
serve as grand marshal when someone suggested Beau.
   The boy has battled leukemia, and everyone in this town of about
1,000 people northwest of Oklahoma City knows of Beau because of
efforts to raise money for him. The blood cancer has been in
remission for a year.
   The parade down Oklahoma Avenue will consist of three or four
floats, a high school band and an elementary school band. Most of
the children in town will be in costume or ride decorated bicycles
in the event.
   With Beau in the convertible will be his parents, twin sister
and 6-year-old sister.
   The fun doesn't stop there. A carnival to raise money for the
bands will follow.
</TEXT>
