<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeamstersCases     10-14 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters Cases,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mob Figure Sued in Teamsters Case; Jury Selection in Ohio Union
Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal attorneys have filed a civil
racketeering lawsuit against alleged Mafia boss Vincent ``Chin''
Gigante, accusing him of controlling Teamsters Local 560 through
mob lieutenants.
   The lawsuit, filed Thursday, also names a trucking company and a
lawyer who worked for members of the 8,500-member local, which has
been placed under a trustee by a federal judge.
   It was the first time that Gigante has been targeted by the
government regarding corruption in Local 560.
   However, many of the allegations of control by the Genovese
crime family have surfaced before in the government's legal battle
to wrest control of the union and during recent efforts to stop
previously barred Local 560 officials from regaining office in
elections this fall.
   Earlier this year, an indictment was brought against seven
reputed family members and associates in a business-takeover scheme.
   Another indictment charged trucking company figure Francis J.
Walsh Jr. and other reputed crime family members of arranging a
``sweetheart'' labor deal with officials of the Union City-based
union. Walsh, of Saddle River, has denied the charges.
   The court papers filed Thursday cite the same alleged scheme
involving Walsh as a reason to take action against Gigante.
   ``What we hope is to get an injunction against (Gigante's)
involvement with 560, which the Genovese family has controlled
since the early 1960s,'' said U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr.
   The government is seeking to have Gigante barred from directly
or indirectly influencing the affairs of Local 560 or any union.
   Gigante, 60, of Old Tappan could not be reached for comment.
There was no telephone listing under his name and federal
authorities did not know who his attorney was.
   In Cleveland, where a Teamsters international vice president and
a local union official are facing trial, jury selection paused
while a federal judge took up several pre-trial motions.
   The defense has asked Judge George W. White to admit as evidence
statements made in 1985 by two former Cleveland FBI agents.
   The jury selection process begun Wednesday is expected to last
into next week.
   Harold Friedman, 66, is charged with two counts of labor
racketeering, two of embezzlement and two of making false
statements to the Labor Department.
   Friedman is president of the 5,000-member Teamsters Local 507,
an international vice president of the union since 1983, president
of the Ohio Conference of Teamsters and president of Teamsters
Joint Council 41 in northeast Ohio. He also is president of Bakery
Workers Local 19 in Cleveland.
   Co-defendant Anthony Hughes, 52, Local 507's recording
secretary, is charged with two counts of labor racketeering and one
count of embezzlement.
   Until recently, both Friedman and Hughes were overshadowed by
the defense of Jackie Presser, Teamsters president from 1983 until
he died of brain cancer on July 9. Presser was also indicted on
charges of labor racketeering and embezzlement.
   Federal prosecutors have alleged Presser, as secretary-treasurer
of Local 507, masterminded a $700,000 embezzlement scheme.
</TEXT>
