<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 10-14 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0541,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says It Will Make Changes In Austerity Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with easing of austerity program. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced plans to
ease an unpopular austerity program, newspapers reported today, as
leaders tried to battle runaway inflation and to quell social
unrest.
   Over the past several months, street protesters and strikers
have demanded an overhaul of the ruling party hierarchy, and
earlier this month they forced out leaders of Vojvodina, one of the
nation's two autonomous provinces.
   Changes in the program include wage increases for workers in
profitable companies and more funding for hard-pressed social
services, such as health and education. The changes were announced
Thursday by the federal government, Belgrade's state-run dailies
said.
   Austerity measures imposed in May to curb a $21 billion foreign
debt and annual inflation of 217 percent, resulted in hefty wage
cuts and substantial price increases. The changes will be adopted
by Yugoslavia's Parliament by the end of October, the reports said.
   In the first nine months of this year, salaries in Yugoslavia
fell by 25 percent in real terms. They have reached the level of
the mid-1960s in comparative purchasing power, official estimates
say.
   Belgrade newspapers said that the International Monetary Fund
had approved the government's proposed amendments. They gave no
details.
   Today's reports also failed to give the exact increase in
salaries, which now average $100 a month in Yugoslavia.
   Adoption of the unpopular austerity program was a precondition
set by the monetary fund and other Western creditors for
rescheduling payments on Yugoslavia's foreign debt and obtaining
new credits.
   The policy switch follows a government announcement last weekend
of emergency imports to alleviate shortages.
   Worker protests and strikes increased markedly after the May
program took effect, prompting angry crowds to march into
Parliament in July to protest low wages.
   The national Communist Party, under pressure to respond to the
unrest with more effective leadership, has announced plans to make
a series of personnel changes at a meeting of its policy-setting
Central Committee on Monday.
   Party leaders in the troubled province of Kosovo and the poor
southern republic of Montenegro, where major anti-government
protests broke out last weekend, met today to consider their own
personnel changes, the state news agency Tanjug said.
   Kosovo, an autonomous province in Yugoslavia's largest republic
of Serbia, is wrought with tension between the ethnic Albanian
majority, who make up 90 percent of its 2 million people, and a
Slav minority that complains that daily harassment by the Albanians
is driving them out of the region.
   Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian Communist party leader, has
spearheaded a Serbian drive for more control over Kosovo and
Serbia's other nominally autonomous province, Vojvodina.
   His push, backed by mass rallies in recent weeks, has launched a
power struggle between Serbia and Communist leaders of Yugoslavia's
other five republics, particularly the northern industrial regions
of Slovenia and Croatia.
   The split broke into the open Thursday when Milosevic clashed
for the first time publicly with national Communist party chief
Stipe Suvar.
   Suvar accused Serbian leaders of not doing enough to stop
attacks by Serbian intellectuals on the late Josip Broz Tito, who
ruled without challenge for 35 years until his death in 1980.
   Milosevic retorted that Serbia had been among the first to
condemn the attacks on Tito, whose legacy is officially sacrosanct
in the party.
   Milosevic's opponents contend he is trying to amend the current
Yugoslav constitution, bequeathed by Tito, in order to gain more
power for Serbia.
</TEXT>
