<DOCNO> AP881014-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSOrigins     10-14 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Origins,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recent Tests Confirm 1968 AIDS-Like Virus Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent laboratory tests on thawed-out tissue
samples taken from a youth who died almost two decades ago confirm
that he was infected with a virus closely related to or identical
with the AIDS virus, a report today said.
   The authors of the report, which appeared in the Journal of the
American Medical Association, said their findings suggest that a
virus related to the AIDS-causing human immunodeficiency virus, or
HIV, was introduced to the United States on at least one occasion
before the late 1970s.
   ``The findings raise important implications about the evolution
of the AIDS epidemic in the United States,'' said the report,
written by Dr. Robert F. Garry of the Tulane University School of
Medicine in New Orleans and colleagues.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome was first clinically
diagnosed in the United States in the early 1980s.
   It has been suggested by researchers that the AIDS virus was
imported from Africa to the Caribbean, and from there to the United
States in the late 1970s.
   However, the report said the issue of when HIV was introduced
into the high-risk populations of homosexuals, intravenous drug
users and hemophiliacs in the United States remains unresolved.
   Its authors raise the possibility that a virus related to HIV
may have been present in the United States, Africa, or elsewhere
for several decades.
   The researchers based their conclusions on the case history of a
15-year-old sexually active black youth who was admitted to St.
Louis City Hospital in 1968. He died after being treated for 16
months.
   There have been been previously published reports in the
scientific and popular press about the case because the youth
exhibited several symptoms characteristic of AIDS.
   Using recently developed laboratory tests for the presence of
antibodies specific to HIV, Garry and his colleagues examined serum
and autopsy specimens from the youth, which were frozen in 1969.
   ``It appears likely that the patient from 1968 was infected with
a virus closely related or identical to strains of HIV-1 that are
currently in the United States,'' the report said, citing the test
results.
   HIV-1 is the most prevalent strain of the AIDS virus in the
United States and other countries. A newly isolated type of the
virus, HIV-2, has been found in people living in western Africa.
   ``What is suggested with this new finding is that the virus has
been around a long time,'' said one of the report's co-authors, Dr.
Marlys H. Witte of the University of Arizona College of Medicine,
who helped treat the patient at the St. Louis hospital.
   The authors suggest the AIDS virus may have been present in the
United States and elsewhere for several decades, but the current
epidemic may be the result of genetic changes in the virus or
sociocultural factors involving sexual practices or the number of
sexual partners.
   They said more detailed tests on the autopsy specimens of the
St. Louis teen-ager are needed to compare the virus from the late
1960s with today's HIV strains.
   AIDS destroys the body's defenses against disease, leaving a
person prey to life-threatening infections and certain cancers.
There is no known cure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0907EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cable     10-14 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cable,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Local Franchise Fee Is Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's ruling that a franchise
fee assessed by the city against a cable television company is
unconstitutional is a victory for freedom of the press, the
company's lawyer said.
   Such a fee ``puts the government too much in control of the
press,'' Harold Farrow, lawyer for Century Federal, said Thursday.
   U.S. District Judge Eugene Lynch, in a decision issued
Wednesday, declared that the franchise fee charged by the city of
Palo Alto discriminated against cable operators in violation of
constitutional guarantees of freedom of expression.
   The city argued that the fee, 5 percent of a company's gross
revenue, was justified as rent for use of the city's right-of-way
to place cables.
   Lynch said Pacific Bell, which uses the same right-of-way for
its telephone lines, is not charged any fee as its access is
guaranteed by state law. Pacific Gas & Electric Co. is charged only
a 2 percent fee for use of a public right-of-way by the neighboring
city of Atherton, also a defendant in the cable case.
   The 5 percent fee ``is aimed exclusively at cable television
operators engaged in speech protected by the First Amendment,''
Lynch said.
   The judge said the city's legitimate goal of raising money could
have been met by a non-discriminatory fee.
   Jerome Falk, a lawyer for Palo Alto and several neighboring
communities that joined in assessing the franchise fee, said he
believed the ruling was the first in the country in which a
franchise fee was held to be ``straightforwardly and without any
question unconstitutional.'' A federal appeals court in
Philadelphia had ruled to the contrary, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
