<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Palestinian, Wound Five in Clashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with one Palestinian killed, general
strike, five wounded. CHANGES byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Uprising, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike called by leaders of the
Palestinian uprising paralyzed the occupied lands today, and Arab
reports said Israeli troops killed one Palestinian and wounded five
in several clashes.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In the West Bank village of Biddya, soldiers today destroyed
five houses and sealed a sixth, the army said.
   The houses belonged to Palestinians arrested in the Oct. 6
shooting death of a village leader who allegedly collaborated with
Israeli authorities.
   In leaflets distrubuted in Nablus, the West Bank's largest city,
the mainstream PLO faction Fatah claimed responsibility for three
slayings of alleged collaborators last month in Nablus and
threatened more such slayings.
   Thousands of people in Nablus gathered in front of homes
demolished by the army two days earlier to punish Palestinians that
authorities accused of killing the three victims, Arab witnesses
said.
   Dozens of masked youths threw rocks and bottles at soldiers, and
troops responded with live ammunition, Arab witnesses said. Three
Palestinians, ages 16, 17 and 21, were shot in their legs, said
officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad Hospital.
   In the West Bank village of Kfar Malik, a 22-year-old Arab was
fatally shot in the stomach when troops raiding the village opened
fire on stone-throwing protesters, hospital officials said. A
16-year-old was wounded in the incident, said the officials,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The fatality brought to 297 the number of Palestinians killed in
the 10-month-old uprising against Israeli rule in lands seized from
Egypt and Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War. Six Israelis also
have died in the unrest.
   In Gaza City, a 22-year-old man was shot in the right thigh with
a plastic bullet after soldiers were stoned, said Arab reports and
hospital officials.
   The army said it was checking each report.
   The army placed curfews on villages, refugee camps and
neighborhoods in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, confining 130,000
Palestinians to their homes.
   Throughout the occupied territories, most businesses were closed
and cars carrying Arab workers to jobs in Israel were stoned.
