<HEAD>Fraternity Becomes First Black Group On Ole Miss Fraternity Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the University of Mississippi's
all-black Phi Beta Sigma fraternity, whose first attempt at moving
onto Fraternity Row was met with arson, have moved into new
quarters on the previously all-white street.
   With the assistance of about 30 members of white fraternities
with houses already on Fraternity Row, Phi Beta Sigma members moved
furniture into the recently renovated house Thursday.
   ``We didn't expect anything like this,'' said Julius Harris, Phi
Beta Sigma's Ole Miss chapter president. ``We are just elated over
our new house. This is a step forward for race relations and for
the university.''
   Mike Stewart, the university's police chief, said Thursday that
no arrests have been made in connection with the fire two months
ago, but the investigation was continuing.
   The house, which Phi Beta Sigma members had been working on
prior to moving in, was destroyed in the pre-dawn blaze.
Authorities said they found an accelerant in the house, indicating
the fire was deliberately set.
   After the fire, the university's Interfraternity Council
established a fund drive to raise $20,000 to renovate another house
for Phi Beta Sigma. So far, $14,000 has been raised.
   University spokesman Ed Meek said Ole Miss had the house
renovated and the fraternity would reimburse the institution from
the fund drive.
