<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Politics     10-14 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Politics,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Speaker Calls Session Next Week To Decide His Fate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini today
called Parliament to meet in Moslem west Beirut next week to renew
his term or to elect a new speaker.
   Christian deputies who have boycotted previous Parliament
sessions in Syrian-policed west Beirut had no immediate reaction to
Husseini's call for a session on Tuesday.
   Husseini's one-year term expires Oct. 15. Parliament's bylaws
require that a new speaker be elected on the first Tuesday after
the previous term expires.
   Parliament has failed three times since Aug. 18 to convene and
elect a successor to President Amin Gemayel, whose six-year term
expired Sept. 22.
   Twenty-seven Christian legislators have boycotted Parliament,
preventing the 76-member body from reaching the 51-member quorum
needed to elect a new president. They said they wanted to prevent
the election of a pro-Syrian candidate.
   The deadlock has led to the formation of rival Christian and
Moslem cabinets.
   Gemayel has appointed army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, a
Maronite Catholic, to head an interim military cabinet.
   The appointment violated an unwritten national covenant dating
to independence from France in 1943 requiring the prime minister to
be a Sunni Moslem, the president a Maronite and the house speaker a
Shiite Moslem.
   Syrian-backed leftist and Moslem leaders have rejected Aoun's
appointment and declared support for acting Sunni Prime Minister
Salim Hoss' five-man cabinet, which governed during Gemayel's term.
</TEXT>
