<HEAD>Ex-LaRouche Aide Ordered To Begin Serving Sentence</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Recasts lead, restoring dropped word.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former associate of political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche has begun serving a three-year conspiracy sentence after
he was arrested and charged with violating bail by illegally
possessing six handguns.
   Roy Frankhauser, convicted last year in the LaRouche conspiracy
case, was ordered Thursday to begin serving the sentence by U.S.
District Judge Robert E. Keeton.
   The order came after federal prosecutors charged Frankhauser
violated terms of his release when he was arrested by FBI agents
last week at a house where six guns were stored.
   Federal prosecutors also said Frankhauser beat his girlfriend
and elderly mother, and left Pennsylvania twice to attend Ku Klux
Klan rallies. However, those allegations were not cited by Keeton
in revoking bail.
   Frankhauser, 49, of Reading, Pa., was escorted out of court by
U.S. marshals and was being held until assignment to a federal
prison.
   He had been free on bail pending appeal of his conviction last
December of conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury
investigation into allegations that LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign raised more than $2 million through credit card and loan
fraud.
   Frankhauser, a former member of the KKK and the American Nazi
Party, was a LaRouche security consultant for seven years until he
left in late 1986, about the time the first indictment in the
LaRouche case was returned.
   He was arrested at the home of his girlfriend, Anne Traczyk, in
Reading, where he had been staying for several months, after the
woman told the FBI he had ``beat her about the face and back, and
then placed a gun against her head and told her, `I'm going to kill
you,''' according to court documents.
   Under the terms of his release, Frankhauser was barred by Keeton
from possessing any guns or being in a house where guns were kept,
and from traveling outside Reading. He was arrested on charges of
being a convicted felon illegally possessing a firearm.
   In court documents, federal prosecutors charged that Frankhauser
crossed state lines at least twice since his February sentencing to
attend KKK meetings and rallies in Maryland and was armed each time.
   The FBI found two handguns _ a fully loaded .38-caliber with a
two-inch barrel and a replica of a German-made weapon _ in
Traczyk's house, according to the documents. Three more handguns
and a rifle were found in a locked metal box opened after
authorities obtained a search warrant.
   Uniforms bearing Nazi emblems, knives, brass knuckles,
ceremonial swords and .22-caliber ammunition also were found in the
house, the documents said.
   Traczyk also told the FBI that Frankhauser ``physically and
verbally assaulted his elderly mother,'' the papers said. At the
time of his sentencing, Franhauser pleaded for leniency, saying he
had to care for his mother and planned to get married.
   Frankhauser was the first defendant in the complex LaRouche
fraud and conspiracy case, and was tried separately because his
defense was to accuse LaRouche of a coverup.
   Testimony during Frankhauser's trial indicated he advised
LaRouche to order fund-raisers to leave the country, burn documents
and refuse to cooperate with investigators. Attorneys claimed
LaRouche workers thought Frankhauser was working for the CIA.
   Frankhauser was convicted in connection with a school bus
bombing in Pontiac, Mich., in the 1970s. He also has served as a
government informant, working closely with the FBI.
   A new trial of LaRouche, six aides and five political
organizations is scheduled to begin in January after the first case
ended in a mistrial in May. Three other defendants are fugitives.
   LaRouche, who has accused world leaders of being Soviet agents
and who is running for president for a fourth time, is charged with
ordering supporters to destroy records and refuse to cooperate with
investigators.
</TEXT>
