<HEAD>Suspected `Black Baron' Arrested For Low-Level Nighttime Flights</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `The French...' to CORRECT to World War I.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a man suspected of being the
``Black Baron,'' a pilot who evaded them for months while making
low-level nighttime flights over the capital, reports said today.
   The Air and Border Police arrested Albert Maltret, 53, when he
landed Thursday at Saint-Cyr, a private airfield in a Paris suburb,
the French news agency, Agence-France Presse, reported.
   Maltret was convicted in 1986 of landing a small plane on the
Champs Elysee, which at the time was temporarily closed to traffic
for the filming of a feature-length movie. He was fined $3,300 and
his pilot's license was suspended.
   Low-level flights over Paris are illegal. For months the pilot
stumped police, who could not identify the plane or even be certain
it wasthe same pilot each time. On Aug. 13, police helicopters
chased the plane but were unable to catch it.
   The French media called the pilot the Black Baron, a play on the
World War I flying ace, the Red Baron.
   Today, police staked out airports around Paris after being
alerted that Maltret left his home to make another illegal flight.
Authorities arrived at Saint-Cyr moments after Maltret's plane took
off. About seven minutes later, a plane was spotted making a low
pass over the Champs Elysees.
   Police arrested Maltret immediately after he landed his rented
Rallye MS 880 Morane-Saulnier plane. Maltret had recently been
granted an amnesty that allowed him to recover his pilot's license.
   In early September, a masked pilot callling himself the Black
Baron was interviewed on French television about his aerial
exploits.
</TEXT>
