<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SavannahRiver     10-14 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savannah River,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Du Pont Says Controversy Unrelated To SRP Manager's Departure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general manager of the Savannah River
Plant is leaving, but his departure has no connection with safety
problems at the nuclear weapons fuel plant, a spokesman for Du Pont
says.
   John T. Granaghan is taking a leave of absence, pending his
retirement after 38 years with Du Pont, because of medical reasons,
spokesman Jim Felder said Thursday. Du Pont operates Savannah River
for the Department of Energy.
   ``It's a personal matter. Mr. Granaghan had surgery earlier this
year,'' Felder said.
   Concerns about safety at the plant arose dramatically at a
congressional hearing last month when a list of what Du Pont
considered the 30 most serious reactor incidents at the 38-year-old
plant was made public.
   SRP's three reactors were reduced to half power last year when
experts questioned whether the emergency cooling system could
handle a problem at full power.
   Since April, all three reactors have been shut down entirely for
maintenance and testing amid additional safety questions. One
reactor was restarted for less than a week in August.
   When it was shut down, SRP was the sole producer of radioactive
tritium and plutonium used in nuclear weapons. The only other
producer, the Hanford Nuclear Reservation in Washington state, has
been shut down for more than a year. The Rocky Flats plutonium
processing plant near Denver also is closed.
   Meanwhile, Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
criticized the Reagan administration's record in dealing with
problems at Savannah River.
   Dukakis said in a statement Thursday that President Reagan and
Vice President George Bush, his opponent, have ``ignored the
serious safety and environmental problems at our nuclear production
facilities.''
   Bush agreed that Savannah River ``needs to be made more safe.''
   Westinghouse Electric Co. is scheduled to assume operation of
the plant on April 1, and company officials say they are planning
for what should be an orderly transition.
   Westinghouse executives have met with officials from the federal
Department of Energy and Du Pont in Washington concerning plans to
restart SRP's reactors.
   ``We still don't run the reactors, but we have a lot of advice
and counsel. ... We're going to be living with them, whatever's
done,'' said Westinghouse spokesman Jack Herrmann.
</TEXT>
