<HEAD>Myerson To Judge's Daughter: You're My Friend But Don't Tell Them
Your Name</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to update with judge's ruling, picking up
at 6th graf pvs, `Ms. Gabel said ...;'' deletes outdated last 2
grafs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors at the divorce-fixing conspiracy trial of
former Miss America Bess Myerson will be allowed to hear a key bit
of testimony from the prosecution's star witness, the judge ruled
today.
   U.S. District Judge John F. Keenan decided, over defense
objections, that Sukhreet Gabel can describe a conversation she had
with her father after learning her mother was the judge presiding
over the divorce of Miss Myerson's lover.
   Miss Myerson, the city's cultural affairs commissioner at the
time, is charged with giving Ms. Gabel a city job to influence the
rulings of her mother, former Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel,
in the divorce of millionaire contractor Carl ``Andy'' Capasso.
   Ms. Gabel testified about the conversation with her father,
Milton, with the jury out of the courtroom Thursday because defense
lawyers objected to the testimony as hearsay.
   She said that when she learned from Capasso's housekeeper that
her mother was the judge in the Capasso divorce, she confronted her
father, and that he told her, ``Your mother knows all about it,''
and advised her, ``Don't get involved.''
   Mrs. Gabel, 75, Miss Myerson, 64, and Capasso, 43, are all
charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and bribe-related charges for
an alleged scheme to reduce Capasso's temporary support payments to
his estranged wife.
   In regular testimony Thursday, Ms. Gabel said Miss Myerson went
out of her way to cultivate a friendship with her, but tried to
keep their socializing secret. She said Miss Myerson told her not
to give her real name when she accompanied Miss Myerson to a party.
   Ms. Gabel, 39, described how Miss Myerson sought out her company
in the summer of 1983 after they met at a dinner party given by Ms.
Gabel's parents.
   Ms. Gabel said she twice made weekend visits to Capasso's Long
Island estate in Westhampton at Miss Myerson's invitation, but on
one visit her hostess fretted about whether to take her along to a
party.
   ``I don't know whether I ought to be doing this,'' Ms. Gabel
quoted Miss Myerson as saying, adding, ``Andy's against it.''
   Miss Myerson asked Ms. Gabel, who was divorced, what her married
name had been.
   When Ms. Gabel replied ``Revis,'' she said Miss Myerson put one
hand to her brow and pointed the other at her, saying, ``You tell
them your name is Revis.''
   Ms. Gabel's re-enactment of the scene provoked chuckles in the
packed courtroom, but Miss Myerson looked on tight-lipped.
   Ms. Gabel said she gave a non-committal answer to Miss Myerson's
idea but it turned out no one at the party asked her name anyway.
   Prosecutors maintain that Miss Myerson's interest in Ms. Gabel
developed only after the younger woman's mother began handling
interim rulings in Capasso's divorce.
</TEXT>
