<HEAD>Quayle Declares Bush the `Hands Down' Winner in Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 12 grafs to UPDATE with Quayle news conference; picks
up 6th graf pvs, bgng: The Indiana...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle said today that Democrat Michael Dukakis lacked ``common
courtesy'' because he let a chance pass to say something nice about
George Bush during their second debate.
   Quayle, in his first news conference since Sept. 15, said he
found the moment ``very telling.''
   Both Bush and Dukakis were asked during the debate whether there
was something specific they had found about their opponent to
praise. Bush said he admired Dukakis' family and their open display
of affection for each other. Dukakis did not make any direct praise
of Bush.
   ``George Bush was very complimentary to Michael Dukakis on a
personal basis,'' Quayle said. He added, ``You would have thought
he (Dukakis) had the common courtesy to say something nice about
George Bush, but he didn't.''
   ``That's a very telling point,'' he said.
   Pressed to elaborate, Quayle said, ``He did lack the common
courtesy to say something nice.''
   After the debate Thursday night, Quayle called Bush the ``hands
down'' winner and said he believed his running mate delivered a
knockout punch to the Massachusetts Democrat.
   ``Say good night, Mike,'' Quayle said at a post-debate rally
Thursday night. Hundreds of supporters picked up the phrase and
began chanting, ``Say good night, Mike.''
   But Quayle said today the race was still competitive. ``We still
have a horse race.''
   At the rally, with a brass band, bluegrass group and American
flag as his backdrop, Quayle noted that Fort Smith had been the
setting for the movie ``True Grit'' and added: ``We know who showed
true grit tonight.''
   Using a baseball analogy, Quayle said Bush not only ``hit it out
over centerfield, he hit it out of sight. The bases were loaded,
and it was a grand slam.''
   Quayle watched the debate from his hotel room with several
advisers. A small pool of reporters and photographers was allowed
into the room just as the GOP nominee was asked whether Quayle was
qualified to be the 41st president should anything happen to Bush.
   The Indiana senator beamed as Bush said, ``I'm proud of my
choice.''
   The press was not present, however, to see Quayle's reaction
when it came time for Dukakis to address that question.
   At the rally, Quayle pulled the covering off a huge sign that
read, ``The winner is George Bush.''
   ``Vice President Bush won the debate tonight, hands down. He won
in every single category,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle telephoned Bush after the debate and told him he did a
``fantastic'' job, aides said.
   The Indiana senator had a light campaign day Thursday, with
appearances in Missoula, Mont., and Lawton, Okla.
   After touring an electric plant today, Quayle travels to
Lafayette, La., Albuquerque, N.M., and Wisconsin.
   His speech Thursday to a Blue Cross@Blue Shield service club in
Missoula was disrupted by a Bible-carrying man who stood on his
chair and declared: ``We need to defend our country with God's
principles, not missiles.''
   ``Why don't you apply them to yourself?'' Quayle retorted.
   As the audience shouted, ``Sit down!'' the man offered Quayle
his Bible.
   ``I would suggest you read it,'' Quayle said.
</TEXT>
