<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoneyLaundering     10-14 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Laundering,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Told Earlier Of Noriega Link With Luxembourg Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank officer implicated in an international
drug-money laundering scheme told Senate investigators that he
managed an account for Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega that was used to
pay Panamanian politicians.
   Amjad Awan, an officer of the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, told a subcommittee of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee on Sept. 30 that he paid cash from the account after
receiving notes signed by Noriega.
   The testimony, made in a closed session, was released Thursday.
   Before the arrival of the notes, Awan said he got telephone
calls ``telling me to expect the person to come in to get these
funds.''
   When asked to whom the money was paid, Awan replied:
``Politicians. This was during the time of the elections in
Panama.''
   Noriega, who as head of the military effectively rules Panama,
has been indicted by two U.S. grand juries on charges of drug
trafficking, and the Reagan administration has pressed for his
ouster as defense chief.
   Awan said the balance in Noriega's account fluctuated but at one
point reached a high of ``$20 million, maybe $25 million.'' He
added that he made monthly trips to Panama to report to Noriega on
the status of the account.
   Awan was arrested by the U.S. Customs Service last week and
indicted this week on charges of money laundering. The
Luxembourg-based bank for which he works was charged in the Tampa
indictment with laundering $14 million in narcotics profits for
Colombia's Medellin cartel.
   Subcommittee counsel Jack Blum told senators present at the
Sept. 30 session that the testimony would be closely held because
of ``our concern for Mr. Awan's life,'' according to materials
released by the office of Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who chaired the
subcommittee.
   A spokesman for Kerry said the panel voted after Awan's arrest
to release the testimony and send a copy to the Justice Department.
   The St. Petersburg Times on Thursday quoted an unidentified
Justice Department official who worked on both the Noriega and Bank
of Credit cases as saying: ``We have never been able to identify a
Noriega bank account outside of Panama. We would like to hope this
account would be a breakthrough.''
   He said U.S. investigators hope to obtain detailed records of
the account by the end of the week.
</TEXT>
