<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DebateRating     10-14 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate Rating,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biggest Audience for Final Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Approximately 62 million viewers tuned in for
the final presidential debate, more than for either of the two
previous face-offs between the two parties, the A.C. Nielsen Co.
said today.
   About 58 percent of those watching television during the time
period Thursday night were tuned into the debate, according to
Nielsen's overnight figures from the 16 largest TV markets.
   The debate between Democrat presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
and Republican George Bush had a rating on NBC of 16.6 and a 24
share. ABC's coverage had a rating of 14.1 and a 20 share. CBS' had
a 9.6 and 14 share.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 households with televisions.
The share is the percentage of sets in use.
   PBS and CNN also carried the debate live, but their ratings are
not available immediately.
   An estimated 50 million viewers tuned into the vice presidential
debate last week between Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and Bush's running
mate, Dan Quayle, and about 60 million viewers watched the first
debate between Bush and Dukakis.
</TEXT>
