<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RabbitRuckus     10-14 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rabbit Ruckus,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scouts Review Neutral Policy on Animal Killing In Survival
Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Boy Scout officials will review
their neutral policy on killing animals for food as part of
wilderness survival training in light of complaints by animal
rights groups.
   National spokesman Frank Hebb initially said Thursday national
scout officials would ``take a look at it and see whether we should
ban this sort of thing. It's not necessary.''
   He said there was no timetable for making a decision.
   At a camp-out in nearby Perry County earlier this fall, scouts
were shown how to kill a rabbit and then prepare it for eating.
   Five to 10 scouts then accepted an invitation to test their
skills on rabbits, and the same procedure was done with four or
five chickens, said William J. Hawkins, executive director of the
Keystone Council, the local scout affiliate.
   ``We looked at the wilderness survival merit badge phamplet and
it put food at the very bottom for survival,'' Hebb said.
   H. Clay Criswell, executive director of the Humane Society of
Harrisburg Area Inc., said the most important things in survival
are finding shelter and water. ``You don't have to have meat to
stay alive.''
   Hawkins said he will recommend discouraging troops in the
11,500-scout Keystone Council from killing animals in future
survival programs.
   ``If we discourage it at the council level, it won't be done,''
Hawkins said.
   ``I don't appreciate the hue and cry. ... It's unfortunate,'' he
said, noting he got about 50 phone calls, mostly negative. ``It's
been blown out of proportion.''
   Trans-Species Unlimited of Williamsport, Pa., a national animal
rights group that has fought live pigeon shoots and fur sales,
demanded the Boy Scouts adopt a ban after The Patriot-News
newspapers reported the incident this week.
   ``We're very pleased to hear about that (policy review),'' said
Vice President Dana Stuchell.
   After a week of investigation, the Humane Society has been
unable to find anyone who would testify that the animals were
treated cruelly, Criswell said.
   About 75 to 90 boys and 20 to 30 leaders from 10 troops attended
the camp, where other sessions touched on building fires and
finding edible plants, Hawkins said. He added that the survival
camp-out was the first held in the 15 years he has been associated
with the council. The decison was made by the camp organizers, he
said.
   Hawkins said he believes the reports he received from scout
leaders who said the animals were not cruelly bludgeoned.
   G. John Giba, scoutmaster for one of the troops involved but who
was unable to make the trip, said his boys felt the killings were
done properly.
   ``We entered into this purely innocently,'' said Giba, who has
hunted deer and said the rabbits were handled better than some
hunters handle deer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
