<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Debate-Reax 2ndLd-Writethru a0560 10-14 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Reax, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0560,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Delighted; Democrats Acknowledge `No Knockout' by
Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dole, Byrd comments in top 5 grafs, picking up
in 3rd graf pvs, ``I think</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans celebrated George Bush's debate performance, some
even declaring the election won, but Democrats said today that
Michael Dukakis had made points, too, in the candidates' final
nationally televised encounter.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said today that Bush
was ``the clear winner'' in the debate, and he added: ``It seems to
me George Bush is going to win this election and he's going to win
it by a big margin, particularly in the Electoral College.''
   On the Democratic side, Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd of
West Virginia, said of Bush, ``I'd say he won the debate if it were
a race for high school cheerleader.''
   Byrd said Dukakis ``had substance to his responses. I thought he
made some good points with his responses to the deficit.'' He
added, ``I'm not sure these debates really amount to much.''
   ``I think Bush can start measuring the curtains for the White
House,'' Delaware's GOP Gov. Michael Castle said Thursday night
after the debate.
   ``I think we got it,'' said Republican Rep. Lynn Martin of
Illinois. ``I've coached him (Bush) and I've never seen him that
good. He walked off that stage the president of the United States.''
   Democrats generally claimed victory for Dukakis on the issues,
but officials in both parties questioned whether he had done enough
to thaw his icy image.
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., did say today on NBC's ``Today''
program that Dukakis ``came across as someone who understands the
problems American families experience out there, the problems of
living from paycheck to paycheck, in many cases one illness away
from financial disaster.''
   But James Baker III, Bush's campaign chairman, said on ``CBS
This Morning'' that Dukakis had too much to handle in trying to
warm up his image while trying to score a breakthrough that would
overcome Bush's lead in the polls.
   ``It's pretty hard to attack in a debate and at the same time
appear more likable,'' Baker said.
   Pennsylvania's Democratic Lt. Gov. Mark Singel said Dukakis was
at least partly successful in breaking his image as a cold
technocrat.
   ``I don't think he's ever going to be Henny Youngman,'' Singel
said. ``But he was certainly more likable tonight and I think he
approached many of the questions with good humor. I think he showed
himself to be capable of warmth and I think the people will
appreciate that.''
   William Cunningham, a former adviser to Democratic Gov. Mario
Cuomo who is now working on Sen. Daniel Moynihan's re-election
campaign, summed it up this way: ``Dukakis was Dukakis. Bush was
loose, chipper, magnanimous. It worked out well for him.
   ``Dukakis should have been more like Zorba and less like Plato,
more like Kojak and less like Socrates.''
   And at least one Democrat gave the decisio to Bush.
   ``The one home run I heard was Bush's,'' said former Sen. Thomas
Eagleton of Missouri, who was George McGovern's running mate in
1972 until he withdrew from the ticket after it was revealed that
he had undergone shock treatments for psychiatric problems.
   ``When they asked who their heroes were, Dukakis was wandering
all over the stage,'' Eagleton said. ``Bush, with two minutes to
think about it, came up with some solid candidates and ended up
with the president.''
   Most observers from both parties agreed that the two candidates
seemed more at ease than they had during their first encounter.
   ``It was a better debate than the first one. There was a little
more spontaneity,'' said former White House Chief of Staff Howard
Baker from his home in Huntsville, Tenn.
   But Baker called Bush the clear winner ``principally because he
took advantage to sharpen the issue differences between them in
defense and taxes ... His general demeanor was the most effective
thing. He was very presidential. He was calm and self-assured; his
answers were direct.''
   Even Republicans who didn't rate Bush a clear-cut winner said it
was enough that he avoided a poor showing.
   ``Dukakis had to do something dramatic and I don't think he did
it. I don't think he laid a glove on Bush,'' said Ellen Sauerbrey,
a GOP delegate from Maryland. ``I think barring some unforeseen
gaffe in the next couple weeks or a major world-shattering event. I
think the election is over. This was Dukakis' last chance to really
turn public opinion.''
   Heading into the debate, most polls gave Bush a narrow lead
among voters nationwide and a strong lead for electoral votes.
   Democratic Rep. John Dingell of Michigan disputed the notion
that it was a do-or-die test for his party's candidate.
   ``It was not really necessary for Mr. Dukakis to deliver a
knockout blow,'' Dingell said. ``There are 26 days left in the
campaign. A lot can happen and a lot will. The Dukakis campaign is
coming together and he'll do well.''
</TEXT>
