<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0488 10-14 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Sasso briefing; pick up 4th graf pvs
bgng ``But the second...; Delete final 2 grafs to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis characterized the
White House race as still ``very close'' as his chief political
adviser said today ``We're down a little bit ... but it's well
within range.''
   Dukakis prepared for a rally here while his campaign scrambled
to put the best face on a Thursday night debate performance that
left the candidate short of a breakthrough to even up a contest
that shows signs of a growing Republican advantage.
   The Democratic campaign unveiled two new televison
advertisements that will begin airing today and top aide John Sasso
said $13 million to $14 million would be spent on commercials in
the final weeks.
   Sasso conceded a George Bush edge in the instant public opinion
polls but said, ``We scored with undecided and swing voters last
evening. That's what we were looking for.''
   ``We're down a little bit, there's no question about that. But
it's well within range,'' Sasso told reporters.
   Sasso also brushed off queries about whether a Bush win was
inevitable as surveys point to an increasing Electoral College
advantage for the vice president.
   ``I don't agree with that,'' he said. ``You campaign as hard as
you can, you continue to talk about the things that are important
to you. You continue to make the case for change.''
   Dukakis ended the debate night with a call for a third debate.
   ``I think we ought to have that third debate, don't you?''
Dukakis asked a post-debate rally attended by about 2,000
supporters Thursday night. The crowd cheered wildly.
   Dukakis said debates enable the Democrats ``to get our opponents
out from behind the flag factory and the balloons and people get a
chance to see how they stand on the basic and fundamental
challenges that face the country.''
   But the second debate, according to some Democrats, did not
prove to be Dukakis' forum for delivering a knockout punch and
overcoming Bush's lead in recent nationwide polls.
   ``Dukakis was Dukakis. Bush was loose, chipper, magnanimous. It
worked out well for him,'' said William Cunningham, a former
adviser to New York Gov. Mario Cuomo who is now working for New
York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's re-election campaign.
   ``Dukakis was so much better on the issues, but he wasn't as
warm as Bush was,'' said Democratic Sen. Dennis DeConcini of
Arizona.
   Instant polls conducted by ABC News and the Los Angeles Times
declared Bush the clear winner.
   The ABC poll of 639 registered voters who viewed the debate
found 49 percent calling Bush the winner, 33 percent saying Dukakis
won and 18 percent rated the debate a tie. The survey had a margin
of error of plus or minus four percentage points.
   The Times survey scored Bush the winner 47 percent to 26 percent
with 27 percent undecided. The poll of 522 registered voters who
saw the debate had a margin of error of five percentage points.
   At the post-debate rally, Dukaks boasted of a ``clean sweep'' in
the debates and ridiculed Bush's selection of a running mate,
saying it demonstrated poor judgment that should not be allowed to
spill over to Supreme Court selections.
   ``If one question tonight demonstrated the stakes in this
election, it was the question about the Supreme Court of the United
States,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Remember this: the people who are appointed to the Supreme
Court of the United States by a president are there long after that
president leaves,'' Dukakis said. ``George Bush supported the
nomination of Robert Bork. George Bush demonstrated his commitment
to standards and quality and strength by picking as his running
mate the senator from Indiana.''
   Dukakis told supporters he was entering the ``all important''
final 25 days in the race for the White House as the underdog but
within striking distance.
   ``I don't have to tell you that this race is very, very close,''
he said. ``And it's going to get even closer after tonight and it's
going to get closer still in the days ahead.''
   Dukakis, who also attended two private receptions following the
debate, was campaigning in California and Washington today,
including a joint appearance with running mate Lloyd Bentsen in
Sacramento and an evening stop at a birthday party for Jesse
Jackson.
   At the post-debate rally, Dukakis said he would welcome a third
showdown with Bush.
   The vice president, whose campaign refused to participate in a
third debate, ruled out another encounter when asked Thursday night
if he would agreee to debate Dukakis again.
   Dukakis began the rally by asking ``What did you think?'' and
``A clean sweep?''
   Both questions were met with rousing applause.
</TEXT>
