<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-BookBan     10-14 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Book Ban,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ban Upheld On War Crimes Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British publisher today asked
bookstores to refrain from selling the book ``Occupation: Nazi
Hunter'' because a judge refused to lift an ordering banning
publication.
   Anton Gecas, who is mentioned in the book in connection with
alleged war crimes, was granted the order last month.
   Gecas, 72, of Edinburgh, is one of 17 people in Britain being
investigated by the Home Office in a war crimes inquiry. Gecas, a
former Lithuanian platoon commander, has denied committing war
crimes.
   Lord Cowie today dismissed a challenge to the banning order by
publishers Ashford Press Publishing of Hampshire at the Court of
Session in Edinburgh.
   He said the book could seriously prejudice a defamation action
against Times Newspapers by Gecas, which is due to be heard by a
Scottish court.
   The publishers had argued that the terms of the order were too
wide and a Scottish court had no power to ban a book in England.
   Lord Cowie said that as long as a Scottish court had
jurisidiction in a case, it could make an order that might apply
anywhere.
   He refused to grant a similar court order against the author of
the book, Efraim Zuroff of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los
Angeles, saying the ruling against the publishers already protected
Gecas. The center is committed to pursuing World War II Nazis who
have escaped prosecution for war crimes.
   After the hearing, Ashford Press sent letters to booksellers
throughout Britain informing them that the court order effectively
barring the firm from publishing the book worldwide and asking that
it should not be put on sale Monday as planned.
</TEXT>
