<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RapeLibel     10-14 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Libel,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Says Women's Group Libeled Man In Assault Accusation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has found that the group Women
Against Rape libeled a man when it circulated a flier that falsely
accused him of assault and attempted rape.
   Steve Carney, who was never charged, was awarded $7,500 for pain
and suffering and $25,000 in punitive damages by the seven-man,
five-woman panel.
   ``I feel a lot better, but I can't say I really won because
there may be people out there who saw it (the flier) and formed
their own opinions,'' Carney, 23, said after hearing Thursday's
verdict.
   ``I think it will teach them to be a little more careful about
what accusations they choose to print about people,'' he said.
   Carney, of Scotts Valley, sued Women Against Rape of Santa Cruz,
claiming the group publicly humilated him in a 1984 leaflet that
said he assaulted and attempted to rape Karen Winkler, 24.
   During the libel trial in Santa Cruz County Superior Court, it
was brought out that Winkler never went to police and swore in a
deposition that she didn't know what happened the night she went
out drinking with Carney and another co-worker.
   Representatives of WAR testified that they based the flier
solely on Winkler's word and by observing her behavior, which they
said was consistent with a profile of women who have been sexually
assaulted.
   Representatives of the organization earlier declined an offer
from Carney's lawyer that the suit would be dropped in exchange for
an apology and a retraction.
   Deanne Pernell and Jan Shirchild, both WAR directors, said they
would discuss an appeal with the organization's lawyers.
   WAR has said it is $500 in debt and is unlikely to be able to
meet the jury's verdict, but Carney's lawyer, David Sabih, said
money wasn't the paramount issue.
   During closing arguments on Wednesday, Sabih told the jury that
the issue was whether ``we as a society tolerate groups of
vigilantes who impose themselves as judge, jury and executioner.''
   Winkler, who did not testify at the trial, originally was named
in the suit but settled out of court with an apology for
participating in the publication of the flier.
</TEXT>
