<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     10-14 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preschool Molest,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McMartin Case Has `Poisoned' All Involved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The McMartin Pre-School molestation case
contributed to the deaths of two witnesses and ``has poisoned
everyone who had contact with it,'' says the judge who is presiding
over the long-running trial.
   The bleak comments by Superior Court Judge William Pounders came
Thursday, one day after he dismissed 27 prosecution charges against
Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey. He spoke in
response to a news media request to make public the prosecutors'
original trial witness list.
   The weekly newspaper, ``The Easy Reader,'' joined by the Los
Angeles Times, sought the names of more than 100 prospective
witnesses who never testified. The prosecution ended its
presentation of witnesses last week, and the defense is to begin
next week.
   The judge angrily refused to disclose the names, saying those
witnesses have privacy rights. Pounders said he refused to subject
people on the witness list to the ``embarrassment and harassment''
that plagued others.
   ``This case, in my view, has poisoned everyone who had contact
with it,'' Pounders said.
   ``We've had two deaths in connection with this case,'' he said
referring to a mother who died in 1986 from the side effects of
alcoholism and an investigator who committed suicide the day before
he was to testify in 1987.
   Kevin Cody, a reporter for ``Easy Reader'' who has covered much
of the trial, told the judge that the case has been ``the subject
of rumors and innuendo'' and added, ``Anything that's left unsaid
at the end of the case is going to weaken public confidence in the
verdict.''
   ``You're acting as a censor on a case which has repercussions
across the country,'' Cody told the judge.
   ``You are a good one to talk about this,'' Pounders shot back.
``You knew Paul Bynum fairly well and saw him suffer in this
courtroom,'' he said of the investigator who committed suicide.``I
understand you had dinner with him the night before this happened.''
   Cody did not respond to that comment but told the judge it was
foolish to base his rulings on ``who might die in this case.''
   Bynum, 39, a former police officer who had worked as a defense
investigator on the McMartin case, shot himself in the head last
Dec. 10, the day before he was to testify. A year before that, Judy
Ann Johnson, the mother who first brought the McMartin case to
police, died of alcohol-related liver disease.
   The McMartin case has been in the courts for five years, and the
trial has been under way for a year and a half.
   Buckey, 30, and his 61-year-old mother were charged with 100
molestation and conspiracy counts until Wednesday when the judge,
at the behest of prosecutors, dismissed 27 counts _ nearly a third
of the case. Prosecutors said they would seek dismissal of eight
more counts. The defendants are accused of molesting children at
the now defunct McMartin Pre-School in Manhattan Beach.
   In another ruling Thursday, the judge agreed to make public
written transcripts of videotapes that were played for jurors
during the trial. The tapes showed children being interviewed about
alleged molestations by therapists. The judge said he would delete
the children's names from the transcripts.
</TEXT>
