<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Study,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study of Drug for AIDS-Related Illness Discontinued</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of treating an AIDS-related condition
with an experimental drug called Ampligen has been stopped because
of disappointing results, the research's sponsors say.
   The study had enrolled about 330 patients with AIDS-related
complex at 11 centers in the United States.
   The research had been sponsored by a joint venture between HEM
Research Inc. of Philadelphia and Du Pont. Cessation of the
experiment was announced in a statement Thursday.
   Interim analysis of data from the study failed to show any
difference between Ampligen and a placebo that would justify
continuing the research, the statement said.
   Symptoms of AIDS-related complex are often less severe than
those of acquired immune deficiency syndome. Symptoms can include
loss of appetite, weight loss, fever, night sweats and swollen
lymph nodes.
</TEXT>
