<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RockyFlats     10-14 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rocky Flats,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockwell Acknowledges Exposure To Plutonium For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International has acknowledged for
the first time that three people were exposed to plutonium last
month in an incident that led to the shutdown of part of the Rocky
Flats nuclear weapons plant.
   Two Rockwell employees and a Department of Energy employee were
exposed to waste tainted by the radioactive element when they
entered an area of Building 771, where plutonium reprocessing is
done.
   Rockwell officials had said previously there was no release of
any radioactive material in the building and no contamination.
   Rockwell said a warning sign was blocked from view and the three
were unaware they should have been wearing respirators to protect
their lungs, Rockwell officials said.
   Rockwell operates the facility 16 miles northwest of Denver for
the Department of Energy, which ordered the building closed.
Rockwell officials said the shutdown of the building will have
little short-term effect on the plant's production of plutonium
triggers for nuclear weapons, but a longer shutdown would cause a
production cutback.
   The shutdown of Building 771 and of reactors at the Savannah
River Plant in South Carolina have raised safety questions about
government nuclear weapons plants.
   Rockwell issued a statement Thursday saying laboratory test
results available this week revealed the three people had been
exposed to small amounts of plutonium.
   ``Results of those tests indicate the employees were exposed to
detectable amounts of plutonium well below all applicable (safety)
standards,'' Rockwell's statement said.
   None of the three is expected to have health problems as a
result of the incident, the Rockwell statement said.
   ``Colorado's annual background radiation level is 350
millirem,'' the statement said. ``This means the maximum exposure
to the three employees involved was nine-100,000ths of the average
Colorado resident's annual exposure to natural background radiation
exposure.''
   Plutonium is considered dangerous even in minute quantities
because of its high radioactivity. Researchers have said it has the
potential to cause cancer and brain tumors when inhaled or ingested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
