<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military: Elections to Be Held No Sooner Than Early 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military government announced
today that general elections will not be held before early 1989 and
that the date will be set after talks with political parties.
   Eighteen parties have taken up the government's call to register
with an election commisson, but none has said whether it will take
part in elections.
   Following weeks of bloody, anti-government protests, hard-line
Gen. Saw Maung seized power from a civilian government Sept. 18,
ordered his troops to shoot protesters and promised to hold general
elections within three months.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said troops killed four people today,
bringing to more than 450 the official number slain by security
forces since Sept. 18.
   The chairman of the five-member election council, Ba Htay, said
registered parties could open branches throughout the country after
consultation with ``law and order restoration councils,'' which
were set up by Saw Maung.
   The parties will be allowed to carry out organizational work on
their own premises, although a ban on public meetings of more than
five persons is still in force.
   ``All arrangements are expected to be ready by early next year,
and the date for holding of elections will be decided after
consultation with political parties,'' Saw Maung said in a
statement carried by the radio.
   Western diplomats in Rangoon are skeptical that free and fair
elections can be held given the ruthlessness with which the ruling
elite put down open dissent in recent months.
   There is a general consensus among Rangoon diplomats that Ne
Win, who seized power in 1962, is still orchestrating the
government and military moves despite his formal retirement in late
July.
   Ne Win molded the military machine and the Burma Socialist
Program Party, which has changed its name to the National Unity
Party.
</TEXT>
