<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-ContraAidChronology     10-14 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Contra Aid Chronology,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Reagan-Contras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since President Reagan took office in 1981,
his policy of financing the Contra rebels in their war against
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government has been one of the most
divisive foreign policy questions facing Congress and the nation.
Here is a chronology of the ups and downs of that policy:
   1981 _ Congress, late in the year, approves $19 million in
covert military aid to the rebels. The money, to be managed by the
CIA, is part of a classified intelligence bill.
   1982 _ A second infusion of $19 million, again part of a
classified bill, is approved. This time, restrictive provisions are
added that prevent any of the money from being used to overthrow
the Sandinistas. There are reports, as well, that the CIA has used
an additional $10 million from its contingency fund.
   1983 _ The House votes to end Contra aid, but a later compromise
results in the appropriation of $24 million for the rebels. This
time, the money is appropriated openly, and the CIA is barred from
using any money from its contingency fund to supplement the new aid.
   1984 _ In April, reports surface that the CIA has supervised the
mining of three Nicaraguan ports, and Congress votes to cut off aid
to the rebels. But at the end of the year, lawmakers vote to set
aside $14 million for the rebels, to be released after Feb. 28,
1985, if Congress approves in a separate vote at that time.
Congress adds new restrictions, saying the CIA and the Pentagon may
not use the money to support paramilitary operations in Nicaragua
unless specifically authorized by Congress.
   1985 _ In April, the Senate votes to release the $14 million,
but the House disapproves the resolution, denying the money to the
rebels. That summer, Congress approves $27 million for the Contras
but restricts its use to food, clothing, medicine and other
``humanitarian'' aid. The money is directed to be used by the
administration as leverage to promote peace negotiations, and the
CIA and Defense Department are barred from any role in distributing
the money.
   1986 _ In the fall, Congress approves $100 million _ its largest
single appropriation for the rebels _ the bulk of it for military
aid. Restrictions on the CIA's role are lifted, except that the
agency remains barred from using its contingency fund.
   1987 _ In March, the House passes a moratorium on Contra aid in
an effort to hold up the final $40 million of the aid bill approved
in 1986, but the measure dies in the Senate. At the end of the
fiscal year, on Sept. 30, Congress begins a series of stopgap
funding measures that include money for ``non-lethal'' aid for the
rebels totaling $20 million.
   1988 _ The House on Feb. 3 kills President Reagan's request for
$36 million in rebel aid, and a month later it rejects a Democratic
alternative of $30 million. The rebels reach a negotiated truce
with the Sandinistas on March 23, and Congress votes to provide $48
million. Peace talks break down in June and U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton is expelled from Nicaragua a month later, although the truce
remains in effect. A $47.1 million aid proposal fails to win
congressional approval in the summer. On Friday, after reports that
Reagan had given up on obtaining new military aid before Congress
adjourned, the president says he ``would not hesitate'' to call a
special session later in the year if he decided military aid was
needed.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0466 10-14 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Might Finish $2.6 Billion Drug Bill Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with resumption of debate; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, Lawmakers who</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate rolled toward passage of a $2.6
billion, campaign-season drug bill today that would dangle the
possibility of the death penalty in front of many drug offenders
who kill.
   Senators today began debating an amendment that would allow
judges to strip convicted illegal drug users of many federal
benefits, including student loans, mortgage guarantees and
licenses. The benefits could be halted for up to one year for a
first conviction and for five years for additional convictions.
   ``If you've got a license to operate a radio station and you're
smoking marijuana, you're going to be subject to losing that
license, and clearly our intent is to say here that we are not
going to tolerate the use of marijuana,'' said the provision's
sponsor, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
   Liberals mounted a fight against the proposal, arguing that it
was too harsh.
   ``Why not adopt the Moslem way of doing things?'' asked Sen. Dan
Evans, R-Wash. ``Cut off a hand for a first conviction. Cut off the
other one for a second conviction. That would be a deterrant.''
   Lawmakers who feared earlier that the wide-ranging measure might
be stillborn because of a torrent of more than 100 amendments began
feeling more optimistic Thursday after a mixture of private
bargaining sessions and floor debates eased several potential
logjams.
   ``I believe the end is in sight now,'' Senate Minority Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan., told his colleagues as they ended their work
Thursday evening.
   Congress, which had hoped to adjourn for the year today, was now
expected to return next week to try to finish the measure. With 33
Senate seats and all 435 House seats being contested on Election
Day, many incumbents would like to have bragging rights to a tough,
crime-fighting package.
   Senators still had more than 50 amendments to wade through. The
suggested changes vary from strengthening child pornography laws
and encouraging states to confiscate the drivers' licenses of
drunken motorists on the spot to requiring warning labels on
containers of alcoholic beverages.
   But many of the testiest disputes, some of them constitutional
issues that pitted liberals against conservatives, seemed to have
been soothed by compromises or were resolved when one side simply
outmuscled the other.
   Conservative lawmakers prevailed when senators voted 64-25 to
retain a provision that would allow capital punishment for people
involved in illegal drug activities who kill or order the death of
civilians or law enforcement officers.
   Death penalty supporters such as Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.,
argued that the sanction was needed to combat ``the incredible
butchery'' drug dealers were committing on the streets.
   ``It's long overdue that that punishment be available,'' D'Amato
said.
   But liberal opponents from both parties, arguing that capital
punishment is barbaric, offered an amendment that would substitute
mandatory life imprisonment without possibility of parole for death
sentences.
   ``Why is it that the Senate's resolve to fight drug abuse and
drug-related crime hangs on whether we will flip the switch on the
electric chair,'' asked Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.
   With the House having passed an even harsher version of the bill
last month _ containing a somewhat broader death penalty provision
_ enactment of the legislation will almost certainly mean a new
federal death sentence statute.
   Senators also voted 88-0 Thursday to add a provision allowing
fines of up to $10,000 to be levied against people found to possess
even small amounts of illegal drugs.
   The two-year legislation uses a shotgun approach to dealing with
illicit drugs, showering 60 percent of its money on prevention and
treatment programs and 40 percent on law enforcement.
   It would add $676 million to federal agency budgets to hire
3,287 new law officers and purchase new equipment, and distribute
$275 million to state and local authorities.
   A Cabinet-level ``drug czar'' would be created to oversee
federal anti-drug efforts, penalties for dealing drugs near schools
would be increased, and public housing authorities would be allowed
to hire investigators to gather evidence of drug-use by tenants.
   In addition, $1 billion would be provided for treatment programs
across the country, including money to build facilities and train
counselors and teachers. And airline, railroad and trucking
industry workers would be subjected drug and alcohol testing.
   Left unanswered is where money to pay for the measure's
initiatives would come from. Some senators and their aides said
Thursday that legislators might pass separate legislation to
provide the funds _ and add to the deficit _ either next week or
after the 101st Congress convenes in January.
   The House and Senate would have to work out their differences
before sending a bill to President Reagan for his signature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
