<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BotchedBurials 1stLd-Writethru a0597 10-14 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Botched Burials, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives Shocked, Saddened After Checking Graves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Wilks' rearrest today,
picking up 8th graf pvs, `Darrell Dowdell ....' Note contents</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CONNIE CASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROSS PLAINS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cross Plains Cemetery is dotted
with mounds of freshly turned soil, marking graves reopened by
families who feared that a funeral director improperly buried their
loved ones.
   Many were horrified by what they found.
   ``This lady right here, her casket was rolled over on its side
and one of her arms and her head was sticking out,'' said Bonnie
Clinard of Springfield.
   Funeral director Bobby Wilks of nearby Milldale was arrested
after family members told authorities he had buried a body without
the $375 vault they purchased. When the grave was opened, there was
no vault.
   At least 10 other families have filed complaints since Wilks,
52, was charged a week ago with fraud and attempting to commit a
felony, Robertson County Sheriff Bill Norman said.
   The funeral director was arrested again today by sheriff's
deputies as he checked out of the Tennessee Christian Medical
Center in Madison, said Robertson County Chief Deputy Milton
Frederick.
   Wilks was charged with six counts of obtaining money under false
pretenses, said sheriff's Lt. J. Jones. Bond was set at $80,500,
and Jones said he expected to turn Wilks over to Sumner County
deputies ``as soon as we get through processing him here.''
   Sumner County Chief of Detectives George Farmer said Wilks is
charged there with one count of larceny by use of false pretenses.
   Wilks' son, Gary Wilks, was charged last week with larceny and
released on bond, authorities said.
   Darrell Dowdell, an independent gravedigger, said he knew of 11
graves that were reopened in three cemeteries around this community
about 40 miles north of Nashville, and only one was done properly.
   ``The others ranged from slightly wrong to grossly wrong. Some
were put in on their sides, some had the vaults removed or the
caskets were damaged or they were the wrong caskets,'' he said.
   ``One had the vault and casket removed. It was just a body
laying in the dirt,'' he said.
   Trash, including cans, bottles, a bag of human hair, and flower
arrangements, was found in all 10 graves, Dowdell said. Some bodies
were found surrounded by trash inside the casket.
   ``One had an old metal flower pot on top of his head. It was
like he (Wilks) was mad at them all,'' Dowdell said.
   Terry Carlisle shoveled dirt from his father's grave Thursday
afternoon as his mother and a dozen other people watched.
   With the help of relatives, he dug down about two feet and used
a metal rod to probe another four feet into the grave. No sign of a
casket or vault for Andrew Carlisle was found.
   ``I don't think we're going to find any casket,'' said Ola
Carlisle, whose husband was buried in 1982. The family said they
would have a funeral home exhume the body Friday.
   Mrs. Carlisle said she had trusted Wilks completely and was not
suspicious at the funeral when he asked family members to leave the
grave site before the coffin was lowered.
   The Robertson County Health Department had issued 19
disinterment permits by Thursday afternoon, secretary Paulette
Cowan said.
   Wilks, who resigned as a Robertson County commissioner the day
he was charged, was admired and respected by the community, Mrs.
Clinard said.
   ``I've known him all my life,'' she said. ``There wasn't nothing
he wouldn't do for nobody. People didn't give him nothing but a
good name. For him to do something like this is crazy.''
   Betty Ruth Jones, whose parents, husband and daughter were
buried by Wilks, said she had no intention of checking the graves.
   ``I think it's a disgrace,'' she said. ``God laid those to
rest.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
