<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Study,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study of Drug for AIDS-Related Illness Discontinued</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sponsors of a study into treating AIDS-related
complex with an experimental drug called Ampligen have stopped the
research, citing disappointing results.
   Ampligen failed to show any advantage over a placebo that would
justify continuing the research, the sponsors said.
   Some 330 patients had been enrolled at 11 centers in the United
States for the study, sponsored as a joint venture by HEM Research
Inc. of Philadelphia and E.I. Du Pont de Nemours & Co. of
Wilmington, Del.
   The end of the experiment was announced Thursday. HEM said it
plans to study Ampligen further for its effect against the AIDS
virus, cancer and other diseases.
   Symptoms of AIDS-related complex, called ARC, are often less
severe than those of acquired immune deficiency syndome. Symptoms
can include loss of appetite, weight loss, fever, night sweats and
swollen lymph nodes.
</TEXT>
