<HEAD>Irish Leader Hospitalized with Lung Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey was
hospitalized Friday with a lung infection, his fourth hospital
visit in eight days, the government said.
   Haughey, 63, was taken to the private wing of the Mater Hospital
from his Dublin home and is expected to spend several days
receiving treatment for ``a severe respiratory infection,'' said
spokeswoman Jackie Coogan.
   No other details on the illness were released.
   Haughey left the hospital Thursday after receiving treatment for
recurring pain from a kidney stone. He also was treated for the
same ailment last weekend and on Oct. 6, the spokeswoman said.
   A Cabinet meeting in Dublin was canceled, she said.
   Haughey heads the Fianna Fail party and was elected to his third
term as Taoiseach, or prime minister, in February 1987.
   He first became prime minister in December 1979, replacing Jack
Lynch, who retired. He lost an election in 1981, was voted back in
for a nine-month term in 1982, and lost another election that year
which left him in the opposition until he defeated Garret
FitzGerald and his Fine Gael party last year.
