<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolPicket     10-14 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Picket,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Return After Picketing Over String Of Temporary Teachers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEARLINGTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven students returned to a
seventh grade class Friday after a four-day boycott and picketing
to demand assignment of a permanent teacher to end a string of
substitutes and temporaries.
   On Thursday, teacher Thad Williams had only one student for his
first day at Charles B. Murphy Elementary School. The other 27
either picketed outside the Hancock County school board offices or
stayed home.
   ``They're confusing us because one teacher comes and tells us
one thing, then another comes and tells us something else,''
student Ronnell Randle said.
   The class has had only one English test and two science tests
this year and only one homework assignment, said student Daniel
McGuire.
   ``The substitutes just make us write the chapter, copy the book.
How can you learn, writing the book?'' Jamie Bennett asked.
   Cheryl Bennett, one of about five parents who marched with the
youngsters, said more students would have picketed had they been
able to get transportation.
   ``It's been seven weeks,'' she said. ``Nine-week tests are
coming up. If they're going to give the kids grades, they're going
to have to have papers at home to justify the grades.''
   She said school officials ``have never contacted us to try to
work it out. We never received any information saying `We're trying
to get you a teacher. We're having trouble.'''
   Bennett said the students returned Friday because they were
willing to give Williams a chance. ``We don't want to make a
spectacle. We just want to make a point,'' she said.
   School Superintendent Terrell Randolph said six teachers had
left Charles B. Murphy this year for various reasons, and the
seventh grade teacher moved to eighth grade. He said a new seventh
grade teacher was employed but had problems obtaining certification
for that grade level.
   He said a certified teacher was then hired, evaluated and let
go. In the interim, substitute teachers have been used.
   Randolph said Williams, a certified teacher with a master's
degree in elementary education, will be paid as a substitute until
he is evaluated sometime next week to determine if he can keep the
job.
   He said he had searched nearby Mississippi and Louisiana school
districts for qualified teachers, but not many wanted to commute to
Pearlington, on the Gulf Coast.
   He said others weren't interested in a job that required
teaching math, English, science and social studies in a
self-contained classroom. In larger schools, seventh and eighth
grades are departmentalized, with different teachers teaching
different subjects.
   Bennett said she understands the district's problems.
   ``But that's not our problem. Our problems are our kids. That's
why these people are elected by us, why they're paid good salaries.
We just want what every other school in Hancock County has,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
