<DOCNO> AP881014-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Baseball Bjt   10-14 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Baseball, Bjt,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Baseball-Crazy Nicaragua, Joy Over `Guerrillas' _ The LA
Dodgers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington and Managua may be at odds,
but how important can that be when the Los Angeles Dodgers _
described here admiringly as ``a bunch of guerrillas'' _ have made
it to the World Series?
   Come October, ``beisbol''-crazed Nicaraguans think more about
the arms in the bullpen than the arms to the Contras.
   ``Baseball defeated the ideologies,'' said Juan Navarro, sports
editor of the opposition daily La Prensa.
   Hundreds of Nicaraguans packed bars at tourist hotels during the
American and National League playoffs, paying about $14 _ almost
the equivalent of a monthly minimum wage _ for three drinks and the
right to sit and watch satellite transmissions on a large screen.
   When the New York Mets' Howard Johnson looked at a called third
strike from the Orel Hershiser on Wednesday night to end the
National League playoffs, Nicaraguans shouted approval in sympathy
with the underdog.
   ``Latins have always liked the Dodgers because the Dodgers have
always had Latin players,'' Navarro said. ``Besides, they always
played the Yankees.''
   The regular anti-U.S. tone of newspapers changes during the
postseason play in ``El Norte.''
   Barricada, the government newspaper, had a one-word headline to
explain the the Dodgers' triumph: ``Guts.''
   Barricada sports editor Edgardo Tijerino wrote that the win over
the Mets by Tommy Lasorda's gang ``ratifies the greatness of
baseball where everything is possible, including having an apparent
flyweight beat a heavyweight.''
   Local columnists write about the Dodgers, Mets, Athletics and
Red Sox with authority.
   One writer, reflecting on a subject Nicaraguans are familiar
with, called the Dodgers ``a bunch of guerrillas.''
   The Sandinista government started as a guerrilla movement that
overthrew dictator Anastasio Somoza in 1979; since then, the United
States has supported Contra guerrillas who want to overthrow the
Sandinistas.
   Baseball arrived in Nicaragua in 1891 and grew in the early part
of the century, boosted by the presence for many years of the
Marines during the many U.S. interventions in Nicaragua.
   Nicaragua has hundreds of amateur teams and an organized
national baseball league. The championship in April pitted a team
from the English-speaking and often rebellious east coast against a
Sandinista army team from the capital of Managua.
   The army team, supported by members of the Sandinista party
directorate, came back from a 3-1 deficit to win in seven.
   One of the most tragic moments in the American film ``Under
Fire,'' which depicted the triumph of the Sandinistas in 1979, came
when an aspiring pitcher turned grenade-thrower is killed by an
American mercenary.
   Baseball fanaticism doesn't stop at the border. Only last month
a U.S. philanthropist delivered a load of vital supplies to
Nicaraguan refugees who have fled to Honduras: bats, balls and
gloves.
   Several Nicaraguans have made it to the majors; the best known
currently is pitcher Dennis Martinez of the Montreal Expos.
   An economic crisis and a U.S. embargo make seeing the playoffs
in Nicaragua difficult, but not impossible. International hotels
pick up the television picture with satellite dishes for their
closed circuit transmissions.
   The high cost of TV rights and problems caused by the U.S.
embargo rule out general television broadcasts, but correspondents
stationed in the hotels relay play-by-play and color commentary in
Spanish on at least four radio stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1241EDT</FILEID>
