<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0617 10-14 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0617,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Winds Up Conservative Convention Looking To The 1990s</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The delegates...' to CORRECT name of anthem.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher,
winding up the annual conference of her Conservative Party, today
pledged she will be as staunch an ally to the new American
president as she has been to Ronald Reagan.
   She was speaking in a keynote address received with thunderous
applause and chants of ``10 More Years,'' from the 4,500 delegates.
   Mrs. Thatcher also urged Britons to maintain a ``generous
society'' _ in what was widely seen as an initiative on social
issues following nearly a decade of her right-wing economic
policies.
   Millions of Britons have become richer as a result of Thatcher's
policies, but unemployment has more than doubled, and critics
charge she has encouraged a materialistic, greedy and uncaring
society.
   At the end of the 45-minute address, delegates waved Union Jacks
and the blue flag of the Conservative Party as the convention
center in this south England resort echoed with more chants of ``10
More Years.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, 63, flanked by the party hierarchy, declared:
``The Conservative Party occupies the common ground of British
politics ... And so it has fallen to us to lead Britain into the
1990s. And, who knows, beyond.''
   The delegates joined in a traditional chorus of the national
anthem, ``God Save The Queen,'' and the favorite Tory anthem,
``Land of Hope and Glory.''
   On Britain's particularly close relationship with the United
States in the 1980s while she and Reagan have been in office, Mrs.
Thatcher said Reagan ``has rebuilt the strength and confidence of
the West _ not without a little help _ and inspired the democracies
to go out and win the battle of ideas.''
   ``It is vital that Britain and America should always stand
together. So the next president of the United States too will have
the United Kingdom as a staunch ally.''
   On social issues, Mrs. Thatcher said her economic policies were
encouraging not greed but ``the best in human nature.''
   She urged Britons to give more to charity, assist in crime
prevention and promised new efforts to preserve the environment.
   ``The fact is that prosperity has created not the selfish
society but the generous society,'' said Mrs. Thatcher.
   She also said the founding concept of the European Economic
Community was ``under attack from those who see European unity as a
vehicle for spreading socialism.''
   Referring to a speech last month in which she ruled out a united
states of Europe and stressed the separate identities of the 12 EEC
countries, Mrs. Thatcher said it stirred criticism because ``it
wasn't at all convenient for those who want to bring about a
federal Europe by stealth.''
   ``We haven't worked all these years to free Britain from the
paralysis of socialism only to see it creep through the back door
of central control and bureacracy from Brussels,'' she said of the
EEC headquarters in the Belgian capital.
   Mrs. Thatcher's domestic theme of civic responsibility in the
keynote speech reflected official anxiety about rising crime,
including street violence and hooliganism by soccer fans, in a
period of growing prosperity.
   On Thursday, Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, the
treasury chief, said the government was determined to hold down
spending, a cornerstone of Mrs. Thatcher's policy.
   With inflation up to 5.7 percent and rising, Lawson in his
address avoided a timetable for a government pledge to cut basic
income tax from 25 to 20 percent. He promised tax cuts ``when
prudent'' and forecast a drop next year in inflation.
   Despite signs of trouble in an economy where earlier tax cuts
and huge borrowing by consumers has fueled growth, Mrs. Thatcher
retains a comfortable lead in polls over the opposition Labor Party.
   Labor, which held its annual conference last week, is tussling
with a policy overhaul aimed at moderating its left-wing platform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0623 10-14 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0623,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Cabinet Dominated by Commmunist Party Members</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `However, Radowski...' to CORRECT spelling to
Rakowski.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament approved a new
communist-dominated Cabinet today that failed, according to Prime
Minister Mieczyslaw Rakowski, to broaden the base of the government
by including opposition members.
   However, Rakowski insisted that Poland will be able to achieve
political reform without participation of the banned trade union
Solidarity.
   ``I don't limit democratization to the recognition of
Solidarity. I don't think that the restoration of Solidarity may be
proof of the fact that our country is becoming more democratic,''
he said at his first news conference as prime minister.
   ``I think the democratic processes which are being implemented
in Poland for several years now are accelerating at present, and it
is all happening without the participation of Solidarity,''
Rakowski said.
   Rakowski made his remarks at a 90-minute session broadcast live
on national radio just after Poland's parliament, the Sejm,
approved the new Cabinet by a 363-1 vote.
   A new generation of young party members Rakowski nominated
Thursday assumed posts to oversee economic affairs, but senior
communist party members retained the key interior, defense and
foreign ministers.
   Andrzej Wroblewski, 38, became the head of the important
Ministry of Finance and Dominik Jastrzebski, 46, took charge of the
Ministry of Foreign Economic Cooperation.
   Mieczyslaw Wilczek, a wealthy private businessman, who is also a
communist party member, assumes the post of Minister of Industry.
   Rakowski reserved four spots in his government for what he
termed the ``constructive opposition,'' but said the unidentified
candidates for the posts have turned them down.
   On Thursday, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said whether the
opposition accepts the posts depends on whether the government
could bring about change and accept the banned union.
   The Cabinet changes are aimed at ending a political and economic
crisis in Poland, with an annual inflation rate of 60 percent.
   Rakowski bumped several senior officials responsible for the
government's failing economic reform program. Deputy Prime Minister
Czeslaw Sadowski, the economic planning chief and Deputy Prime
Minister Zbigniew Szalajda, the industry chief, lost their jobs.
   Rakowski proposed nine new ministers. Five belong to the ruling
Polish United Workers' Party, or communist party, one is from the
Peasants' Party, and two are from the Democratic Party. Both
parties are allies of the communist party.
   Izabela Planeta-Malecka, the designated minister of health and
social policy, was the only non-party member and only woman
nominated.
   Rakowski had proposed the four opposition members, who he didn't
name, as deputy premier, minister of labor and social policy,
undersecretary in the Housing Ministry, and a newly created post as
minister without portfolio in charge of contacts with various
communities.
   In his speech Thursday, Rakowski said he hoped coming talks
between the government and the opposition, including Walesa, could
lead to change.
   ``We approach it with the best of will. We are aiming for
reasonable compromise which would ensure the maximum of possible
change,'' he said.
   Authorities promised the talks following widespread strikes in
August, Poland's worst labor unrest in seven years.
   The talks, to begin next week, will discuss the political and
economic crisis and consider the future of Solidarity, which was
the Soviet bloc's only recognized trade union until it was
suppressed in 1981 and banned in 1982.
   U.S. Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead, at the end of
a three-day visit to Poland, today urged patience in the talks and
said he hoped they would lead to the relegalization of Solidarity.
   Rakowski, former party propaganda chief, was approved Sept. 27
to replace Zbigniew Messner, whose Cabinet resigned Sept. 19 after
fierce criticism for mishandling the party-approved economic reform
program. It was the first time the entire government stepped down
in postwar Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
