<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru   10-14 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0589,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks for Hostage Release in Recess, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 5 grafs at bottom with U.S. denial.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported today that teams
representing the United States and Iran have recessed talks aimed
at releasing American hostages in Lebanon because of news leaks
about the negotiations.
   But The Nation, a new English-language weekly that has run
several articles on the subject, said ``skeleton delegations''
remained in Switzerland ready to resume talks.
   The United States has denied repeatedly that any official
negotiations are under way with Iran to try to secure freedom for
nine Americans held hostage in Lebanon by Iranian-backed Shiite
Moslems.
   The nine are among 14 foreigners missing in Lebanon. The longest
held is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   This month, Indian professor Mithileshwar Singh was freed by his
Shiite captors. Singh, a legal resident of the United States, was
kidnapped 20 months earlier with three American professors who
remain in capitivity.
   ``Leaders of the U.S. and Iranian negotiating teams returned
home for consultations this week, leaving skeleton delegations
ready to resume contacts,'' The Nation said.
   It added: ``The delay in resumption of negotiations is
attributed partly to the reports on the talks.''
   The recess came after the talks ``reached a crucial phase''
following Singh's release, the paper said. It did not elaborate.
   The paper also quoted an unidentified Iranian diplomat in Geneva
as saying Iran has been disappointed with the U.S. stance in the
talks.
   ``All the U.S. and Britain are offering to date is long-term aid
for restoring Iran's war-damaged economy and only through a
friendly Third World nation,'' the diplomat was quoted as saying.
   In its first story on the reported talks two weeks earlier, The
Nation said the United States struck a secret deal with Iran,
promising economic aid, renewal of arms sales, the release of
billions of dollars of frozen Iranian assets in U.S. banks and
resumption of diplomatic relations.
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals held by
pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists _ Anglican envoy Terry Waite,
journalist John McCarthy and teacher Brian Keenan, a Belfast man
with dual British and Irish nationality whose release is also
sought by the Irish government.
   The British Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec
Collett, a New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian
abductors claim they killed him. His body was never found.
   At the White House today, presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater again denied that negotiations with Iran were taking
place.
   ``No one is authorized to talk for the (U.S.) government. No one
is authorized to negotiate for the government,'' he said.
   ``As we have said before, there are all kinds of people around
the world free-lancing on this situation,'' he said. Fitzwater also
predicted there would be more such stories, although he did not say
why.
   ``Suffice it to say, we find them (the news reports) mostly
detrimental,'' he said. ``What they do is build up people's
expectations when they are not warranted.''
   ``We think they are very counterproductive in terms of getting
the hostages out,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
