<HEAD>PLO Advised To Hold New Initiatives For After Israeli Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union convinced PLO officials they
should wait until after the Israeli elections to declare a
Palestinian state and government or they would hurt chances for
peace, a newspaper reported.
   The French daily Le Monde said the Soviets told Palestinian
leaders that making their move before the Nov. 1 vote could benefit
candidates of the Israeli right.
   The officials met with Mahmoud Abbas, a member of the Palestine
Liberation Organization executive committee, on Monday and Tuesday
in Moscow, Le Monde said in a report published Thursday.
   Also Thursday, the United Arab Emirates newspaper Al-Ittihad
quoted Yassir Ahd-Rabbo, head of the PLO information department, as
saying the Palestine National Council will meet Oct. 31 to declare
the independent state. The PNC is the PLO's parliament in exile.
   Soviet officials said before the Israeli elections, the PNC
should set out a political manifesto on the recognition of Israel,
Le Monde said.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass reported Tuesday that
Soviet officials told Abbas it was time to take ``concrete steps
founded equally on the interests of all concerned parties, such as
those that were outlined by Mikhail Gorbachev in his meeting last
April with Yasser Arafat,'' according to Le Monde.
   In that meeting, President Gorbachev told the PLO leader that
recognition of Israel and the self-determination of the Palestinian
people were inseparable and were indispensable to the peaceful
solution to the conflict in the Middle East, Le Monde said.
   PLO officials have said Egypt and the Soviet Union were advising
the PLO to wait to launch any new initiatives until after Nov. 8,
when both Israeli and American elections will be over.
