<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Book     10-14 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Book,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Rules Out Lifting Ban On ``The Satanic Verses''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi on Friday
ruled out the idea of lifting a ban on the book ``The Satanic
Verses,'' saying he supports free expression but not if it insults
others, a news report said.
   Gandhi was responding to protests of his government's banning of
Salman Rushdie's latest novel. The book has been nominated for
Britain's highest literary award, the Booker Prize.
   The United News of India quoted Gandhi as saying he had not read
it and would not reply to a letter from Rushdie urging Gandhi to
end the ban. The prime minister spoke to reporters while touring
four flooded states in northern India.
   Rushdie, 41, is a British citizen of Indian descent and lives in
London. He won the Booker Prize, Britain's most prestigious
literary award, for his first book, ``Midnight's Children,'' a
broad satire on India after independence. His second novel,
``Shame'' also earned him acclaim.
   On Oct. 5, the Finance Ministry barred importation of the novel
or sale of it within India.
   Moslems, including members of Parliament, said they feared
Moslem militants might use the book to incite riots.
   According to UNI, Gandhi told reporters the ban was imposed
because the government believed the book might hurt the feelings of
Moslems, who make up 11 percent of India's 880 million people.
   UNI quoted Gandhi as saying that his government supports press
freedom, but that this does not warrant encroachment on sentiments
of certain communities.
   If writers do not show adequate restraint, he said, the
government must take measures ``which we generally do not want to
take,'' UNI said.
   Rushdie, a non-practicing Moslem, is sharply critical of
religious fundamentalism and makes thinly veiled references in the
book to the prophet Mohammed and the Koran.
   In his letter, which was published on the front pages of major
Indian dailies Thursday, Rushdie accused Gandhi of denying him the
right to free expression at the behest of religious zealots.
   Indian newspapers have been particularly outspoken in opposing
the ban.
   Even the Times of India, which usually supports the government,
said in an editorial today that the demand for the ban was
unjustified.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' was published Sept. 22 in Britain and is
scheduled to be published in the United States in February.
</TEXT>
