<HEAD>Yale Gets 50 Gandhi Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty letters and post cards written by
Mahatma Gandhi to a student he grew to treat like a daughter have
been donated to Yale University.
   The letters and cards were the gift of Vijayaben M. Pancholi,
who began writing to Gandhi in 1935. Gandhi took her in as a
student at his ashram after several years of correspondence.
   Pravin N. Bhatt, a senior research virologist at the Yale
Medical School and a friend of Vijayaben and her husband, Manubhai,
is translating the volume into English from Gujarati, a language
spoken in western India.
   Gandhi, who advocated passive resistance, led the struggle for
India's independence from Britain.
   The letters ``are not political. They give insight into Gandhi
as a human being writing to a daughter about day-to-day things,''
Bhatt said. ``It is the story of how he took in a girl he hardly
knew and accepted her as his daughter for life.''
