<HEAD>Sonic Booms Shake Foundation Of Historic Fort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fort Jefferson, a hexagonal, 140-year-old
fort 70 miles offshore in the Florida Straits, never faced enemy
attack but its caretakers say it is fighting a losing battle with
the U.S. Navy.
   For about two weeks, sonic booms from jet fighters on maneuvers
from the Key West Naval Air Station have rattled windows and
dislodged bricks at the fort, said Mike Finley, superintendent of
Fort Jefferson and Everglades National Park.
   Despite threats of legal action by Finley and several pleas from
Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., to reroute the flights, the Navy has no
immediate plans to alter the flight exercises.
   Capt. William Denning, head of air station at Boca Chica, said
the weather is ideal for fighter training and the fort is in the
station's radar tracking zone.
   ``The Navy is not being cavalier or thumbing our noses at what's
going on with Fort Jefferson,'' Denning said. ``We try not to go
supersonic any more than we have to.''
