<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HijackingSuspect     10-14 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says Accused Hijacker's Confession Valid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors may use a suspected Lebanese
terrorist's confession as evidence when he stands trial on charges
of leading a 1985 airline hijacking in the Middle East, a federal
appeals court ruled Friday.
   A three-judge appeals panel reversed the decision of a lower
court judge that the FBI had illegally obtained the signed
confession from Fawaz Younis about the June 11, 1985, hijacking of
a Royal Jordanian airliner.
   Younis was arrested Sept. 13, 1987, after being lured aboard an
FBI-chartered yacht off Cyprus by the prosepct of making a drug
deal. He is awaiting trial in U.S. District Court on charges he led
a group of five men who hijacked the airliner in Beirut.
   The appeals panel said it found no evidence to support U.S.
District Judge Barrington D. Parker's finding that Younis'
recurrent bouts of seasickness had impaired his understanding when
he was advised by the FBI of his right to remain silent.
   The panel rejected as ``clearly erroneous'' Parker's finding
that during the interrogation sessions aboard a Navy ship, Younis
suffered ``throbbing and numbing'' pain from wrists that were
fractured when FBI agents slammed him to the deck of the yacht.
   ``The interrogation of Younis hardly qualifies as a model for
law enforcement behavior,'' Circuit Judge Abner Mikva wrote for the
panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here. ``But the
Constitution does not require picture-perfect routines.''
   ``Younis' physical circumstances at the time that he waived his
Miranda rights may well have been uncomfortable, and his sudden
arrest no doubt took him by surprise,'' the court said.
   ``The FBI agents might well have used less force in arresting
Younis (so as not to have fractured his wrists); they could have
also been more solicitous of Younis' welfare following arrest (for
example by giving him medication against nausea right away).
   ``But discomfort and surprise, by themselves, have never
sufficed to render a waiver unknowing and involuntary _ provided
that police administer proper warnings and do not engage in
intimidation, coercion or deception,'' Mikva said in an opinion
joined by Circuit Judges James L. Buckley and Douglas H. Ginsburg.
   Parker, who sharply criticized the FBI's tactics, had suppressed
the confession as evidence last February, prompting an appeal by
federal prosecutors that has delayed the trial, now scheduled to
begin Nov. 14.
   The appeals court concluded that the FBI properly advised Younis
of his constitutional rights under the procedure mandated by the
Supreme Court's landmark Miranda decision in 1966.
   Each time Younis complained of seasickness, the interrogation
was stopped so the suspect could rest, the court noted.
   ``Younis not only said that he understood the warnings and
agreed to waive the rights contained therein but proceeded to
recount his participation in the hijacking,'' the court said.
   ``Assessing the totality of the circumstances, we cannot
conclude that Younis' waiver was invalid,'' the court said.
   Following his arrest aboard the yacht, Younis was transferred to
the USS Butte, on which he was interrogated during a four-day
voyage before he was flown to Washington.
   Younis, a former member of the Shiite Amal militia, is accused
of leading the group of five men who stormed the Royal Jordanian
airliner with AK-47 assault rifles at Beirut International Airport.
   The hijackers forced the airliner to fly to several locations in
the Mediterranean, including Cyprus and Sicily, before the plane
returned to Beirut 30 hours later.
   After the airliner's 74 passengers and crew members were
released, the hijackers blew up the plane on the runway.
   Besides the confession, federal prosecutors have a videotape of
a man identified as Younis reading a statement to reporters at the
airport. The tape shows the plane being blown up in the background.
   The hijackers, seeking to force the Arab League to remove
Palestinian refugees from Lebanon, ordered the plane to fly to
Tunis, Tunisia, where the organization was meeting. Tunisian
authorities refused to allow the plane to land there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0149 </DOCNO>
