<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--MoneyPipe     10-14 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Money Pipe,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carbondale Police Blow Up `Bomb' Full Of Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bits of $10 and $20 bills fluttered
through the air when authorities, suspecting they had found bombs,
blew up a piece of pipe that turned out to be filled with money.
   ``I think there was several people there that were quite
surprised,'' police spokesman Neal Jacobson said Friday of
Thursday's incident.
   An arson team found two sealed metal tubes, about 18 inches long
and capped on both ends, while investigating a house fire. One of
the tubes contained several hundred dollars, said another police
spokesman, Art Wright.
   ``These had the appearance and dimensions to make people think
they were a bomb when in fact they weren't,'' Jacobson said. ``Our
concern was safety of people and property first.''
   Police summoned an Army bomb squad, which used explosives to
destroy the tubes.
   Wright said the pipes apparently were left behind by a previous
resident of the house.
</TEXT>
