<DOCNO> AP881014-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Advantage Bjt   10-14 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Advantage, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Comeback Could Be Tough During Structured Final Weeks</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With just three and a half weeks to go until
the presidential election, Democrat Michael Dukakis may have lost
his last best chance to overtake Vice President George Bush.
   The opportunities and potential surprises of the debates are
over, and the 1988 campaign entered its final phase on Friday with
the guideposts from now until Election Day clearly marked.
   From now on, campaign packaging will assert an even stronger
hold, with schedules and rhetoric more tightly controlled than
before _ and that should benefit Bush and make it even harder for
Dukakis to find an opening to turn the tide of the campaign.
   Even Dukakis' people conceded after Thursday's encounter at UCLA
that the Massachusetts governor did not deliver the leveling blow
that some had hoped for.
   ``We didn't expect a knockout. What we expected was a strong
effort,'' said campaign manager Susan Estrich.
   But whether that effort will be enough to make much difference
in the dwindling days remaining, for a campaign that has been
lagging in the polls since late August, seemed questionable.
   The vice president _ described by aide Sheila Tate as ``good at
dodging and weaving'' _ might have gloated that Dukakis didn't lay
a glove on him, the phrase he had used after his on-air spat with
CBS' Dan Rather last winter.
   Instead, Bush merely said he was ``very happy about the way
things went.'' He had aides pronounce the victory for him.
   For Bush, the stakes weren't as high as for Dukakis in
Thursday's jousting; he only had to avoid making serious mistakes.
   Most analysts seemed to agree that Bush looked more comfortable,
Dukakis stiffer in the final debate, with no major gaffes on either
side.
   For his part, Dukais was supposed to try to look warmer, more
human.
   And, in fact, both candidates seemed to be seeking
less-negative, more-open images _ although Bush aides denied that
Dukakis had scored many points in the Miss Congeniality contest.
   ``I think I'm a reasonably likable guy,'' Dukakis told an
audience estimated at a bit more than 60 million. ``But I'm also a
serious guy. I think the presidency of the United States is a very
serious office.''
   Bush, who polls show has overcome most of the earlier perception
of him as being aloof and ``wimpish,'' had his own words on the
issue of likability.
   ``I don't think it's a question of whether people like you or
not to make you an effective leader. I think it's whether you share
the broad dreams of the American people. I think it's a question of
values, not likability or lovability.''
   Bush aides before the debate said they expected some kind of
surprise assault from the Democrat. But it never materialized.
   And what may have been Dukakis' harshest thrust, his criticism
of Republican running mate Sen. Dan Quayle, who polls have shown is
hurting the GOP ticket, brought what may have been a neutralizing
parry from Bush.
   ``I've never seen a campaign where a presidential nominee runs
against my vice presidential nominee,'' he said.
   From now on, Dukakis will have to look even harder for something
dramatic to turn around his campaign in a year in which even Bush
contends political activity so far has generated ``more heat than
light.''
   With no more debates planned, and with polls suggesting Bush is
in good shape to win an Electoral-College majority, Dukakis' work
appears to be cut out for him.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the Bush campaign for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
