<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Elections     10-14 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Elections,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Election Official Bans Party Ad Featuring Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign commercial featuring an interview
with PLO leader Yasser Arafat was banned Friday by an election
official on the grounds it violated anti-terrorism laws, the
producer of the advertisement said.
   The two-minute commercial for the left-wing Progressive List for
Peace shows Arafat saying: ``I accept (Israel's) international
legitimacy.... I accept U.N. resolutions 242 and 338.''
   Israel has said it will not negotiate with the PLO unless it
accepts the two U.N. resolutions, which recognize the Jewish
state's sovereignty and call for Israel to withdraw from territory
occupied in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The Progressive List for Peace will appeal the decision to the
Supreme Court on Sunday, party spokesman Adam Keller said.
   ``It's nonsense to say that showing a Palestinian speaking about
peace violates a law against terrorism,'' Keller said, noting that
the right-wing Likud party was permitted to use an ad showing a
1970 film of Arafat with a machine gun.
   ``It's unreasonable that the Likud can show him as a war-monger
and we can't show the other side of the coin,'' Keller said. ``We
had hoped to break the monstrous image given to the PLO by the
official propaganda in Israel.''
   Israel's law against terrorism forbids public identification
with a terrorist organization.
   Under Israeli election laws, all campaign commercials must be
approved for airing by the Central Elections Committee. The
committee has representatives of all parties, but its chairman,
always a Supreme Court judge, rules on the ads.
   Eyal Sivan, the commercial's producer, said he was told by the
office of Judge Eliezer Goldberg, the committee chairman, that
portions of the ad with interviews of Arafat and other PLO members
were banned.
   Sivan said the party will air the ad Saturday night with all but
the last 30 seconds blacked out.
   ``From our point of view, this is more proof that Israeli
officials are not interested in peace with the Palestinian
people,'' Sivan said.
   Keller said the commercial, which shows a closeup of Arafat
sitting on a sofa, was taped a few weeks ago but he would not say
where.
   The ad also quotes Khaled El Hassan, a member of the PLO's
parliament-in-exile, as saying: ``We don't want to throw anybody
into the sea. ... We want peace.''
   The Progressive List, which currently holds two seats in the
Israeli Parliament, favors negotiations with the PLO and advocates
a withdrawal from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   Israeli policy in the occupied territories, where more than 290
Palestinians have been killed in a 10-month-old uprising, is a key
issue in the Nov. 1 national elections.
   Right-wing parties, lead by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
Likud bloc, are trying to convince the Supreme Court to disqualify
the Progressive List from the elections on grounds it threatens
Israel's existence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
