<DOCNO> AP881014-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Missiles     10-14 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missiles,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Outline Plans for Missile Launcher Destruction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military officials outlined
plans Friday for turning rocket launchers into scrap under the
U.S.-Soviet treaty eliminating intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   Starting Wednesday, torches and electric saws will cut in half
the first nine of the Pershing 2 launchers at a U.S. Army site in
the Hausen section of northwest Frankfurt.
   Work crews will don welding suits and helmets, safety glasses,
leather gloves and safety shoes, said Chief Warrant Officer Richard
Moore.
   U.S. and Soviet experts, wearing hards hats and goggles, will
watch from behind a glassed-in partition about four yards away, the
site supervisor told a news briefing.
   Late Friday, the U.S. European Command in Stuttgart said the
team of Soviet inspectors would arrive in Frankfurt Monday. It did
not say how many Soviets were expected.
   All 114 of the Pershing 2 rocket launchers stationed in West
Germany will be destroyed in Hausen within a three-year period,
said site commander Christopher Evans.
   The launchers themselves are flatbed trucks outfitted with beams
designed to raise the missiles into a vertical position for firing.
The launchers were designed for both transport and firing of the
mobile rockets, and each is about 31 feet long.
   Evans, a civilian employee of the Army, stressed that the
missiles themselves were being taken back to the United States.
   ``I would like to emphasize that this facility has nothing to do
with the actual missile and never has had,'' Evans told reporters
invited to the pre-destruction briefing. ``This facility only works
with the launchers and ground support equipment.''
   Evans said the launchers will be brought one by one into a
covered work area, where the trailer part and the erector mechanism
will be cut in half.
   The work will take about two days for all nine launchers, and
the remains will be taken to a facility in suburban Frankfurt to be
used as scrap metal, he said.
   ``All personnel involved have the proper training and
certification and there is no, I repeat, no adverse environmental
impact,'' Evans said.
   The first nine launchers to be destroyed were stationed at a
base near Stuttgart and were hauled away along with the missiles
Sept. 1. That was the first U.S. missile removal under the
Intermediate-Range Nuclear Force treaty signed by President Reagan
and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in December.
   U.S. officials said in September the remaining 420
intermediate-range U.S. missiles will be removed from Western
Europe over a 36-month period. Of the missiles deployed, 108
Pershing 2 missiles and 96 cruise missiles were stationed at four
bases in West Germany.
   Stationing of the missiles had sparked massive protests in
Western Europe, including a coordinated demonstration in several
cities that drew hundreds of thousands of people to the streets in
October 1983. Deployment of the missiles began the following month.
   The Soviet Union began removing its missiles from Czechoslovakia
and East Germany in February, before the U.S. Senate ratified the
treaty.
   Under the treaty, the Soviet Union and the United States agreed
to eliminate all land-based, intermediate-range nuclear missiles,
which have ranges of 300 to 3,000 miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya     10-14 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moi Marks 10th Anniversary, Warns of Difficult Futur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi on Friday marked
his 10th year in power with a warning that the next decade will
bring population growth certain to strain the nation's resources.
   ``The era of soft options is over,'' said Moi, who became
Kenya's second president in 1978 after the death of his
predecessor, Jomo Kenyatta. Moi was Kenyatta's vice president for
11 years.
   Moi also hinted that the current crackdown on alleged dissidents
will continue.
   ``No government can stay idle when the security of the state is
threatened,'' he said.
   Moi cut into a 10-tiered cake and then spoke at the ceremony
marking the end of a week of celebrations.
   Presidents Siad Barre of Somalia, Ali Hassan Mwinyi of Tanzania,
Joachim Chissano of Mozambique, Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia, Robert
Mugabe of Zimbabwe, and Juvenal Habriyamana of Rwanda were the
principal foreign guests.
   Moi said Kenya's 22 million population will be more than 30
million by 1999. It is the world's fastest growing population, with
an annual growth rate of 3.9 percent.
   ``Let us not be complacent about the implications of these
numbers,'' Moi said. ``They mean we must provide more jobs, more
schools, more hospitals and, above all, more food for this fast
growing population.''
   The economy, Moi said, must continue to grow faster than the
population. The economy is expanding by almost 5 percent annually.
   He promised the government would provide incentives for foreign
investors and streamline laws to make industry profitable, but he
did not elaborate. Foreign investment in Kenya has been declining
since the mid-1970s.
   Moi, however, warned industrialists ``to avoid the temptation of
trying to make quick and unwarranted profits because of the new
policies we are introducing.''
   ``We have no intention of creating a nation of a few Kenyans
amidst a sea of poverty,'' said Moi.
   On the issue of national security, Moi said the country was
ready to meet any challenge to maintain its peace and stability.
   Authorities in the last five weeks have detained four people
under security laws that allow for indefinite imprisonment without
charge or trial.
   Since Aug. 8, four people have been sentenced to seven-year jail
terms after confessing to belonging to groups seeking Moi's ouster.
   The government revealed the existence of the Kenya Revolutionary
Movement and another group, the Kenya Patriotic Front, on Sept. 16.
It claims the core of the Kenya Patriotic Front are former members
of Mwakenya, an underground movement.
   ``Let such people make no mistake, for we shall meet their
challenge with all the appropriate means at our disposal,'' Moi
said.
   Moi delivered his speech after three hours of entertainment that
included a military parade, an air force aerial display,
traditional dance troupes, and songs by children born Oct. 14,
1978, the day Moi was sworn in for his first full term.
   The government built a $950,000 monument downtown to mark the
10th anniversary of Moi's rule.
</TEXT>
