<HEAD>Soviet Official Expelled for Spying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has expelled a member of
the Soviet trade delegation who was suspected of industrial
espionage, the Foreign Ministry said Friday.
   The Soviet delegate left last week, said ministry spokesman
Martin Hallqvist. He declined to identify him.
   ``He tried to get information about Swedish and foreign economic
and industrial conditions,'' the spokesman said.
   No further information was released on the delegate's
activities, but Hallqvist said he was caught before Swedish
interests could be harmed.
   Since spring 1987, the government has granted visas to 10 Soviet
and Eastern European diplomats who were indentified by the Swedish
security police as intelligence officers, the national news agency
TT said.
