<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PaloAltoShooting     10-14 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palo Alto Shooting,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worker Shots Two Supervisors, Kills Himself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city electrician with a history of
emotional problems walked into a work meeting today with a gun and
shot two of his supervisors, then shot and killed himself, police
and colleagues said.
   Vladimir `Walter' Kozubov, who worked for the city since Oct.
15, 1979, had threatened in the past to shoot up his office, a
co-worker said. He had recently returned from a leave of absence
and seemed upset over job-related situations, colleagues said.
   The wounded men were identified as Tom Darden and Richard
Pennock. Stanford Hospital spokesman Karl Knapper said one man was
in critical condition and undergoing surgery, while the other was
in guarded condition.
   City electrical assistant Ken Schwab told the Palo Alto Times
Tribune that he and about nine other electrical substation workers
sat down at about 6:50 a.m. to discuss morning assignments when
Kozubov came in with a small-caliber handgun and began shooting.
   ``I got under the table as fast as I could. As soon as I saw
Walter hit the ground, I got out and called the police,'' Schwab
said.
   Schwab stood outside the fenced-in control center trying to calm
coworkers, including one with bloodstains on his shoes and jeans.
   ``I am just glad I wasn't in the line of fire,'' he said. ``I
think it will all sink in later.''
   Debra D'Alessandro, an electrical department employee, said she
was walking into the center when somebody stopped her. ``They said,
`Don't go in there, Vlad has a gun and he is going nuts,'''
Alessandro said. She said Kozubov had made threats in the past.
   ``He had not threatened with a gun before, but he has threatened
that he would come out and shoot up the place,'' she said.
   Bob Britton, field representative for the Service Employees
International Union that represents the electrical workers, said he
had been trying to help Kozubov work things out.
   ``He had a temper,'' Britton said. ``I was trying to get him to
work on his temper, trying to get him to use the union to deal with
his problems.''
   Britton said Kozubov took a two-month leave of absence a year
ago.
   Schwab said Kozubov had been back to work about a month, ``but
he still seemed agitated about something.''
</TEXT>
