<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-14 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It isn't kosher for police to deny Effie
Sharabi a permit to sell his hot dogs on the streets of San
Francisco, the Israeli immigrant is telling City Hall.
   ``In the summertime, there are so many Jewish tourists, and
there is no place to get a kosher meal,'' Sharabi said.
   The Police Permit Bureau, however, noted that an ordinance bars
a pushcart within two blocks of a restaurant that sells similar
food.
   ``Our contention is that a hot dog is a hot dog is a hot dog,''
said Lt. Harlan Wilson, commanding officer of the permit bureau.
``What if a Roman Catholic priest walks by, throws holy water on
(hot dogs) and calls them holy dogs?''
   Sharabi said he'll go before the Board of Permit Appeals on Nov.
14, flanked by a lawyer and two rabbis. His opponents not only
include the police, but some neighborhood merchants.
   Jill Hollander, whose Findley's Fabulous Fudge on Geary Street
would be a knish-throw from the pushcart, said the smell of hog
dogs outside her place would repel fudge lovers.
   Sharabi allowed that he might lose his kosher crusade, but he
added that he intends to give it a good try.
   ``What can it hurt?'' he shrugged.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   That wasn't an unidentified flying object
in the sky, just Wolf's Furniture store on the ground.
   State police in Greensburg and others said they received several
calls Thursday night about bright beams of light darting across the
sky near U.S. 30 in Hempfield Township.
   Stan Gordon, a member of the Pennsylvania Society for the Study
of the Unexplained, said many who called him thought they had seen
