<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1984, Democratic vice presidential
nominee Geraldine Ferraro explained about ``those Italian men.''
Now one of the best known, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, may have
turned the tables.
   While introducing Cuomo at a Democratic fund-raiser Thursday
evening, former Monroe County Democratic Chairman Mike Miller noted
that two years ago a magazine had proclaimed the New York governor,
at age 54, among the country's 10 sexiest men.
   Miller, 49, said that ``honor'' was inspiring to all men who
were approaching that age. The governor said he saw things somewhat
differently.
   ``I've been married to a Sicilian for 34 years,'' Cuomo told
several hundred people at the crowded cocktail reception. ``And
when you've been married to a Sicilian for 34 years, you're not
talking about being sexy. You talk about survival.''
   The parents of Matilda Cuomo, the governor's wife, are from
Sicily.
   Later, on a flight back to Albany, Cuomo said he had meant it
all in jest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KAMPSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike and Debi Herren wanted to be
farmers, but were looking to raise ``something different and
something simple that would allow us to get on our feet.''
   They settled on snails, or ``escargot'' if you meet one in a
French restaurant.
   The Herrens, both 26, also tend buffalo on their 176-acre farm.
   Raising snails in Illinois is tricky because of the weather,
Herren said.
   ``Cold weather is the biggest problem,'' he said. ``In
California they can be raised in the open or in greenhouses, but
here you can't do that.''
   The Herrens raise their snails in a limestone basement of a
farmhouse where they can keep the temperature constant. ``Between
70 and 80 degrees is the optimum temperature,'' he said.
   ``Snails are deaf and blind, but need sunlight to reproduce,''
Herren said. Artificial light, fortunately, also gets their juices
flowing.
   ``The snails have been a piece of cake,'' Herren says. ``Well,
maybe I shouldn't say that because we both grew up on farms and so
we're used to working hard.''
</TEXT>
