<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Bomb     10-14 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Bomb,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Injured As Bomb Explodes in Downtown Johannesburg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in a concrete
trash bin at a downtown bus station Friday evening, hurling
shrapnel that injured four people, police said.
   The 6:30 p.m. blast damaged two cars and a bus, shattered nearby
shop windows, and wrecked a bus inspector's office at the Van der
Bijl Plaza bus station, said police spokesman Col. Frans Malherbe.
   On Sept. 20, a bomb at the bus station injured 19 people.
   There have been more than 150 bombings in South Africa since a
national state of emergency was declared June 12, 1986. More than
30 people have died and more than 600 have been injured.
   The bombings have increased recently, with an average of nearly
one a day since the beginning of September.
   The government says the outlawed African National Congress is
waging a bombing campaign leading up to the municipal elections for
segregated local councils on Oct. 26. But there have also been an
increasing number of attacks and bombings of anti-apartheid
organizations which the ANC has blamed on the government's security
forces.
</TEXT>
