<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALAMOSA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire Malcolm S. Forbes was
formally dressed in the requisite pin-striped suit, but he
approached the question of business success with informal humor and
a bit of irreverence.
   ``If it's not too late, pick out parents who are in business,''
Forbes told students at Adams State College Thursday. ``So when
they die ... then you're in business.''
   Forbes, 69, was at Adams State to collect an honorary degree as
this year's Distinguished Executive in Residence _ a role he
fulfilled with his talk.
   ``I didn't balloon in, but as you'll soon find out, I brought
the hot air with me,'' Forbes said.
   Forbes, editor in chief of the business magazine that bears his
name, has made headlines for everything from escorting actress
Elizabeth Taylor to piloting a hot air balloon into a high-security
Chinese military base.
   In the animated talk to more than 600 people he spoke of the
promise he sees in the decline of communism and the ``breaking out
of peace.''
   ``The American economy is in such extraordinarily good shape
that we can withstand either one of these guys getting elected,''
he said, commenting on presidential candidates Michael Dukakis and
George Bush.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic weightlifting champion Naim
Suleymanoglu was joined in Turkey Friday by his family, which was
finally allowed out of Bulgaria, state radio reported.
   Suleymanoglu, an ethnic Turk, defected to Turkey two years ago.
He won the country's first gold medal in 20 years in the Seoul
Olympics last month, breaking a world record by lifting 342.5
kilograms.
