<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CounterfeitCassettes     10-14 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Counterfeit Cassettes,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI, Police Seize $4.5 Million in Bootleg Music</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents and local authorities seized more
than $4.5 million worth of ``bootleg'' music cassette tapes and
counterfeiting equipment and arrested eight people during a series
of raids.
   The alleged piracy operation was earning $30,000 to $40,000 a
week producing music cassettes, said Lt. Roger Clark of the Los
Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
   The operation was producing an estimated 5,000 tapes a day of
pirated music by such popular recording artists as Bob Dylan,
Jackson Brown, Janet Jackson and the Bangles, officials said.
   The tapes, business records and equipment were confiscated
Thursday in raids in Los Angeles, Fontana, Ontario, Montclair,
Monrovia, Costa Mesa, Upland and Westminster.
   The alleged ringleader, identified as Najeh Badawi, 32, of
Fontana, and the other seven were arrested for investigation of
conspiracy to commit grand theft, Clark said.
   Badawi told a reporter who accompanied authorities on the raid
that he didn't know that duplicating copyrighted musical recordings
onto cassette tapes was against the law.
   ``It's not my business,'' Badawi said. ``I'm working for
someone. I was looking for something to do, something to feed my
family.''
   Clark identified the other suspects as Portino Delgado, 52, of
Mexico; Juan Espinosa, 28, of Mexico City; Juan Luis Perez, 21 of
Temuri, Mexico; Mohamed Abdallah, 57, of Pasadena; Olivia Moreno
Salcedo, 35, of La Puente; Salim Matsubsi, 28, of Westminster and
Adman Mohamad, 34, of Westminster.
   Steven D`Onofrio, chief of anti-piracy operations for the
Recording Industry Association of America, estimated that the
recording industry loses about $300 million a year to music
counterfeiting.
</TEXT>
