<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoodRider     10-14 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hood Rider,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced To Six Years In Prison For Wife's Wild Ride</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORRANCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired United Airlines pilot who sped
down the San Diego Freeway at 80 mph while his estranged wife clung
to the hood of his car was sentenced to six years in state prison.
   Russell A. Jobst, 44, who pleaded guilty last month to child
endangerment and two counts of asault with a deadly weapon, was
sentenced Thursday by Torrance Superior Court Judge William C.
Beverly Jr.
   Jobst drove off with his 19-month-old son on Aug. 17, 1987, as
his wife, Madonna Kennedy-Jobst, clung to the car's hood.
   Jobst said he was remorseful and wouldn't hurt Mrs.
Kennedy-Jobst in any way if he was spared a prison term.
   But the judge said the circumstances outweighed the defendant's
good behavior in jail, his solid record as a Navy helicopter pilot
and his apparent belief that he had received custody of the boy
during a divorce and custody dispute in a Hawaiian court.
   ``What can't be sympathized with is his response to this
situation,'' Beverly said. ``When he reacted the way that he did,
he endangered the life of his son, his estranged wife and everyone
around him.''
   Mrs. Kennedy-Jobst, 37, testifying at the sentencing, said this
incident was not the first in which her estranged husband was
violent.
   ``It is simply the most recent and the most public,'' she said.
``He has an inability to deal with anger.''
   Jobst could be eligible for parole after about two years and two
months in prison, a state Department of Corrections official said.
</TEXT>
