<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Sierra     10-14 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Sierra,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Complains Of Sierra Club Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's campaign has protested to the
Sierra Club that the club is unfairly criticizing one of his
actions in delaying a reduction in the lead content of gasoline
seven years ago, a club lobbyist said Friday.
   The lobbyist, Blake Early, said Bush aides said the regulation
in question went into effect ``after a period of review and we
shouldn't be hitting them up on it.'' He did not say who lodged the
complaint.
   Mark Goodin, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said he did not
have information immediately at hand on such a protest. Asked if
the campaign believed the criticism unfair, Goodin replied, ``We
sure do.''
   Bush as vice president headed an administration task force that
forced agencies to re-examine, and in some cases delay or cancel,
hundreds of regulations just after President Reagan took office in
1981.
   One of these was a planned reduction in the lead content of
gasoline. Fourteen months later, in July 1982, the Environmental
Protection Agency went ahead with a rule closely paralleling its
original plan.
   Lead is a deadly poison in high concentrations and can cause
brain damage in children. Used for decades in gasoline to boost
octane, it can disable exhaust pollution control equipment on
post-1975 cars. EPA said thousands of children probably were
suffering slight IQ reductions because of lead in their blood from
auto exhausts and other sources.
   Since then, the agency has ordered a further 90 percent
reduction in the lead content of gasoline, which Bush claimed
credit for in Thursday night's debate with Michael Dukakis.
   The reconsideration ordered by the Bush task force in 1981 was
prompted by complaints from small refiners that they would lose
money if they had to meet the new standards.
   Early said it was ``not clear that (the administration's
eventual) support was not the result of the large public outcry''
that followed news of EPA's decision to reconsider the lead
reduction program.
   Early spoke at a news conference where the club released a
report critical of another action of the task force that led EPA to
drop its requirement for double liners under 1,078 existing surface
impoundments of hazardous waste liquids, a requirement that
Congress wrote into the law in 1984 and which becomes effective
next month.
</TEXT>
