<DOCNO> AP881014-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RecklessHiking     10-14 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reckless Hiking,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hiker Charged After Drunken Rescue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fed up with dangerous search and rescue
missions for reckless hikers in New Hampshire's White Mountains,
the state has brought its first criminal charge against a hiker who
had to be rescued after getting drunk on a mountaintop.
   Jeffrey Morgan, 30, of Atlanta, was charged Thursday with
reckless conduct after rescuers were rousted in the middle of the
night to help him off snowy Mount Moriah outside Gorham. He pleaded
guilty in Gorham District Court and was fined $500, half of which
was suspended.
   ``The executive director, Donald Normandeau, made the decision
to `get tough with this business _ it's gone too far,' so we
charged him,'' Maj. Henry Mock, head of Fish and Game Department
law enforcement, said Friday.
   ``We did it to make a statement, and the statement is that we
are no longer going to tolerate this kind of activity on the part
of the hikers,'' Mock said. ``Whenever we see something that is
this flagrant, we will be considering these charges.''
   Morgan, Mock said, had been hiking the Appalachian Trail for six
months and three days. He hiked from Georgia to Maryland, then took
a bus to Maine, where he turned around and began hiking south,
authorities said.
   ``When he hit the North Country, he did not like cold weather,
so he went into Gorham, bought himself a fifth of vodka and decided
that would help him finish the trail,'' Mock said.
   He said Morgan was found ``violently ill'' at the top of Mount
Moriah at 8 p.m. Wednesday by two hikers from Massachusetts, one of
whom was a doctor.
   ``The doctor could see that he was also extremely hypothermic
and was not going to make it unless something was done for him,''
Mock said.
   He said the two pulled Morgan from the summit to some shelter,
put him in his sleeping bag and wrapped him in a space blanket
before heading down the mountain for help.
   At 2 a.m., they reached a farmhouse and called authorities.
   A fish and game officer and volunteer headed up the mountain at
3 a.m., and reached Morgan at about daylight, Mock said. Meanwhile,
a sizeable crew was mobilized to help carry Morgan down, based on
the report from the doctor.
   When the two rescuers reached Morgan, he had gotten out of the
sleeping bag and was stumbling down a trail, with no memory of how
he had gotten where he was, Mock said.
   The reckless conduct charge, a misdemeanor, can be applied in
cases in which a person knows his actions will place the lives or
safety of others in jeopardy, Mock said. It specifically mentions
alcohol use.
   Mock said other recent rescues also could have been considered
for charges and that more will be brought in the future.
   ``We have to make that fine-line difference between
foolhardiness, stupidity, lack of good judgment and recklessness,
and that's not always easy to do,'' he said. ``In this case, it
was.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
