<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SwineIdentification     10-14 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swine Identification,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meat Industry Backs New Program To Track Pork Across State Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the nation's meat industry on
Friday pledged support of a new Agriculture Department rule that
will require identification and recordkeeping on all swine sold
across state lines.
   The new regulation will go into effect on Nov. 14 as a
long-sought method of tracing the source of diseased hogs or those
with harmful drug or chemical residues.
   ``We intend to cooperate very closely with the department to
work out all the technicalities of this program so that it will be
as effective and efficient as possible,'' said Manly Molpus,
president of the American Meat Institute. ``We are delighted USDA
has made this a mandatory requirement.''
   His comments followed USDA's final rulemaking procedure that
will put the new regulation into force within 30 days. The proposed
rule was announced last Feb. 3.
   The regulation will require each hog to be identified
individually, which can include eartags, tatoos and backtags.
Record on each animal must be kept for two years and must include
the serial number of other approved identification appearing on the
swine.
   ``Every person who handles swine is responsible for the
identification as soon as it moves into interstate commerce,'' said
Assistant Secretary Kenneth A. Gilles. ``If the identification is
already on the hog, the next person in the chain is only required
to make and keep a record of it.''
   Pressure for swine identification came from Congress and the
National Research Council of the National Academy of Sciences.
Besides the American Meat Institute, support also came from a
number of other trade and professional associations such as the
Livestock Conservation Institute and the National Pork Producers
Council.
</TEXT>
