<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaezzaSentence     10-14 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laezza Sentence,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maximum in Wedding Limousine Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A driver who caused a crash that killed
three members of a wedding party last year was sentenced to prison
Friday, and the judge complained that he could not make the
sentence longer than seven years.
   In setting the sentence of two and one-third to seven years, the
maximum permitted by law, Judge Richard Delin said defendant
Vincent Laezza had made his automobile ``a lethal weapon ... in a
blatant disregard for human life.''
   Laezza, 21, was convicted of three counts of criminally
negligent homicide and one count of assault in a jury trial last
month, but acquitted on the more serious counts of manslaughter.
   Delin said he found it ludicrous that he could give the
defendant no more than up to seven years for the deaths of three
people.
   ``He used a public highway of our county as a racetrack,'' Delin
said, noting that witnesses said Laezza was drag racing at speeds
of up to 100 mph at the time of the collision. He said Laezza had
shown no remorse.
   ``I feel terrible for what happened,'' a sobbing Laezza said in
pleading for leniency. Speaking in a barely audible voice, he
added, ``It is something I have to live with for the rest of my
life.''
   Police said Laezza was speeding down Lido Boulevard when his car
smacked into a stretch limousine carrying the wedding party on
April 3, 1987.
   Killed instantly was the groom, Peter Phillips, 27, of North
Massapequa, and his brother and best man, John, 29, of Islip. The
bride, Carol Zagorski Phillips, 24, died of her injuries 18 days
later without ever knowing of her new husband's death.
   The bride's sister and maid of honor, Debra Zagorski, was
seriously injured.
</TEXT>
