<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CoptersGrounded     10-14 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copters Grounded,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Return Super Stallion Copters to Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps has returned to operation its
fleet of CH-53E Super Stallion helicopters after a one-time
inspection prompted by the discovery of a defective nut, officials
said Friday.
   The heavy-lift transport copters, almost all of which are based
inside the United States, were temporarily grounded ast Sunday
after mechanics at a training squadron at the Tustin, Calif.,
Marine Corps Air Station found a scratch on a main transmission
gearbox nut.
   The 1{-inch nut, subsequently judged to be defective, was one of
12 used to secure the main transmission inside the CH-53E, allowing
it to deliver power from the engines to the copter's rotor blade.
   Lt. Col. Fred Peck, a Marine spokesman in Washington, said all
93 of the Super Stallions were returned to service after the
emergency inspections failed to turn up any other defective nuts.
   The Naval Air Systems Command has concluded, however, that some
of the ``transmission barrel nut assemblies'' purchased by the
Defense Logistics Agency for the Super Stallions are defective and
they are being removed from the inventory, Peck added.
   William Armstrong, a spokesman for the Naval Air Systems
Command, declined immediate comment on the matter or to say what
company had manufactured the nut assemblies.
   The temporary grounding was the third for the Super Stallions in
the past two years prompted by a transmission problem.
   The fleet was grounded in February 1987 because of a defective
gear that forced an emergency landing. The following July, another
grounding was ordered because of three bearing failures, one of
which resulted in an emergency landing.
   In a related development, local officials at the Tustin base
said Thursday that a Super Stallion had been damaged on Sept. 27
when one of its three engines caught fire while taxiing. Base
firefighters extinguished the flames and none of the four Marines
on board was injured.
</TEXT>
