<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-US Grain,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Negotiators Fail to Agree on Long-Term Grain Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet officials Friday ended two days of
negotiations without a new long-term grain agreement, the U.S.
Embassy said.
   Negotiators also set no date for the next round of talks, the
embassy said.
   Both delegations put forward new proposals and were taking them
to their governments for consideration, with the United States
continuing to press for a five-year deal, an embassy statement said.
   The U.S. negotiating team left for the United States, it said.
   The Soviet Union on Wednesday proposed extending the previous
deal for just one year, catching the Reagan administration by
surprise, the Financial Times said.
   The newspaper quoted Soviet negotiator Yuri Chumakov as saying
the Soviets preferred to reach a short-term agreement now, leaving
room for further negotiation in the future.
   The most recent five-year agreement expired Sept. 30, although
the Soviet Union since has made some large purchases of U.S.
grains, including 275,000 tons announced Oct. 11. That brought the
total sold for Soviet delivery in the 1988-89 corn marketing year
to more than 4.7 million tons.
