<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle     10-14 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says He'll Now Be Only ``Background Issue''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle predicted Friday that he will now become a ``background
issue'' in the campaign and he said Democrat Michael Dukakis is the
real political liability.
   Quayle, who polls have suggested has been a drag on George
Bush's Republican campaign, commented during his first news
conference since Sept. 15.
   He criticized Dukakis for failing to say anything nice about
Bush after each candidate was asked during the debate to praise the
other.
   ``George Bush was very complimentary to Michael Dukakis on a
personal basis,'' Quayle said. Dukakis, he said, ``did lack the
common courtesy to say something nice.''
   Quayle held the news conference in Fort Smith, Ark., before
touring an electric plant and traveling to Louisiana for a rally
and fund-raiser. He then flew to Albuquerque, N.M.
   At a rousing rally at the University of Southwestern Louisiana,
Quayle released a list of what he called Dukakis debate
``failures.''
   He said Dukakis dodged the issue of taxes, failing to commit
himself to opposing tax increases. He also faulted Dukakis for his
``short-sighted and obstinate opposition to the death penalty'' and
for a ``shocking lack of knowledge'' on defense issues. He said
Dukakis would appoint liberals to the Supreme Court.
   In a series of interviews with Fort Smith media, Quayle was
asked about polls indicating substantial percentages of likely
voters view him negatively. Dukakis' negative ratings in recent
polls have rivaled or surpassed Quayle's.
   ``Governor Dukakis' negatives have gone up ... and ours have
actually switched to the better,'' Quayle said. He called Dukakis a
``drag on his ticket'' and added: ``The political liability happens
to be Governor Dukakis.''
   Quayle predicted a race that would go ``right down to the
wire.'' But he said he would become less of an issue.
   ``Obviously, there's going to be continued interest in me and
the reason for that is there's been so much interest in me up to
now,'' Quayle said. ``But it will be very much of a background
issue because the American people are trying to make up their minds
on the top of the ticket.''
   Quayle's news conference included no major stumbles. During his
last one, a month earlier, he called the Holocaust an ``obscene
period in our nation's history'' and then added, ``I didn't live in
this century.''
   He was asked Friday whether he would like to take another shot
at giving his opinion of the Holocaust, the killing of millions of
Jews under Adolf Hitler.
   ``I don't think it's necessary to get in and have a history
lesson on the Holocaust,'' he said. ``But let me say this ... if we
make the right decisions and we stay committed to peace and human
rights and if we can work with our allies and if we have good
intelligence, hopefully we can avert anything like the Holocaust.''
   ``Hopefully we have a learned a lesson about a very tragic event
in world history. ... Hopefully we will not repeat or allow things
that were truly tragic to happen again.''
</TEXT>
