<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     10-14 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Attack U.S. Building; 13 Police Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students shouting ``Drive out
Yankees!'' attacked a U.S. government office, firebombed a police
bus and injured 13 officers Friday, police and U.S. officials said.
   Two police were seriously hurt in the battle in the southern
city of Kwangju, the U.S. Embassy said in a statement. Police said
four protesters were arrested.
   About 100 protesters, many with iron pipes and clubs, hurled
rocks and about 150 gasoline bombs at the U.S. Information Service
building, the statement said.
   Some bombs hit a police bus by the gate with about 30 people
aboard, said The Chosun Ilbo, a leading newspaper in Seoul.
   No one was injured in the building, but a car inside the
compound was destroyed by firebombs and another was slightly
damaged, the embassy said. About 10 windows at the center's library
were damaged, it said.
   U.S. Embassy officials said seven assailants scaled the center's
roof from nearby inns while police outside fought back protesters
for about 10 minutes.
   ``From there, they hurled Molotov cocktails, steel pipes and
tiles which they ripped from the center roof,'' the officials said.
   The students on the roof carried a placard that read ``Repeal
armistice agreement, conclude peace treaty,'' said Yonhap, the
South Korean news agency. The 1950-53 war between North Korea and
South Korea ended with an armistice, and both sides are technically
still at war.
   Yonhap said the students denounced the United States and
demanded the arrest of former President Chun Doo-hwan, who has been
under parliamentary investigation for alleged corruption and
brutality during his seven-year rule. Chun left office in February.
   The students also hurled firebombs at a downtown police station,
shatterring windows, Chosun said.
   The U.S. Information Service building has been the target of
frequent attacks by radical students demanding the withdrawal of
U.S. forces in South Korea under a mutual defense pact. Radicals
contend the United States has enforced division of the Korean
peninsula.
   On Thursday, hundreds of students firebombed a government party
building and protested in downtown Kwangju when police blocked them
from approaching the U.S. center.
   Dissidents and radical students stepped up an anti-U.S. campaign
after the Olympics. Government officials are concerned about
growing anti-U.S. sentiment fueled partly by trade conflict.
   About 300 students Friday battled riot police at Hankook
University of Foreign Studies in Seoul after burning effigies of
President Reagan and President Roh Tae-woo.
   Radicals contend the Roh regime is a front for a military
dictatorship supported by the United States, despite substantial
reforms being carried out by Roh.
   The students threw dozens of firebombs and rocks at riot police,
who responded with tear gas. Several students were bleeding, but it
was not known how many people were injured or arrested.
</TEXT>
