<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignAbroad     10-14 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Abroad,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sampling Of Foreign Comment On Presidential Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of what people and media around the world are
saying about the U.S. presidential election:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The daily Le Monde said that after Thursday night's presidential
debate, Vice President George Bush retained his lead over Gov.
Michael Dukakis.
   ``Already favored in presidential polls, George Bush seems to
have had success in passing the last, perilous obstacle on the road
to the White House. In the second and last televised duel of the
campaign ... he managed, at least, to deprive his adversary ... of
the victory that he (Dukakis) badly needed.''
   The front-page article added that Dukakis failed to defeat Bush
or to ``improve his image to one of a man open and inspired.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HUNGARY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Budapest evening journal Esti Hirlap said Friday that the
debate pushed Bush toward victory.
   ``Bush argued in an amiably lighthearted manner, and his
down-to-earth approach to the subjects is likely to have driven
home his points among the voters _ one-third of whom are yet to
make up their minds which way to vote.
   ``Michael Dukakis, noted for his seriousness, made no small
efforts to look winsome at this last face-to-face occasion, but his
very concrete definitions of the nation's cares and worries, and
the need for unpopular measures that he deemed unavoidable, may
have acted the opposite way in the bid to win voters.
   ``As to the arms issue, Dukakis endorsed faster development of
conventional weapons while Bush _ accusing him wrongly of backing
unilateral disarmament _ stressed the Reagan administration's
achievements in promoting world peace while upholding the `peace
from strength' principle.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NORWAY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The independent daily Verdens Gang said Friday that Dukakis had
his last chance in the debate _ and misused it.
   ``Despite doing one of his best TV appearances ever, he never
managed to run over George Bush,'' it said. ``Dukakis entered his
final 90-minute TV round knowing that this final debate was his
biggest chance to pick up the 14 percent he was behind in public
opinion polls. But regardless how earnest and sincere he was, his
opponent George Bush was too good for him to succeed.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   British bookmakers shortened the odds Friday on a Bush victory.
   Ladbrokes gave odds of 1-6 on Bush, meaning that if he wins, a
bet of six dollars wins $1 plus the original stake. It gave 3-1
odds on Dukakis, meaning a bet of $1 would win $3 plus the stake.
   Before Thursday's debate, Ladbrokes gave Bush 1-3 odds and
Dukakis 7-4.
   William Hill gave Bush 2-9, from 4-7 on Thursday; and Dukakis
11-4, from 5-4.
   ``We've lost count of the bets of three figures we've taken
today for George Bush,'' said William Hill spokesman Graham Sharpe.
``And we've just been contacted by a punter in Manchester who said
he wanted to put 20,000 pounds ($35,000) on Mr. Bush.''
</TEXT>
