<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     10-14 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Government Radicals Blamed For Railway Bomb, Two Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government radicals bombed a
railway station in central Sri Lanka on Friday and assassinated two
members of the governing party in separate incidents, officials
said.
   No one was reported injured in the bombing at the Kadugannawa
Railway Station, but state-run radio said the blast prompted the
government to extend a curfew in the region.
   The station is about 50 miles northeast of the capital, Colombo.
There was no claim of responsibility, but police blamed the
extremist Sinhalese People's Liberation Front, which opposes a
government plan aimed at making peace with minority Tamils.
   A senior police official said Sinhalese extremists arrived at
the station at 3 a.m., chased out all employees and then set off
the bomb.
   The blast destroyed part of the station and damaged some rail
tracks, according to the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. Rail service was suspended indefinitely, he said.
   After the explosion, the government extended a curfew in Kandy
district and southern Matara district until 6 a.m. Saturday,
state-run radio reported.
   The curfew was imposed in Matara on Monday after anti-government
demonstrators clashed with security forces. At least 15 people were
killed.
   On Tuesday, it was extended to the Kandy region after police
opened fire to quell a student demonstration. One student was
killed and three were injured.
   A government statement issued in Colombo said Piyadasa Witharana
and H.A. Podiappuhamy, both provincial council members of the
governing United National Party, were murdered by members of the
the People's Liberation Front.
   Witharana was killed Thursday in the southern Matara district
while Podiappuhamy was assassinated the same day in the central
Badulla district, the statement said. Both areas are dominated by
Sinhalese.
   The People's Liberation Front opposes a peace accord aimed at
ending a 5-year-old war by Tamil rebels demanding a separate nation.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They claim they are oppressed by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the
population.
   The leaders of Sri Lanka and India signed the accord in 1987.
India, Sri Lanka's northern neighbor, has a large Tamil population
of its own and mediated the agreement.
   Sinhalese extremists say the accord makes too many concessions
to Tamils, and they have vowed to kill anyone who supports it.
</TEXT>
