<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Astronauts     10-14 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Astronauts,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Salutes Discovery Astronauts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan borrowed a phrase from Vice
President George Bush on Friday to hail the five Discovery shuttle
astronauts as ``America's heroes.''
   Giving the men a hearty White House welcome, the president
appeared with the astronauts at an affectionate Rose Garden
ceremony as many NASA employees and some of their family members
looked on.
   ``Thank you for taking us into space ... and welcome home,''
Reagan said, evoking a round of applause from the crowd of several
hundred observers.
   The president told the five-member crew that he agreed with a
statement made by the vice president during his debate Thursday
evening with Democratic rival Micheal Dukakis.
   ``The vice president was right last night _ you are America's
heroes. You are his heroes and mine ... what you have done for the
program and the country will be long remembered,'' Reagan said.
``You ... and the entire team that made the mission of the
Discovery a success, deserve the praise of a grateful nation.''
   Although Reagan mentioned that the space program had had
``setbacks,'' he did not specifically mention the tragic fate of
the shuttle Challenger.
   The Discovery flight, which began on Sept. 29, was the first
shuttle mission since the Challenger blew up on liftoff, killing
all seven aboard.
   Reagan asserted that the Discovery mission symbolized a return
to space for the country and ``America intends to stay there.''
   ``We just want to say thanks again for this mission and for all
that it has meant to this country,'' Reagan said.
   The president also saluted the astronauts' wives, telling them
they were ``just as brave as these gentlemen.''
   The shuttle's commander, Frederick H. Hauck, presented the
president with a blue astronaut's jacket, complete with patches
from the mission that had been taken into space aboard the shuttle.
   Reagan beamed as he held the shiny, royal blue jacket aloft.
   In contrast, the five astronauts appeared a bit out of their
element, dressed in business suits and ties.
   The crew had met with Reagan at the Johnson Space Center in
Houston late last month, just days before their space mission
began. At that time, the astronauts had pledged to bring the jacket
and its patches back to the president at the White House.
   ``This is a great team that we work with,'' Hauck told the
president, adding, ``The team is only as good as its leader, and as
far as we're concerned, you're the captain of the team.''
   Hauck and his crew, pilot Richard O. Covey and mission
specialists John M. Lounge, David C. Hilmers and George D. Nelson,
were completing a two-day capital tour. On Thursday, they visited
the House gallery, where they were met by the applause of members
on the floor.
</TEXT>
