<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Arrest-Clipping     10-14 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arrest-Clipping,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Suspect Carried News Clipping That Led to Positive ID</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rural Iowa sheriff says a newspaper clipping
led to the arrest of a Baltimore man wanted since Aug. 10 in
connection with the murder of his former girlfriend.
   Authorities said Andrew McCollough, 24, was given away by a
newspaper clipping in his wallet that detailed the killing. He was
in custody Friday in Greenfield, Iowa, facing extradition to
Maryland on murder charges in the shooting death of Andrea Fuller,
23.
   McCollough used a phony identification when Iowa authorities
arrested him Monday on a California car theft charge, Adair County
Sheriff Fred Skellenger said.
   ``If he had not had that newspaper clipping in his billfold,''
Skellenger said, ``I don't think it would have ever dawned on us''
to question his identity. ``We would have dropped the charges and
he'd be out.''
   McCollough was using the name Frankie Smith when he and two
passengers were stopped for a broken headlamp about 60 miles
southwest of Des Moines, Skellenger said.
   A registration check revealed that the car had been stolen in
Los Angeles three days earlier. Smith, a 30-year-old man and a
23-year-old woman from Los Angeles were arrested and charged with
auto theft.
   During booking in Greenfield, Skellenger said, ``I noticed in
Frankie Smith's billfold a newspaper item'' from The Evening Sun of
Baltimore.
   The eight-paragraph article said Baltimore police had obtained a
warrant for the arrest of Andrew McCollough for Ms. Fuller's
murder. She was described as McCollough's former girlfriend.
   Skellenger said he asked Smith why he was carrying the clipping.
   ``He said it was his family,'' Skellenger said.
   Elsewhere in the billfold, Skellenger found a birth certificate
for Frankie Smith issued by the Baltimore City Health Department on
Aug. 11, the day after the murder.
   Authorities in California declined to seek extradition of the
passengers on car theft charges, and they were released, Skellenger
said.
</TEXT>
