<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Hostage,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Consular Agent, Secretary Freed Unharmed After 14-Hour
Hostage Taking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VERACRUZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer who held a U.S. consular agent
and his secretary at gunpoint for 14 hours released them unharmed
Friday and surrendered to authorities.
   Authorities said the gunman, identified as Francisco Delfin
Perez of Cordova, Veracruz, was arrested and taken to the state
capital of Jalapa to face kidnapping charges.
   Officials said Delfin Perez, about 48, walked into Edwin Culp's
office Thursday and took Culp and his secretary, Teresa Jesus
Horts, hostage.
   He was demanding that two brothers, a sister-in-law and a notary
public be imprisoned for allegedly cheating his mother in a dispute
over her late husband's estate, said Alfredo Algarin Vega,
assistant secretary of the Veracruz state government.
   It was unknown if the consulate office had a connection to the
inheritance dispute.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Bob Hugins said Delfin Perez surrendered
and ``agreed to talk about his problems with Mexican government
officials.'' Hugins said Culp and Horts were freed shortly after 3
a.m.
   Culp's doctor said Culp was resting at home after the ordeal and
could not speak to reporters.
   Negotiations lasted through the night and included Algarin,
Delfin Perez' mother, and a friend of the lawyer. About 50 police
surrounded the downtown office building where the consulate office
is located.
   Algarin said Delfin Perez knew Culp. Officials understood from
the gunman's mother that the relationship was cordial, he said.
   Culp, 46, is from Missouri and has lived in Mexico for at least
15 years, Hugins said. While he is not a foreign service officer,
he has run the consular agency for at least six years, is
accredited to the Mexican government, and has diplomatic status,
Hugins said.
   William Graves, the chief U.S. Embassy spokesman, said Culp has
a restaurant, discotheque and clothing factory in this port city,
140 miles east of Mexico City.
</TEXT>
