<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShingellosisOutbreak     10-14 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shingellosis Outbreak,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Food Illness Prompts Flood Of Calls To Health Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Northwest Airlines passengers
have been stricken with an illness that state health officials said
Friday may be linked to contaminated food served aboard at least
four flights.
   ``We have cases all over the country,'' said state
epidemiologist Michael Osterholm. ``This morning, we were dealing
with a family as far away as Germany.
   ``The one common phrase being reported (to investigators) is
people thinking they have never been so sick, that they thought
they were going to die,'' Osterholm said.
   Four reports were confirmed Thursday as cases of the bacterial
illness shingellosis, and Osterholm said he expects more than 100
additional cases to be confirmed in the next several weeks.
   The people who were confirmed with the illness were on stretches
of a Northwest flight that originated in Minneapolis-St. Paul and
went to Nashville, Detroit and Seattle, as well as on a Minnesota
Vikings football team charter flight to Miami, Osterholm said. The
flights were between Sept. 25 to Oct. 4.
   ``We have no reason to believe it is happening now,'' Osterholm
said.
   The outbreak first came to light after 21 players and staff
members of the football team became acutely ill two to five days
after their game in Miami Oct. 2.
   All the illnesses confirmed so far have been traced to food
prepared in Marriott Corp.'s airline kitchen at the Minneapolis-St.
Paul International Airport. The facility serves 100,000 meals a
week for the airline.
   ``Marriott has taken extraordinary measures to see it's not
happening now,'' Osterholm said.
   Alan Munchaster, vice president of corporate relations for
Northwest, said preliminary tests on Marriott employees who may
have handled the food were negative. Additional tests were being
conducted by Marriott to pinpoint the source of the bacteria,
Munchaster said.
   ``They're looking at cold food and the lettuce,'' Munchaster
said. ``Those seem to be the culprits.''
   Shigellosis is an intestinal infection that causes intense
diarrhea and other symptoms that can last for five to seven days.
The illness spreads easily from person to person.
</TEXT>
