<2ND_LINE>AM-Arson Town,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Former Firefighter Has Admitted Setting About 17
Fires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former volunteer firefighter in
neighboring Jefferson has admitted setting about 17 of the more
than 20 arson fires that have plagued the area since May,
prosecutors said Friday.
   ``Given the nature and number of these offenses, defendant poses
a serious risk to the safety of the community and should be held
without bail,'' Coos County Attorney Pierre Morin said in a motion
for a bail hearing held Friday for Lance Lalumiere.
   Lalumiere, 23, a restaurant dishwasher, was charged Wednesday
with setting one fire and state police said they planned to seek
indictments charging him with 15 others.
   Morin's motion said that in addition to the Aug. 23 fire
Lalumiere is formally charged with setting, ``defendant has given
statements admitting to committing some 16 other acts of arson in
the Jefferson, N.H., area.''
   Jefferson, population 850, has had 21 suspicious fires since
May. Nearby towns have had at least three others, including one
Oct. 3 in Dalton for which a second suspect was charged Thursday.
   Lalumiere's bail was set at $50,000 Wednesday. Friday's bail
hearing was continued until next week.
   The fires began in brush and fields and escalated to buildings.
No one was been killed or seriously injured, although many were
left homeless.
   The original charge against Lalumiere involves an Aug. 23 fire
at his brother Michael's cabin. Lalumiere reported the fire and was
there trying to put it out when firefighters arrived. He had been
asked to quit the fire department earlier in the year when he moved
briefly to a neighboring town.
   On Thursday, Lawrence Coulter Jr., 19, also a Jefferson
volunteer firefighter and lifelong resident, was arrested and
charged with setting fire to a vacation home in nearby Dalton.
Police said that fire went out on its own.
