<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BerlinWall     10-14 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Berlin Wall,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fatigue-Clad Students Jam Traffic Trying to Get Out The Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students clad in military fatigues
created a traffic jam Friday in this village of 3,000 by stopping
motorists at concrete block ``Berlin Walls'' to hand out
get-out-the-vote pamphlets.
   But feelings ran so high over the congested traffic and the
``Check Point Charlie'' atmosphere that the vocational education
students had to tear down the walls by late morning.
   ``We don't want to harass anyone,'' said Herb Locy, the masonry
teacher from the Ashtabula County Joint Vocational School who
organized the effort. He said the walls were supposed to give
residents a better feeling for what it would be like to live in a
police state, thus increasing interest in voting.
   ``If they're provoked as it is, how would they feel if it was
the real thing?'' Locy said. He said that by the time the decision
was made to dismantle the walls, the students had handed out most
of the 1,000 pamphlets that encouraged residents to vote Nov. 8.
   The walls were 4 feet, 6 inches high and made of stacked
concrete blocks. One had red stars and the words ``Stop USSR'' and
``Check Point Charlie'' painted on it. More than a dozen students,
wearing green fatigues borrowed from a National Guard unit in
Youngstown, manned the check points that simulated those in
communist East Berlin.
   Police officer Dwayne Patrick said police received at least 100
complaints from drivers about the walls at three main intersections.
   ``But it was approved by the Village Council, so unless we get a
bad accident, there's really nothing we can do,'' he said.
   Some complained because only one car at a time could pass
through a narrow opening and other complaints were from ``people
getting the wrong idea because of what was written on the walls,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
