<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     10-14 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Debating Bush Like Eating Jell-O With Fork</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen said Friday
that debating George Bush is ``like trying to eat Jell-O with a
fork'' but that he thought Michael Dukakis had managed the task
well.
   Still, he said, polls suggesting Dukakis lost Thursday night's
debate and indicating he is trailing in the presidential race mean
``we have a tough fight down to the end.''
   Bentsen, who watched the debate on television in his home state
of Texas, flew to California Friday to greet Dukakis at a
post-debate rally at the state capitol.
   ``He's a real pressure player. He stepped up and delivered for
America,'' Bentsen told the Sacramento crowd.
   ``Debating George Bush is just like trying to eat Jell-O with a
fork,'' he said. ``It keeps slipping off, sliding off, and when you
finally get a bite there's not much substance to it, just a lot of
sugar water and artificial ingredients.''
   Bentsen told reporters aboard his campaign jet on the trip from
Texas that he thought Dukakis ``did an excellent job'' in the
debate. ``I think he was warm. He was friendly. He was precise. He
spoke to the issues. He gave answers to the questions.''
   ``He was feeling pretty good about it. So was I,'' said Bentsen,
describing a post-debate conversation between the two Democrats.
   Bentsen objected to a question from one reporter on what it
meant to the campaign that Dukakis failed to score a knockout punch
against Bush.
   ``I never said he had to get a knockout punch. That was you
folks. You were buying the Republican line,'' he said. ``When
you're three or four points behind, what you want to do is speak to
the issues, and I think that those issues, keep repeating them,
they'll sink in and we'll win it.''
   ``You know, middle-income America, that is who Dukakis is
talking to,'' he said, ``real concerns'' such as home ownership and
college costs.
   ``I think those things finally get across. I think that's why
we're still in the running,'' he said.
   ``I don't think he dealt with issues that are going to have
voters jumping up on their chairs,'' he said. ``But he dealt with
the real concerns about their futures, and I think that is a more
lasting approach to the issues.''
   Bentsen did have some criticism, agreeing in part with comments
by House Speaker Jim Wright this week that Dukakis needed to speak
directly to voters and dump his TV ad package.
   ``When it comes to the expenditure of funds and all ... more
time on radio to discuss the issues so you're not 30-second bites,
I believe, would be more effective, frankly,'' he said.
   The Texas senator called the opening question of the debate,
when Dukakis was asked what he'd do if someone attacked and killed
his wife, ``a horrible question ... almost an outrageous question.''
   He declined to criticize Dukakis for being unemotional in his
response.
   ``He is against capital punishment he thinks that's not a
deterrent to crime,'' he said. ``I'm sure he would have done what
he could to put that fellow in jail for a lifetime to rot.''
   Asked if he would have responded the same way, Bentsen said,
``I'm not going to try to second guess him.''
</TEXT>
