<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Mortgages     10-14 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mortgages,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 30-year, fixed-rate
mortgages fell to the lowest level in five months this week,
according to a nationwide mortgage survey released Friday.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., a government-chartered
corporation owned by savings institutions and known as Freddie Mac,
said fixed-rate mortgages average 10.33 percent this week, down
from 10.38 percent last week.
   That was the lowest since rates averaged 10.32 percent in the
week ending May 6. The averages do not include add-on fees known as
points.
   Fixed-rate mortgages hit a high for the year of 10.71 percent in
the week ending Aug. 19. That was the week after the Federal
Reserve Board raised the discount rate, a key bank lending rate, in
an effort to cool economic growth it believed was leading to
accelerating inflation.
   However, since then the Fed has not found it necessary to
tighten further because a number of signs of slowing have emerged,
including declines in retail sales, lackluster growth in industrial
production and less robust employment growth.
   Yields on long-term bonds have been falling in recent weeks and
mortgage rates have followed along.
   However, short-term interest rates have eased only slightly.
Freddie Mac said rates on the most popular type of one-year,
adjustable-rate mortgages, those with caps on how high the interest
can go, averaged 8.11 percent last week, down slightly from the
peak of 8.16 percent six weeks ago.
   Adjustable rates this year have averaged as low as 7.49 percent
in March, while fixed rates hit a post-stock market crash low of
9.84 percent in February.
</TEXT>
