<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0709 10-14 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0709,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov't Plans To Relax Austerity Program, Communists Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Serbian criticism of
national leader; PICKS up 6th pvs, `During the ...' SUBS 10th pvs
``It seems ...'' to fix typo in chauvinism. Minor editing
thereafter to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced plans
Friday to ease an unpopular austerity program, three days before it
meets to consider widespread demands for resignations in its
leadership.
   The Central Committees of four of Yugoslavia's six republics and
of ethnically troubled Kosovo province also met Friday to iron out
political rifts as fiery politicking continued before Monday's
meeting of the policy-setting national Central Committee.
   Several Serbian Communist Party groups, including the
influential Belgrade city organization, joined calls for the
resignation of national party chief Stipe Suvar.
   Milanko Renovica, a member of the ruling Communist Party
Politburo and a former party chief, became the third member of the
23-man body to offer his resignation in the past three weeks, the
state news agency Tanjug reported Friday. The move was expected to
be ratified Monday.
   Deputy Premier Janez Zemljaric said Yugoslavia would import $600
million in emergency staples _ triple the amount announced Oct. 8
by the government _ to ease the worst economic crisis in the
country in four decades.
   Belgrade dailies said the government also would increase wages
for workers in profitable companies and in social services.
   The Serbian Communist Party groups attacked Suvar Friday for
criticizing Serbia the day before. Belgrade Communist chief Rados
Smijlkovic was among leading Serbian officials who charged that
Suvar is trying to turn Monday's meeting into an indictment of
Yugoslavia's largest republic.
   Suvar has promised a shake-up of top personnel following three
months of economic protests and nearly daily ethnic rallies led by
Serbian nationalists.
   During the Kosovo meeting, Communists representing the
province's ethnic Albanian majority and others from its Slav
minority clashed on several issues, Belgrade radio said.
   Serbians have demanded more control over its autonomous province
in rallies and prompted an unprecedented power struggle. The mainly
Christian minority accuse mainly Moslem ethnic Albanians of
harassment.
   At the Kosovo meeting, Serb and Montenegrin representatives
demanded the resignation of the province's mostly ethnic Albanian
communist leadership, the official news agency Tanjug said.
   In Albania, the Communist Party daily Zeri i Popullit charged
Yugoslavia's Serbian leader, Slobodan Milosevic, and his followers
with spearheading a campaign of discrimination against Albanians
similar to apartheid in South Africa.
   ``It seems the hotheads of Serb chauvinism seek to set not only
Kosovo and Yugoslavia on fire, but the Balkans as well,'' said the
newspaper in comments carried by the official Albanian news agency
ATA. ``We would advise them not to play with fire.''
   In Yugoslavia's liberal northern republic of Slovenia, its
official youth organization demanded direct elections and the
``formal abandonment of a one-party system,'' the Belgrade daily
Borba said.
   The government imposed an austerity program last May designed to
curb a $21 billion foreign debt and 217 percent annual inflation by
reducing or freezing wages and allowing prices to rise.
   The new pay increases will be adopted by Parliament by the end
of the month, Belgrade dailies said.
   The newspapers said the International Monetary Fund had approved
the measures. The IMF and other Western creditors insisted on the
austerity program before rescheduling debt payments and extending
new loans.
   At the meeting of Kosovo's Communist leaders, representatives of
Kosovo's Serb and Montenegrin minority demanded the resignation of
the province's mostly ethnic Albanian Communist leadership, Tanjug
said.
   In the southern republic of Montenegro, where police used tear
gas and clubs to break up anti-government protests last weekend,
republican party chief Miljan Radovic complained that
``anti-Socialist and anti-Communist'' outbursts never heard before
are now so common that ``it gives a man the chills.''
   Hundreds of Montenegrin students are boycotting university
cafeterias to press demands for the leaders' ouster and free
elections. They have refused official appeals to stop their action.
</TEXT>
