<1ST_LINE>u p PM-NewJerseySenate-Ads     10-14 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Jersey Senate-Ads,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indignant Bradley Lambastes Dawkins' TV Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley lashed out Friday
at what he called an ``offensive'' television attack on Democratic
colleague Frank Lautenberg by Peter Dawkins, the Republican
challenger to Lautenberg's Senate seat.
   ``This makes me angry. It's offensive to me,'' Bradley said of
the Dawkins' commerical depicting Lautenberg as motivated by greed.
Dawkins, a retired Army general and investment banker, is seeking
to deny Lautenberg a second term.
   The ad, which ran on New York and Philadelphia television this
week, ends: ``Frank Lautenberg: He'll deny anything to get elected
... as long as he can make some money on the side.''
   Bradley, who is chairing Lautenberg's re-election effort, said
that the ad ``goes beyond the line of propriety.'' The news
conference was held at Democratic national headquarters.
   The 30-second commercial accuses Lautenberg, a multimillionaire,
of conflicts of interest between his office and his investments, of
greedily voting for a Senate pay raise, and of accepting campaign
money from ``toxic polluters.''
   Bradley said Lautenberg, former top officer of the worldwide
Automatic Data Processing Corp., took a ``gigantic'' pay cut in
coming to the Senate and has no motive to use his office for
personal financial gain.
   But Dawkins spokesman Bill Kenyon said Lautenberg, not Dawkins,
began the negative advertising. ``It's interesting they feel
compelled to bring out their big gun,'' he said. ``We'd like to see
Frank stand on his own two feet.''
   Both Lautenberg and Dawkins have been engaging in increasingly
negative attacks, and their race is becoming one of the nastiest in
the nation.
   Lautenberg surprised observers in September when he used his
first paid television time to question Dawkins' motives in moving
to New Jersey.
   Most analysts expected the senator's first commercials to be
positive promotions of his legislative record.
   Negative advertising by both sides has continued since.
   The gutterfight continued face to face when the two met
Wednesday in their first debate. They devoted little time to
issues, concentrating more on insults.
</TEXT>
