<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1728EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Thatcher     10-14 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Triumphant Thatcher Winds Up Tory Party Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A triumphant Margaret Thatcher wound up
her Conservative Party's annual conference Friday rejecting the
notion of a politically unified Western Europe and pledging to
support the next U.S. president.
   To thunderous applause and chants of ``10 more years'' from the
4,500 delegates, the prime minister also declared her Conservatives
will hold power into the 1990s _ ``And who knows, beyond.''
   ``We are all too young to put our feet up ... I include
myself,'' said Mrs. Thatcher, who turned 63 Thursday.
   Mrs. Thatcher came to power in 1979, has won three elections in
a row and already is the longest-serving leader in the Western
world.
   On the subject of the European Economic Community, Mrs. Thatcher
charged that advocates of closer political union wanted to use the
12-nation trade bloc ``as a vehicle for spreading socialism'' and
sought to ``bring about a federal Europe by stealth.''
   In remarks widely regarded as setting a new agenda to focus on
social issues, the prime minister also urged Britons to maintain a
``generous society'' and exercise civic responsibility.
   Millions of Britons have become richer through nearly a decade
of Mrs. Thatcher's right-wing economic policies. But unemployment,
at 8 percent, is twice as high as in 1979, and critics charge
Britain has become a greedy, materialistic and uncaring society.
   At the end of the prime minister's 45-minute address, delegates
waved Union Jacks and huge, blue party flags while Mrs. Thatcher,
her grip on the Conservatives unchallenged, stood with arms raised
acknowledging the cheers.
   As Mrs. Thatcher left the hall in this south England resort to
the strains of the favorite Tory anthem, ``Land of Hope and
Glory,'' some delegates waved signs declaring ``Bush-Thatcher 88''
and ``Bush-Quayle.''
   Mrs. Thatcher did not mention by name Republican presidential
candidate George Bush and his running mate, Dan Quayle, or
Democratic contender Michael Dukakis.
   Of President Reagan, with whom she has developed a particularly
close relationship through the 80s, Mrs. Thatcher said he ``has
rebuilt the strength and confidence of the West _ not without a
little help _ and inspired the democracies to go out and win the
battle of ideas.''
   ``It is vital that Britain and America should always stand
together. So the next president of the United States too will have
the United Kingdom as a staunch ally,'' she added.
   Mrs. Thatcher's blunt remarks on the EEC followed a
controversial speech last month in which she rejected moves for
closer political or monetary union after 1992, when all trade
barriers among member nations are to be dismantled.
   ``We haven't worked all these years to free Britain from the
paralysis of socialism only to see it creep through the back door
of central control and bureacracy from Brussels,'' Mrs. Thatcher
said.
   The chief bureaucrat at the EEC headquarters in the Belgian
capital, Commisssioner Jacques Delors, is a French socialist.
   The remarks were Mrs. Thatcher's clearest rejection yet of what
she sees as unrealistic talk of some form of political union in
Western Europe.
   On the Irish Republican Army, which blew up her hotel here in an
assassination attempt during the 1984 party conference, Mrs.
Thatcher said her government would never compromise with terrorists
``at home and abroad.''
   ``If they IRA think they can weary us or frighten us, they have
made a terrible miscalculation,'' she said of the guerrilla
movement fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
   As she headed back to London, police dismantled the biggest
security operation ever mounted around a British party convention.
The four-day gathering was the Tories' first in Brighton since 1984.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 16 months into her third term, holds a five-point
lead of over the opposition socialist Labor Party.
   But she is sensitive to charges by Labor that the well off have
benefited from big tax cuts, while the poorest have been hit by her
rein on state spending.
</TEXT>
