<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StealthPilots     10-14 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stealth Pilots,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Lauds Pilots of `Secret' Stealth Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon still doesn't talk officially
about its Stealth aircraft. But Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
is not above discussing some of the men who fly the planes.
   Carlucci, appearing in Beverly Hills, Calif., on Friday to
deliver a speech before the Society of Experimental Test Pilots,
identified by name two pilots ``who flew in the earliest days of
Stealth aircraft development.''
   The secretary lauded ``men like Bill Park and Ken Dyson'' as
``unsung heroes'' and ``the backbone of our nation's defenses.''
   ``Although for now your achievements must remain private, the
results can be seen in the successes America is realizing
throughout the world,'' Carlucci declared. ``The time will come
when history will fully record your accomplishments.''
   A copy of Carlucci's speech was released in Washington.
   Norman Kenneth Dyson is the chief test pilot for the Rockwell
International Corp., and William M. Park is director of flight
operations for advanced development projects at the Lockheed Corp.
   Although Dyson was described in a recent book as a test pilot
involved in flying experimental Stealth aircraft, the Pentagon and
Air Force never have acknowledged the work of either man on such
programs.
   Rockwell was the prime contractor on the B-1B bomber, an Air
Force plane that incorporates some Stealth _ or radar-evading _
design features, but it was not clear whether Carlucci was
referring to work by Dyson while employed by Rockwell.
   Mike Matthews, a Rockwell spokesman, said Friday that Dyson did
not join the company until 1983. He was unable to say where Dyson
had worked previously.
   Lockheed, meantime, developed and produced a Stealth fighter for
the Air Force starting in the late 1970s and extending into the
1980s, defense sources have said.
   Jim Ragsdale, a Lockheed spokesman, said Friday he was not at
liberty ``to discuss the work of Park that prompted the mention by
Secretary Carlucci.''
   Carlucci, who recently scuttled a plan to unveil Lockheed's
Stealth fighter before the presidential election, said Friday the
United States ``must not falter in (its) commitment to developing
state-of-the-art weapons systems.''
   ``Our latest generation of aircraft ... with their Stealth
technology represent the pinnacle of American scientific
leadership. Not since the Manhattan Project (to develop an atomic
bomb) have we seen a program cloaked in such secrecy and a
technology with such enormous potential to guarantee the security
of our nation.
   ``However,'' he continued, ``we must not forget that the success
of weapon development programs like these requires the hard work,
sacrifice and dedication of many individuals _ men like Bill Park
and Ken Dyson, who flew in the earliest days of Stealth aircraft
development.''
</TEXT>
