<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jamaica-Gilbert     10-14 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jamaica-Gilbert,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Prepares To Lift State of Emergency Imposed After
Hurricane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LLOYD WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday prepared to
lift a monthlong state of emergency imposed after hurricane Gilbert
ravaged Jamaica, but a nighttime curfew to prevent looting was to
remain in force.
   Prime Minister Edward Seaga said in a nationwide radio address
Thursday that the state of emergency covering four eastern
parishes, including the capital of Kingston, was no longer
necessary and would be lifted at midnight Friday.
   But he said the nightly curfew would remain in effect until
electricity is sufficiently restored.
   ``This is necessary because many homes and places of businesses
are damaged and still insecure,'' Seaga said.
   The government ordered the state of emergency on Sept. 15, three
days after the hurricane struck the Caribbean island with 145 mph
winds, killing 45 people and causing damage estimated at between
$800 million and $1 billion.
   Under the emergency order police were empowered to force
businesses providing essential services, such as gasoline stations,
to open if they could. The government was allowed to requisition
trucks and heavy equipment for distributing supplies and cleanup
work.
   The order included a curfew because of looting of warehouses and
stores in the first days after the hurricane. Seaga said the curfew
sharply reduced the looting.
   The emergency order covered the parishes of Kingston, St.
Andrew, St. Catherine and St. Thomas _ an area housing about half
of Jamaica's population of 2.3 million.
</TEXT>
