<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ASNE-Candidates     10-14 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ASNE-Candidates,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Answer Editors' Queries On FOIA, Privacy Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both George Bush and Michael Dukakis are
committed to openness in government and support the Freedom of
Information Act, the candidates said in answer to questions put by
the American Society of Newspaper Editors.
   The editors' association released on Friday the presidential
candidates' answers to a series of questions regarding the First
Amendment, openness of their administration, attitudes toward press
conferences and other press issues.
   In the answers, Dukakis pledged opposition to the use of
mandatory lie detector tests to track down the source of government
leaks to the press.
   Bush said access to the president is ``absolutely vital'' for a
press secretary, and that he and his spokesman should have ``a
close, personal working relationship.''
   Both candidates were given written questions in early August,
and they responded in writing in September and October.
   Both were asked their views regarding the conduct of government
business in the open.
   Bush responded: ``Within the limits of national security,
government should be open to scrutiny by the media and the public.
... The information process from a news conference to the Freedom
of Information Act is an appropriate and integral part of ensuring
that accountability.''
   Dukakis responded: ``A Dukakis administration would fully comply
with the Freedom of Information Act. The fundamental premise of
this statute is that American citizens have the right to know about
he activities of their own government. The current administration
claims that complying with the FOIA is too time consuming, too
expensive, and too bothersome. These are excuses for government
secrecy. And they could serve as a cloak for incompetence,
mismanagement, illegality or corruption.''
   Both were asked if they would hold regular, frequent news
conferences, and how often they would be held.
   Bush said he would hold a combination of press conferences,
interviews, and news conferences with regional media by satellite.
He declined to say how many.
   Dukakis said that as governor of Massachusetts ``I have been
accessible to Statehouse reporters several times a week. ... As
president, I would hope to continue this pattern.''
   Each was asked if they would continue the practice of arranging
for press coverage _ by a small pool if necessary _ to go into
military operations with U.S. forces.
   Dukakis said he would ``require the secretary of defense and the
Joint Chiefs of Staff to develop policies which ensure that members
of the press are able to provide coverage of military operations.''
   Bush stopped short of such a pledge. He said the public has a
right to know details of military operations ``in an appropriate
time frame and in a way that does not risk national security. But
the safety of the troops and success of the mission must be
paramount, and I will risk neither.''
   Both were asked if they would use lie detectors to track down
the source of leaks.
   Bush left open their use, responding that his administration
will be open but ``that doesn't mean every staff member will be
authorized to serve as an administration spokesman or interpreter
of events and policies.''
   Dukakis said, ``I am strongly opposed to mandatory lie detector
tests ... to determine the source of leaks to the press.''
   Dukakis denounced efforts to amend the Freedom of Information
Act by the Reagan administration as ``excuses for government
secrecy.''
   Bush said disagreements over the scope of the act will be up to
the courts.
   Dukakis said he opposed the use of press credentials as cover
for covert operations by intelligence agencies. Bush, asked about
the use of credentials, did not state a view but said the CIA and
other agencies ``must obey the law.''
   The full questions and answers are published in the
September-October issue of The Bulletin, the ASNE's monthly
magazine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
