<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-GulfPeacekeepers     10-14 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf Peacekeepers,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Asks $100 Million To Extend Peacekeeping Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
says the U.N. should prepare to spend almost $100 million to keep a
Persian Gulf peacekeeping force in place 12 more months, according
to documents released Friday.
   The U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group is monitoring the
cease-fire between Iran and Iraq that began Aug. 20, bringing peace
for the first time since war broke out in September 1980.
   Originally mandated for a six-month period that began Aug. 9,
the force may well have to stay in place during long, arduous peace
negotiations.
   Perez de Cuellar asked the U.N. member nations for $76.5 million
for the first six months of the peacekeeping operations, and now
says the force will cost $99.7 million to extend for a year
beginning in February.
   The U.N. chief's latest report, dated Oct. 10 and released
Friday, provides the first detailed public accounting of how the
$75.6 million that he requested for the force's first six months is
being spent.
   Among the expenses are the purchase of the distinctive blue
berets and helmets for the 350 peacekeepers, fragmentation jackets
and chemical warfare protective clothing.
   Iraq has admitted using chemical weapons against Iran during the
war, but accuses Tehran of having used them first. Iran says it has
the capability to make chemical weapons but has not done so.
   The peacekeepers, deployed along the 730-mile warfront, receive
basic pay of $950 a month plus $65 for personal items. Specialists
receive an extra $280 monthly.
   Rental of fixed-wing aircraft is budgeted at $2.16 million for a
medium-size cargo plane that can carry 20 people, and three light
planes of six-to-10 passenger capacity each.
   A dozen helicopters are being rented at a cost of $3.1 million,
and two marine patrol vessels _ the first U.N. ``navy'' _ are being
rented for $230,000.
   The force plans to spend $6.2 million for vehicles, including
256 jeeps, 15 autos, 27 station wagons, three buses, 11 water
trailers for use in the desert, and dozens of other vans and trucks.
   Communications equipment in the budget includes three code
machines at $30,000 each and four satellite communication ground
stations with a total cost of $1.7 million.
   The General Assembly met in special session in August to assess
its members $35.7 million for the first three months of the force's
cost, and plans to consider the balance of the costs in November.
Approval is expected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
