<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Push-Jackson     10-14 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Push-Jackson,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Settles Claims With Jackson's Push-Excel Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Friday that Jesse
Jackson's Push-Excel program will pay the government $550,000 to
settle more than $1 million in claims arising from federal grants
and contracts awarded by the departments of Labor and Education.
   Government audits indicated that some expenditures of Push for
Excellence Inc. either didn't comply with the terms of the
contracts and grants or weren't properly documented, the Justice
Department said in a statement.
   The program will pay $100,000 initially, with the remainder to
be paid in quarterly installments over a five-year period.
   The contracts and grants were awarded in the late 1970s and
early 1980s to finance programs designed to assist minority
children.
   The labor department had made a claim against Push for
Excellence Inc. for $434,600 plus $54,100 in interest as of 1985.
   The education department had asserted a claim of $671,300 plus
$61,800 in interest as of June 1987.
   Jackson launched Push-Excel in 1977 as a program to motivate
black youths to take their academic studies more seriously.
   The program had the backing of the late Vice President Hubert
Humphrey and former Health, Education and Welfare Secretary Joseph
Califano. The program received federal grants totaling almost $6
million during the Carter administration.
   No grants were awarded during the Reagan administration, because
of federal audit problems, although some of the previously made
three-year grants continued to 1982.
</TEXT>
