<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-WesternSahara     10-14 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Western Sahara,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Morocco, Polisario Movement At Odds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morocco and the Polisario independence
movement in the Western Sahara remain at odds over most major
issues despite having agreed in principle on a regional peace plan,
a Polisario official said Friday.
   The official, Bachir M. Sayed, said Polisario and Morocco so far
have agreed only on the wording of a referendum on the future of
Western Sahara, an arid northwest Africa coastal territory, and on
how voter eligibility will be decided.
   Outstanding issues in dispute include the presence of 185,000
Moroccan troops in the territory; the Moroccan administration; the
tens of thousands of Moroccan settlers who have moved into Western
Sahara and ``the key issue of direct negotiations, still opposed by
Morocco,'' Sayed told reporters.
   ``Morocco still refuses to shake our hand for peace,'' he said.
``It is proof of their lack of political will.''
   A Moroccan official, speaking on condition anonymity, said:
``They want to renegotiate everything. But we say we did come up
with a peace plan that was agreed to by both parties.''
   ``We are not going to pre-empt the population by giving anybody
legitimacy,'' the Moroccan official added. ``The people of Western
Sahara will decide who shall lead them, and whether these people
(Polisario) will lead them.''
   On Sept. 20, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar told
the Security Council that Morocco and Polisario had agreed to
proposals, including the framework for a cease-fire in the nearly
13-year-old guerrilla war and a referendum on whether the territory
will become independent or be affiliated with Morocco.
   When the Spanish colonial administration withdrew from their
former possession in 1975, Moroccan troops occupied the Western
Sahara and the Marxist-led Polisario began the fight for
independence.
   More than 10,000 people have died in the war, which has cost
Morocco up to $2 million a day to fight.
   The phosphate-rich desert territory covers about 110,000 square
miles and its population at the last Spanish census in 1974 was
only 76,000.
   Polisario and Morocco have agreed on that census as the basis
for voter eligibility in the upcoming referendum, said Sayed.
   The United Nations plans to send about 2,000 peacekeeping troops
to the Western Sahara to monitor the referendum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
