<HEAD>Town Gets Morning Wake Up Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this Pittsburgh suburb
got an alarming wake-up call before dawn Friday when a siren
normally reserved for a nuclear attack was accidentally activated.
But few paid attention.
   Only about 30 people out of the town's population of about
34,400 called to find out what was going on, said Fire Chief Steve
Walther.
   Walther said an alarm in the Mount Lebanon Municipal Building
was accidentally bumped, setting off the siren's wavery wail
shortly before 5:30 a.m. He did not say who set it off.
   Walther said the siren is designed to sound the up-and-down wail
to warn of an impending nuclear attack. He said it sounds a
continuous drone for a local emergency.
   The siren continued sounding for about three minutes, as
programmed.
   ``We also learned our cancel button doesn't work,'' Walther said.
