<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NaziCollaborator     10-14 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi Collaborator,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aged Suspect In Nazi Case Said To Have Fled to West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boleslavs Maikovskis, an 83-year-old who was
awaiting deportation to the Soviet Union on charges that he
committed Nazi atrocities in his native Latvia, has secretly left
the country and is believed to be in West Germany, government
sources said Friday.
   Maikovskis had been living in Mineola, N.Y., since 1951, and was
sentenced to death in absentia by the Soviet Union in 1965. He had
been awaiting deportation since 1986, when the Supreme Court turned
down his appeal. Jewish groups in New York had recently been
calling action on Maikovskis' case long overdue.
   ``The order of deportation has been accomplished,'' Neal Sher,
director of the Justice Department's Office of Special
Investigations, said Friday.
   OSI had had lost track of Maikovskis several months ago, Sher
said, but ``we just found out a day or so ago'' that he had left
the country. Sher declined to say how OSI learned this or where
Maikovskis might have gone.
   But a government source, speaking on condition that he not be
identified, said Maikovskis was in West Germany.
   ``We have no way of knowing how he got there,'' the source said.
Maikovskis had no passport or other travel documents.
   Maikovskis' leaving came to light Friday because the
Anti-Defamation League issued a press release calling on Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh for an ``immediate investigation into
Maikovskis' whereabouts and prompt action to bring him to justice.''
   ``The whole thing is a little bit strange,'' ADL National
Director Abraham Foxman said from New York. ``We are baffled why
the secrecy around this issue.''
   Foxman said the ADL confirmed Thursday that Maikovskis was
missing from his Mineola home and called the Justice Department to
report it.
   ``They said in confidence they know that he's missing and they
know where he is,'' Foxman said. ``So we said, `Why don't you tell
the American people?' They said they can't do that.''
   Sher suggested that the ADL deal with the German authorities.
``His being brought to justice is out of our hands,'' he said.
   Maikovskis had been a chief of a Nazi-created police force in
Latvia during World War II. He is accused of having ordered the
mass arrest of residents in the Latvian village of Audrini and then
burning the town. The 200 villagers were later killed by the Nazis.
Deportation proceedings against Maikovskis began in the United
States in 1976 and dragged on through several appeals.
   Maikovskis had designated Switzerland as the country to which he
wanted to be deported, but that country refused him and he faced
deportation to the Soviet Union.
   In fact, OSI filed papers on Oct. 7 redesignating the Soviet
Union Maikovskis' deportation destination, Sher said, but
Maikovskis was apparently already gone.
   ``He saw the handwriting on the wall,'' Sher said, pointing to
the case of Karl Linnas, who was accused of Nazi collaboration and
was deported last year to the Soviet Union. Linnas, also of Long
Island, died before he could be tried.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
