<HEAD>Bush Closing Gap In Minnesota</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush, who
once trailed Michael Dukakis by a wide margin in Minnesota, has
narrowed Dukakis' lead in the state, according to a Northstar Poll
published Friday.
   Dukakis led Bush among likely Minnesota voters 47 percent to 43
percent, according to the poll, published Friday in the St. Paul
Pioneer Press Dispatch.
   In May, Bush trailed Dukakis 55 percent to 34 percent in
Minnesota. By mid-September, however, he had narrowed the gap to
seven percentage points.
   Along with Massachusetts and the District of Columbia, Minnesota
has been regarded as among the few safe bets for the Democratic
presidential nominee.
   Minnesota controls ten electoral votes and has been carried by
the Democrats in six of the last seven presidential elections.
   The telephone survey, conducted among 690 likely voters in the
week preceding Thursday night's debate, had a margin of error of
four percentage points.
