<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AcidRain     10-14 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Acid Rain,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Decides Not To Decide For Now On Acid Rain Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has
decided not to make a decision for now on a petition asking it to
determine that U.S. pollution forms acid rain hurting Canada, the
agency said Friday.
   The petition was filed in April by the six New England states,
New York, New Jersey, Minnesota and four environmental groups. In
addition, the Canadian province of Ontario filed a separate
petition.
   Don Clay, EPA's acting assistant administrator for air
pollution, wrote the states and environmental groups saying, ``It
would be premature to rule on your petition at this time,'' the
agency announced.
   A similar letter was sent to Ontario.
   In the last days of the Carter administration in 1981, EPA
Administrator Douglas Costle wrote Secretary of State Ed Muskie
that sulfur dioxide emissions originating in the United States were
``endangering'' Canada.
   These emissions help form acid rain, which environmentalists say
is killing aquatic life in lakes in sensitive watersheds of the
Northeast, the Upper Midwest and in eastern Canada.
   The Reagan administration did nothing about the letter, though
the states, environmental groups and Canada argued that it
triggered an obligation under the Clean Air Act for EPA to force
states to rewrite their air pollution control plans to reduce the
emissions harming Canada.
   A federal appeals court ruled against the states, holding that
Costle's letter was not a formal enough finding of harm to Canada
to trigger a requirement forcing states to act. Such a finding must
be arrived at through regulations requiring notice to all parties
involved and a chance to comment, and the states could request such
a proceeding, the court said.
   Some of the states in July lost a separate but related suit
claiming that sulfur dioxide originating in power plant and
industrial smokestacks of the Midwest made it impossible for them
to meet federal clean air standards in their own territories.
   ``I do not believe that EPA presently has sufficient information
to undertake the regulatory program required (if the petition were
granted), including the endangerment finding requested in your
petition,'' Clay wrote.
   Clay said his letter ``does not necessarily reflect the position
of the administrator,'' but ``I cannot recommend that the
administrator take the discretionary action of making the
findings.''
   In New York City, David Wooley, assistant state attorney
general, said Clay's assertion of insufficient information was
``pure rubbish.''
   Wooley said the letter appears to be formal enough to be the
basis of another lawsuit, ``And that's what I'm going to recommend
to the nine states,'' Wooley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spycatcher     10-14 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spycatcher,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copies Of `Spycatcher' To Be Imported From Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The publishers of ``Spycatcher'' said Friday they
will not print the book in Britain despite a court ruling allowing
British newspapers publish extracts. Instead copies will be
imported from Australia.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government fought a long
legal battle to ban the book by former intelligence agent Peter
Wright, claiming he had violated his oath of secrecy.
   William Heinemann Ltd., the book's publishers, said British
booksellers have ordered more than 70,000 copies of ``Spycatcher''
printed by its sister company in Australia. Last June Mrs.
Thatcher's Conservative Party government lost its court bid in
Australia to ban the book there. Wright, 73, now lives in Australia.
   If the book were printed in Britain, the government might take
court action to seize the profits, the company said.
   ``It would be quixotic of us to rush out and incur another
injunction,'' said Helen Fraser, spokeswoman for William Heinemann
Ltd. ``The government has shown every sign of never being weary of
legal action.''
   Tim Godfray, director of the Booksellers Association, said
Friday: ``After consulting lawyers we have been advised that
booksellers can sell any edition of ``Spycatcher,'' provided it was
originally purchased or invoiced abroad, and imported by them.''
   London's Daily Telegraph said Friday the government was
considering new moves in its three-year struggle to suppress
Wright's book. It said government lawyers think the copyright for
the book may rest with the government because of Wright's
descriptions of the MI5 counter-intelligence agency.
   On Thursday the Law Lords, the nation's highest court, lifted
orders that had barred three London newspapers _ The Guardian, The
Observer and The Sunday Times _ from publishing extracts from
``Spycatcher.''
   British newspapers called the ruling a triumph for freedom of
the press, but the government claimed a moral victory because the
five judges also said Wright violated the secrecy oath he took as
an intelligence officer.
   Miss Fraser said William Heinemann originally intended to print
200,000 copies of the book in Britain. But now she said
distributors in the Netherlands and West Germany were sending
directly to British booksellers 33,000 paperback copies of
``Spycatcher'' printed in Australia and have taken orders for at
least 40,000 more copies.
   ``No bookshop is now in contempt of court because there are no
court proceedings pending,'' Miss Fraser said. ``The whole thing is
finished.''
   She added William Heinemann Ltd. of Britain will play no part in
the importation or distribution of the book in Britain.
   To take action against the imported copies the government
``would have to go against Heinemann Australia and that is a
jurisdiction where they have lost and lost and lost,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
