<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Cisneros     10-14 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Cisneros,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Acknowledges Relationship, Will Finish Out Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SA2, DN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Henry Cisneros acknowledged
Friday a close, personal relationship with a woman outside his
marriage after a newspaper wrote about it.
   Cisneros, a popular Hispanic leader once considered a potential
Democratic vice presidential candidate, said he will try to serve
the remainder of his fourth term until May with dignity.
   Cisneros, 41, recently acknowledged problems in his 19-year
marriage. He said Friday he wants to work out his problems to
protect his wife, Mary Alice, and his teen-age daughters and young
son.
   The mayor, who has announced he won't seek a fifth term next
year or run for state office in 1990, talked to reporters outside
his home after reading a newspaper article detailing his
relationship with Linda Medlar, 39.
   Mrs. Medlar, who has helped the mayor in various fund-raising
campaigns, was quoted in a front-page column in Friday's San
Antonio Express-News as saying she loved the mayor. She is married
to the co-owner of a jewelry store.
   ``He's the love of my life,'' she said. ``I've never before met
such a charming, talented man. Our rapport is marvelous and we hope
to be able to live out the rest of our lives together.''
   Mrs. Medlar could not be reached Friday. There was no answer at
her office, and her home telephone number is unpublished.
   The mayor declined to elaborate on his relationship with Mrs.
Medlar, but said it was not the major problem between him and his
wife.
   Mrs. Cisneros, who declined to speak with reporters Friday, has
said she still loves her husband and will not immediately seek a
divorce.
   ``This is a discussion that has gone on for some period of time.
It is nothing new, but it is painful to see it on the front pages
of the newspaper,'' Cisneros said.
   ``Linda is a very intelligent, bright, attractive person.
Clearly we have been very close,'' he said.
   ``I am saying that I am a human being in addition to being
mayor,'' Cisneros said. ``That I am not perfect and that I have
various kinds of needs of friendship and support.''
