<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NRC-DukakisAide     10-14 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NRC-Dukakis Aide,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Aide Dragged From NRC Hearing On Massachusetts Reactor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top aide to Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis was dragged from a Nuclear Regulatory Commission meeting
Friday after he tried to speak out as commission officials
discussed a reactor in his state.
   Peter Agnes, the governor's chief aide on atomic power issues,
stood up as NRC staff members told the commission the Pilgrim plant
in Plymouth, Mass., was ready to open after a 2{-year shutdown even
though it lacks an approved emergency evacuation plan.
   Agnes, an assistant Massachusetts public safety commissioner who
has been working to help create acceptable evacuation plans for
nearby towns, immediately was approached by several NRC security
guards.
   He was pulled from his row in the audience and dragged from the
hearing room as he yelled that he was tired of hearing
``half-truths.'' He was not arrested, but was barred from the
Rockville, Md., building.
   ``If that's the way they treat people, public safety officials,
then that's a commentary on the fairness on this process,'' Agnes
said after the hearing.
   ``My concern was that we were reaching a decision point and that
the commissioners ought to know that at least one public safety
official from the commonwealth took exception with what they
said,'' he said.
   Dukakis and other state officials have urged the NRC to keep the
670-megawatt reactor shut down until an acceptable emergency
evacuation plan is in place and tested.
   But NRC officials said the management and equipment problems
that triggered the shutdown on April 12, 1986, have been resolved.
They added that evacuation planning, while not completed, is
greatly improved and should not halt the plant's reopening.
   The commission made no immediate ruling. NRC Chairman Lando W.
Zech Jr. said the commission needed time to review testimony
presented earlier in the day.
   Zech said later he did not know Agnes was a Dukakis
administration official. An NRC spokesman said the chairman had
drafted a letter expressing his regrets about the ``unfortunate
incident.''
</TEXT>
