<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0722 10-14 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Appeals For Transition Talks; Junta Member Will
Negotiate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with opposition list of demands, plans for
single candidate. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties appealed Friday for
talks with the military junta on legal changes that would pave the
way for a transition to full democracy. One junta member said he
welcomed some negotiation.
   The 16-party opposition coalition, in its six-page ``Proposal
for a National Consensus,'' also vowed to remain united and to
present a single presidential candidate in next year's elections.
   No opposition candidate has been agreed upon, but most
speculation has centered on Christian Democratic Party president
Patricio Aylwin, who read the proposal at a news conference.
   The document was critical of military President Augusto Pinochet
for taking a hard line since his resounding defeat in an Oct. 5
plebiscite on whether to extend his rule to 1997.
   Gen. Pinochet has insisted there will be no bargaining with the
opposition, and that the constitution will be strictly followed.
   The opposition document said: ``Instead of assuming the
political consequences of his defeat, he (Pinochet) opted to anchor
himself to power and adopt a position of total intransigence.
Pinochet is the obstacle to dialogue and accord among Chileans.''
   It made no specific demand for Pinochet's departure, saying only
that ``he must step aside to facilitate national reconciliation.''
   Under terms of an 8-year-old constitution drafted by Pinochet's
administration, he remains in power until March 1990, when he is to
hand over power to a successor chosen in an open election scheduled
for Dec. 14, 1989.
   The document said the military junta's willingness to negotiate
``will determine, in large part, the success of a consentual path
we believe to be indispensable for Chile.''
   ``The armed forces have an immense responsibility before the
people and the future in this important hour,'' it said. ``It is
their patriotic duty to join in the Chilean people's decision to
make urgent changes that allow an effective transition to
democracy.''
   The four-man junta acts as a legislature in the absence of
congress, disbanded when Pinochet led a 1973 coup and took power.
Junta members include a Pinochet-designated army representative,
Gen. Humberto Gordon; the navy commander, Adm. Jose Merino; the
director of the national police, Gen. Rodolfo Stange; and air force
chief Gen. Fernando Matthei.
   In remarks to foreign reporters, Matthei said Friday that he
would accept negotiations on some constitutional reform.
   ``Yes, yes,'' Matthei said in Enlgish. ``We (junta members) have
discussed it quite often. I myself would welcome some of it.''
   Matthei added, however, that the junta would never accept
changes in the constitution's ``main frame,'' meaning clauses
protecting private property rights and an economy based on free
enterprise.
   The opposition proposal called for several constitutional
changes, saying the amendment procedure as outlined in the
constutution is too restrictive.
   It also demanded a fully elected congress. The constitution
calls for congressional elections at the same time as the 1989
presidential vote, but would reserve at least nine of the Senate's
36 seats for government-designated representatives.
   Other opposition demands include eliminating a clause forbidding
Marxist parties and increasing the number of civilians on the
powerful National Security Council, currently dominated by military
representatives.
   Matthei, speaking at the air force academy, said, ``I would be
very happy to have a change that makes it easier to reform some
things, and harder to reform other things, for example private
property (rights) and the economy.''
   He refused to elaborate.
   Any constitutional reform would have to be approved in a
national referendum, but would be assured of passage if it were
backed by both the right-wing junta and the opposition coalition,
whose parties range from the center-right to the Socialist left.
   Many observers see such a referendum as a tool for reconciling
Chileans divided in the Oct. 5 ballot, in which 55 percent of
voters cast ``no'' ballots on a proposal that Pinochet stay in
power until March 1997.
   Of the vote result, Matthei said: ``We will abide by it. It is
for us mandatory what the people said. They said, `no.' We say,
`all right, no.' ''
   ``We don't want the armed forces involved for a long time or
forever in a military government,'' he said. ``That is bad for the
country and bad for the armed forces.''
   ``Right from the beginning we said, all right, it is easy to
take power. It is not as easy to get graciously out of power,'' he
added.
</TEXT>
