<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialPolls     10-14 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Polls,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Gives Bush A Popular Boost</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two presidential preference polls conducted
after the final debate between George Bush and Michael Dukakis
found the vice president leading by similar margins.
   A survey of 529 debate viewers by The Los Angeles Times found
the Republican Bush was favored over the Democratic Dukakis, 52
percent to 42 percent. A CBS survey of 442 viewers showed Bush was
preferred by a margin of 54-43.
   Both national surveys had a margin of error of plus or minus
five percentage points.
   A Times survey after the vice presidential debate a week ago
gave Bush a 44-41 lead. A CBS News survey before the debate showed
Bush leading 50 percent to 46 percent.
   The Times survey also found indications that Bush was beginning
to attract voters who consider themselves undecided, said I.A.
Lewis, director of polling for the newspaper.
   The newspaper survey's results Thursday night just after the
debate in Los Angeles suggested that Bush had won the debate, 47
percent to 26 percent, with 27 percent unsure who had won. Friday's
CBS poll said Bush won the debate by a 48 percent to 25 percent
margin.
   ``The bottom line is there isn't very much good news here for
Dukakis,'' said Lewis in a telephone interview.
   ``There are indications that the undecideds are breaking for
Bush,'' Lewis said. ``And there was almost nothing that Bush
supporters were disappointed about in (Bush's performance in) the
debate.''
   ``The undecideds are going two-to-one for Bush, but the numbers
aren't enough to make a full blown prediction about it,'' he said.
   Lewis said Bush pleased his supporters Thursday night in all
areas except his responses on questions about the environment.
   The CBS survey did have some good news for Dukakis. Among debate
watchers, Dukakis' favorable ratings rose to 43 percent after the
debate from 34 percent beforehand. Bush also benefited in that
category, receiving a 58 percent favorable rating after the debate,
compared with 44 percent before.
   Bush's early defense of running mate Dan Quayle may have had
some impact. He was seen as qualified by 41 percent of the viewers,
compared with 32 percent beforehand.
   The CBS survey noted that less than two-thirds of the probable
electorate viewed the debate, meaning the real impact of the debate
on voter preferences won't be known for about a week.
   CBS found its sample by re-interviewing 729 of the 1,009
probable voters interviewed Oct. 8-10 for a CBS-New York Times poll.
</TEXT>
