<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Senate-Judges     10-14 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-Judges,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves 11 Judicial Appointments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted approval Friday of 11 of
President Reagan's judicial appointments, but at least 15 others
have virtually no chance of approval before the chamber adjourns
for the year.
   The voice-vote decision was the latest chapter in a long-running
fight in the 100th Congress, involving the treatment by the
Democratic-controlled Judiciary Committee of the nominees picked by
Reagan to move the federal courts in a conservative direction.
   The nominees approved late Friday had been passed by the
committee last week.
   But 15 other judicial nominees have not yet had confirmation
hearings before the committee, and their nominations will die when
the Congress adjourns, which is likely to occur next week.
   The partisan fight over judges reached its zenith last year when
Democrats defeated Reagan's nomination to the Supreme Court of
Robert H. Bork after charges he was too much of a conservative
ideologue.
   In recent months, Senate Republicans have accused Democrats of
stalling Reagan's nominees and GOP legislators responded last month
by using Senate rules to block other legislation.
   Of the 110 judicial nominations made by Reagan in the past two
years, the Judiciary Committee had acted on 95, according to
figures compiled by the panel.
   Approved Friday were Richard L. Voorhees, Gastonia, N.C., for
U.S. district judge for the Western District of North Carolina;
state common pleas Judge Richard L. Nygaard of North East, Pa., for
the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals; U.S. District Judge John M.
Duhe Jr., of Lafayette, La., for the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals; and Paul V. Gadola, Grand Blanc, Mich., for the Eastern
District of Michigan.
   Also approved were Alex R. Munson, Saipan, for the Northern
Mariana Islands; Norwood C. Tilley, Greensboro, N.C., for the
Middle District of North Carolina; Charles R. Butler Jr., Mobile,
Ala., for the Southern District of Alabama; and Lewis T. Babcok,
Boulder, Colo., for the District of Colorado.
   In addition, others approved were Robert Leon Jordon, Johnston
City, Tenn., for the Eastern District of Tennessee; D. Brooks
Smith, Altoona, Pa., for the Western District of Pennsylvania; and
Jay C. Waldman, Philadelphia, for the Eastern District of
Pennsylvania.
   The Senate also approved a number of Justice Department
nominations Friday, including the appointments of both Thomas M.
Boyd and Douglas W. Kmiec to be assistant attorneys general; Stuart
E. Earnest of Oklahoma to be U.S. Marshal for the Western District
of Oklahoma; Richard W. Cameron of California to be U.S. Marshal
for the Southern District of California; and Noreen T. Skagen of
Washington to be U.S. Marshal for the Western District of
Washington state.
   The chamber also endorsed the appointments of Jay B. Stephens to
be the U.S. Attorney for the District of Columbia and Dennis C.
Vacco of New York to be U.S. Attorney for the Western District of
New York.
</TEXT>
