<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, Hail Hit Arizona</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe rain and hail hit portions of Arizona on Friday but most
other sections of the nation enjoyed calm and dry weather.
   An inch of rain and hail of one inch in diameter pelted Phoenix,
wind gusts of 40 mph hit Chandler and three quarters of an inch of
rain landed in New River in 15 minutes.
   There were a few showers and thunderstorms scattered from
eastern Kansas to northeastern Missouri and in Washington state and
northern Idaho. There were some snow showers in parts of Maine.
   Clouds were over much of the nation west of the Great Plains and
skies were partly cloudy to cloudy across New York state and
northern New England.
   Sunny and dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures warmed into the 70s across Florida and much of the
central United State early Friday afternoon with readings in the
80s in western Kansas, much of Texas and extreme southern Florida.
   Temperatures were below 60 degrees from North Carolina to New
England and the lower Great Lakes region, with readings in the 40s
across northern New England.
   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s over much of the western
United States, with readings in the 70s and 80s in the southwestern
deserts.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Caribou and Limestone, Maine, to 87 degrees at Blythe,
Calif.
   The low for the nation Friday morning was 18 degrees at Elkins,
W.Va.
   Saturday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from eastern Arizona to extreme western Texas, in
extreme southern Florida, from western New York state to
northwestern New England and across western Washington state. Skies
were expected to be partly cloudy to cloudy over the Rocky Mountain
region and much of the Northwest. Sunny skies were expected in the
rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were forecast for the 80s across southern Florida,
from Louisiana and Texas to the lower Missouri Valley, in Southern
California and southern Arizona with readings in the 90s at some
locations. Afternoon highs were expected in the 60s from the
northern Pacific Coast to the Rocky Mountain region, and from the
Great Lakes region and upper Ohio Valley to New England. Highs in
the 50s were predicted in the lower Great Lakes region and northern
New England. High temperatures were expected in the 40s across
northern Maine.
