<HEAD>Roving Ads Leave No One Asking `Where's The Beef'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Racek is enlisting a herd of cattle
to put some some moo-mentum into his campaign for Congress.
   Racek, a Democratic challenger to Republican Rep. Virginia
Smith, said he will paint ``Racek'' on one side of his cows and
``Congress'' on the other with a purple compound usually used to
mark sheep.
   The cattle then will be let loose in a field near Interstate 80
to graze and advertise, said Pat Racek, the candidate's wife.
   ``They'll stand next to each other'' and deliver the message,
she said. Racek couldn't comment because he was out in the fields
on a combine Friday afternoon.
   The sheep dip won't hurt the animals, she said.
   ``You couldn't use regular paint,'' she said. ``The sheep dip
absorbs into the hair, not in the skin.''
   Mrs. Smith, 77, is running for her eighth term from the huge 3rd
District. After winning a close race in her first campaign, Mrs.
Smith has captured landslide victories, defeating her opponent two
years ago by 77,000 votes.
