<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MyersonTrial     10-14 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Myerson Trial Witness: Bess Was `Very, Very Angry'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of the judge that Bess Myerson is
accused of bribing testified Friday that the former Miss America
became ``very, very angry'' with her for talking to a reporter
about her qualifications for a city job.
   ``She was furious. She was very upset and very angry,'' Sukhreet
Gabel said at Miss Myerson's divorce-fixing trial. ``It was plain
that she was very put out,'' she added.
   Ms. Gabel, the prosecution's star witness, was special assistant
to Miss Myerson in 1983 when she headed the city's Department of
Cultural Affairs.
   Prosecutors claim Miss Myerson gave the $19,000-a-year post to
Ms. Gabel to influence her mother, former state Supreme Court
Justice Hortense Gabel, who was then hearing the divorce case of
Miss Myerson's lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso.
   Miss Myerson, 64, Capasso, 43, and the former judge, 75, are all
charged with a bribery conspiracy in which Ms. Gabel got a job
while her mother slashed Capasso's temporary alimony and child
support payments to his estranged wife, Nancy.
   Ms. Gabel described how her work and personal relationship with
Miss Myerson cooled drastically after an Oct. 18, 1983, newspaper
report noted her mother's involvement in the Capasso divorce. She
said her boss had to write a letter to Mayor Edward I. Koch
claiming there was nothing improper about Ms. Gabel's hiring.
   Ms. Gabel, who had accompanied Miss Myerson to various social
functions, found their contacts limited and her own public
appearances curtailed.
   ``I was told to lay low for a while,'' said Ms. Gabel.
   Ms. Gabel said she began working for Miss Myerson in August 1983
and just a few months later found a telephone message from New York
York Post reporter Richard Johnson on her desk.
   Miss Myerson told her not to return the reporter's call until
after lunch, she testified, and then to do so from Miss Myerson's
office where she and her top assistant, Richard Bruno, could listen
in on extension phones.
   But Ms. Gabel returned from lunch five minutes early and called
the reporter from her own desk, thinking he had some routine
question about the department, she said.
   Instead ``he proceeded to ask me a series of questions and I
answered them'' about her background, education and ``whether I was
friendly with Miss Myerson outside the office.''
   When Miss Myerson passed her desk and realized who she was
talking to, said the witness, ``she didn't say anything but she
looked very, very angry.''
   After she got off the phone with the reporter, said Ms. Gabel,
Miss Myerson summoned her to her private office and questioned her
about what she had said.
   ``She was frowning, her brow was furrowed,'' said Ms. Gabel, but
Miss Myerson did not ask her why she disobeyed orders.
   Shortly after that, the New York Post reported the coincidence
that cultural affairs had hired ``the daughter of the judge who's
handling the divorce of Bess Myerson's boyfriend.''
</TEXT>
