<HEAD>Neglect Charges Changed To Manslaughter In Blind Woman's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS charge to second-degree manslaughter in 1st and last
grafs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEBREE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges against a man whose blind, diabetic
wife was found lying nude on a bloody mattress with a gangrenous
foot have been upgraded to second-degree manslaughter following the
woman's death, authorities said.
   John Charles Gates, 41, initially had been held on a charge of
criminal neglect, according to Webster County Sheriff Raymond Ray.
   Gates ``was really slow to understand what was going on'' when
he was arrested, Ray said.
   ``Even when we told him his wife had passed on, he was upset,
but still didn't know why he was in jail,'' Ray said.
   Helen Eldora Gates, 45, died Tuesday at Community Methodist
Hospital in Henderson, where doctors had amputated her foot in an
attempt to save her, officials said. Gangrene had blackened her
foot and was spreading past her ankle, Ray said.
   Mrs. Gates also an open wound on her leg which was infested with
maggots, Webster County Attorney Aubrey R. Mooney said in a
telephone interview Thursday from his office in Dixon.
   A neighbor had reported the woman's condition last month after
finding her lying on a mattress in the couple's trailer, Mooney
said. He said the mattress was covered with blood and feces.
   Gates, who worked at a restaurant in Evansville, Ind., had asked
the neighbor to check on his wife, Mooney said.
   Police took Mrs. Gates to the hospital on Sept. 28, Mooney said.
   ``It was pitiful,'' said Harry Durbin, emergency medical
services director for Sebree, who said the woman was nude. ``I've
been (EMS director) for 12 years and that was the worst thing I
ever saw.''
   Durbin said neighbors told him Gates did not sleep in the
trailer with his ailing wife, but instead slept outside, under the
trailer.
   Gates had worked at the Evansville fast-food restaurant for less
than a month and did maintenance work and some cooking, said Teresa
Jones, one of the managers.
   ``We had to tell him how to do things over and over again,'' she
said. ``He really didn't comprehend some things.''
   Commonwealth Attorney Tommy Chandler changed the neglect charge
Wednesday to second-degree manslaughter, a felony. A preliminary
hearing is scheduled for Tuesday.
</TEXT>
