<2ND_LINE>AM-Algeria-Photographer,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Photographer On Assignment In Algiers Arrested, Expelled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A photographer for The Associated Press on
assignment in Algiers was arrested Friday while taking pictures of
Moslem worshipers and expelled from Algeria.
   Roberto Pfeil, carrying an authorization form for photographers
issued by the Algerian Information Ministry and valid for one day
at a time, said he was seized by men who appeared to be
plainclothes security officers. Pfeil said they put a sack over his
head and took him to a prison.
   After an hour in a cell, Pfeil said, he was taken to a hotel
room to pick up his baggage and photographic equipment and put on
the next plane to Paris.
   Pfeil, based in Frankfurt, West Germany, was sent to Algeria to
cover riots that broke out Oct. 4 over shortages, high food prices
and the government's program of austerity and economic reform.
   Several days of fragile calm have followed a week of unrest.
   Pfeil said he was taking photographs of Moslem prayers in the
street outside a mosque in Algiers' El Biar district when he was
taken into custody.
   He said he was given no official explanation for his expulsion,
except that one security man ``told me I was an enemy of the
country and had to leave.''
   In Algiers, the telephone at the Information Ministry rang
unanswered Friday afternoon. Friday is the Moslem day of prayer and
government offices are usually closed.
