<HEAD>Fugitive Arrested in San Francisco on West German Fraud Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sought by West Germany in a $14 million
fraud case was arrested in San Francisco on Friday by federal
agents and police, the U.S. Marshals Service said.
   The man, identified as Michael Herman Kortmann, 46, was unarmed
and offered no resistance when he was taken into custody in the
city's financial district, the marshals said.
   He was carrying large amounts of money from at least eight
countries, including almost $28,000 in U.S. currency, said Stanley
E. Morris, director of the Marshals Service.
   Kortmann, traveling on a false Brazilian passport under the name
of Robert Herman Sander, had been tracked through eight states
during a four-month search, the marshals said.
   West German authorities said in June, through Interpol, the
international police information agency, that Kortmann is wanted on
charges of defrauding a Cologne firm, Tekronix, of more than $14
million, the marshals said.
   Kortmann was held for an identity hearing in San Francisco
federal court, after which he was to be detained in the San
Francisco city jail for a hearing on possible extradition to West
Germany.
