<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru   10-14 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0758,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Acknowledges `Tough' Road Ahead For Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 8th pvs, Drawing a..., to update with
Seattle appearance.
^Precede LOS ANGELES</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, confronted
by disappointing poll results after his final debate with
Republican rival George Bush, went on the offensive Friday,
denouncing ``Mr. Bush's diet of old chestnuts, new baloney and the
same old voodoo stew.''
   At a rally in front of the California state capitol, Dukakis
invited several thousand partisans to declare him the winner of the
debate.
   ``The Republicans have been up to the plate three times during
this campaign,'' Dukakis told the crowd.
   He went on to contend that the first debate was ``strike one for
Mr. Bush.'' He said that in the vice presidential debate Republican
Dan Quayle ``swung and missed.''
   ``And last night here in California, well, you be the umpire.''
And the crowd responded, ``Strike three.''
   Dukakis said that in the final debate ``we defined what's at
stake in this election. George Bush is satisfied. I know we can do
better. George Bush is complacent. We want to move forward.''
   Dukakis was introduced at the rally by his running mate, Texas
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, who asked the crowd, ``Did you watch the debate
last night? Didn't you think Mike Dukakis was wonderful?'' The
partisan crowd roared its agreement.
   Drawing a contrast between where he would take the country and
where Bush would lead it, Dukakis said, ``Think of where we'll be
four years from now if we try to get by on Mr. Bush's diet of old
chestnuts, new baloney and the same old voodoo stew.''
   Dukakis flew later to Seattle, where thousands of people waited
more than an hour in the rain to hear his call for clean air, clean
water, a clean coastline and clean government.''
   The crowd at the Seattle waterfront was one of the largest of
Dukakis' campaign. He addressed them from an open platform as a
steady windblown rain fell.
   Earlier in the day, in Los Angeles, Dukakis appeared much more
subdued when he appealed for support from a group of black
ministers.
   After the Sept. 25 debate, Dukakis opened every speech by
declaring his session with Bush was ``the best 90 minutes of this
campaign.''
   But, this time, quick polls after the debate said people named
Bush the winner by a substantial margin.
   Deputy campaign chairman John Sasso insisted at an early morning
briefing that the poll numbers did not tell the true story.
   ``It was the swing voters we connected with last night,'' he
said.
   ``We're obviously very pleased. ... We felt the governor made a
very compelling case for change,'' he said.
   It was the first time Sasso briefed reporters since his return
to the campaign just before Labor Day.
   Long considered Dukakis' most important political adviser,
Sasso's return to the spotlight appeared to signal the campaign's
realization that it had little time left to get its strongest case
before the voters.
   Sasso had left the campaign after admitting he was responsible
for leaking a videotape that demonstrated that Sen. Joseph Biden of
Delaware, then a Dukakis rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination, was using as his own, a political speech of British
Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock.
   ``We're poised for a very strong last three weeks of the
campaign,'' said Sasso, who cited recent economic statistics,
including a widening trade deficit and a report of declining
consumer confidence.
   Sasso said that in the debate Dukakis ``connected throughout the
evening in a very personal way.''
   ``Our best messenger is our candidate,'' he said and showed two
new Dukakis commercials in which the candidate delivers his message
in a relaxed, conversational tone.
   In one of the commercials, Dukakis is sitting in shirtsleeves on
a couch and says that despite Republican claims of prosperity ``if
I were a young father today, I'd want to know my government wasn't
blind to the changes in my life.''
   In the other, Dukakis is standing behind a chair and says the
country is falling behind in the competition with other nations.
   ``I'm not going to let that happen,'' he says.
   Dukakis was introduced to the Black Ecumenical Leadership
Breakfast by Jesse Jackson who told the ministers that what was at
risk in the elction was everything ``we've gained the last 25
years.''
   ``There is hope in Michael Dukakis,'' he said and urged them to
work to get out black voters on Nov. 8.
   ``He or she who would be free must strike the first blow,'' he
said.
   He told them to work ``for one who has integrity, intelligence
... not based upon smile, style, profile, but substance, sincerity
and the will to make a difference.''
   Dukakis sounded many of themes he used in the debate, including
citing former federal judge Robert H. Bork as an example of the
sort of appointment Bush would make to fill Supreme Court vacancies.
   He said Bush's use of the case of Willie Horton, a Massachusetts
prisoner on furlough who raped a woman in Maryland, was an effort
to ``divert attention'' from his own ``pathetic'' record on drugs
and crime.
   He called the Horton case ``a terrible human tragedy. I accepted
the responsibility for it.''
   He made passing reference to the style issue: ``There's a new
word in our lexicon, likeability.''
</TEXT>
