<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru   10-14 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0826,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Aide Says Big States Are Still `Very Close'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with further comments on debate performance, INSERT
three grafs after 15th pvs, He also...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CERRITOS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate George
Bush boasted Friday about his debate peformance against Democrat
Michael Dukakis and said, ``I believe that I moved my campaign
forward by what happened last night.''
   Bush and his campaign strategists combined optimism with
cautiousness about Nov. 8 as the race for the White House entered
the home stretch. Just 25 days remained Friday before the election.
   Although polls showed Bush the clear winner in Thurday night's
debate with Dukakis, the vice president's campaign manager, Lee
Atwater, said there was no room for complacency.
   ``This election is going to be won or lost in the last three
weeks,'' he said. ``We're not going to take anything for granted.
...
   ``If the campaign gets smug or overconfident, we're going to be
in trouble in a matter of days. These big states are all still very
close.''
   Plunging back into the campaign, Bush appeared at a rally in the
Los Angeles suburb of Cerritos amid nearly a dozen air balloons
tethered on a high school field.
   He was introduced by California Gov. George Deukmejian as ``the
new heavyweight debate champion of the world.''
   However, in brief exchange with reporters, Bush said: ``There's
no overconfidence at all. I can remember how these polls can
change.''
   Later, Bush delivered an environmental speech in San Diego at
the Scripps Institution of Oceanography, with waves of the Pacific
Ocean crashing behind him.
   For the first time, Bush said ``we should take a very close
look'' at environmental concerns before proceeding with ocean
drilling in Southern California in the Santa Monica Bay and
adjacent areas.
   Previously, Bush supported a delay in any drilling in a scenic
tract in Northern California pending study of environmental factors.
   Environmentalists _ a key voter block in this crucial state _
oppose drilling in either site.
   Bush also said that one of his first priorities if elected would
be winning passage of stronger clean-air laws.
   He called air quality ``perhaps the most pressing environmental
concern'' in Southern California, claiming that the areas's recent
growth had not come without a price, ``a price commonly described
with four letters: s-m-o-g.''
   He also promised to convene a global conference on the
environment, claiming that most of the major environmental
problems, including acid rain, warming of the Earth and
deterioration of the oceans, ``are truly international in nature.''
   Speaking with reporters aboard Air Force 2, Bush was reluctant
to place too much emphasis on a pair of polls that showed Thursday
night's debate increasing his lead over Dukakis.
   ``You're talking to a guy who, when the polls were going the
other way, I said it wasn't over,'' Bush said. ``It wasn't, so why
should I now suddenly have the luxury of changing my position.''
   But when asked how he felt about Thursday's performance, Bush
said, ``Read my smile.''
   In Cerritos, he addressed a crowd of several thousand from a
stage overshadowed by a balloon reading ``Good night, Mike,'' a
not-too-subtle message to the Democratic candidate.
   ``I'm glad that that last debate is over and now we have three
weeks to take our case to the American people in rallies like this
and in events all over this country,'' Bush exclaimed. ``I mean to
run hard, to campaign hard, to stand on the issues and I mean to
win this election on Nov. 8.''
   The vice president said: ``Last night the American people had a
chance to watch two candidates in action. We were specific on the
issues. We came at each other pretty hard. And when the smoke
cleared it was pretty clear where we stood and I believe that I
moved my campaign forward by what happened last night.''
   Brushing aside criticism he was waging a negative race, Bush
said: ``I'm glad we can wage an upbeat campaign about America. I'd
hate to be dragging myself around this country trying to convince
American people that everything is bad. It isn't. A lot of things
are good about our country and this recovery and I want to keep the
expansion going until every man and woman that wants a job has a
job.''
</TEXT>
