<HEAD>Government Says Troops Killed 39 Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozambique said Friday its forces
killed 39 guerrillas in battles in the southern Inhambane province.
   An army communique said 33 guerrillas of the Mozambican National
Resistance were killed Thursday while they were en route to a
military training center in Malova on the main north-south road in
the district of Massinga.
   Six guerrillas were killed in a second battle Thursday as they
were moving toward Mapinhane, 125 miles north of the provincial
capital of Inhambane, the communique said.
   In the neighboring province of Manica, rebels sabotaged power
lines Thursday, causing an electricity blackout in the central port
city of Beira, the state news agency AIM reported. The damage was
still being investigated Friday, AIM said.
   The Mozambican National Resistance _ first supported by
Rhodesia, then South Africa _ has been fighting the Marxist
government since 1977. Mozambique has repeatedly charged that South
Africa continues to support the guerrillas despite a 1984 peace
agreement, but Pretoria denies it.
