<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Italy     10-14 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Italy,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy To Loan Millions For Soviet Consumer Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy and the Soviet Union signed an agreement
Friday for Italy to provide the Soviets with a $680 million loan to
help produce consumer goods, the Tass news agency reported.
   It also said an accord was reached that could include Italian
participation in the Soviet space program.
   Scarcity of some basic commodities has been a chronic problem
for years in the Soviet Union.
   A consortium of Italian financial institutions will provide the
government- guaranteed export credit loan so the Soviets can buy
Italian machinery to produce consumer goods, Italian officials said
without elaborating.
   The agreements were reached during a state visit to Moscow by
Italian Premier Ciriaco de Mita.
   Italy and other North Atlantic Treaty Organization countries
suspended intergovernmental credit concessions to the Soviet Union
after it sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
Marxist government battle anti-communist rebels. The Soviet troops
are withdrawing from Afghanistan under a timetable that will have
all of the forces out by early next year.
   Italy is the Soviet Union's third-largest Western trading
partner.
   Tass said Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and
Italian Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti signed an accord on
cooperation on outer space.
   It did not say if the pact included provisions for an Italian to
join in a flight aboard a Soviet spacecraft, but quoted Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev as telling de Mita: ``Maybe some
time in the future an Italian national will keep Soviet cosmonauts
company ... in a joint expedition in orbit.''
   Several foreigners have participated in Soviet space flights,
most recently in August when an Afghan national was in a crew sent
to the space station Mir. The next foreign guest to visit the Mir
station is scheduled to be a Frenchman in a launch set for Nov. 21.
</TEXT>
