<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru a0696 10-14 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan To Release Report On Zia Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last 2 grafs to CORRECT date and nature of coup, remove
reference to dictatorship.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan will release a report on Monday
regarding the plane crash that killed President Zia ul-Haq two
months ago, the White House said Friday.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater declined to discuss the
contents of the report, saying it was up to Pakistani authorities
to reveal the document about the Aug. 17 crash that killed 30
people, including U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel.
   Rumor and speculation have flourished in the absence of any
official report on the case, which is widely assumed to have been
an assassination.
   They range from speculation that a bomb, missile or tampering
with the plane's engines caused the fiery crash. Those blamed in
the reports and rumors have included the Soviet Union,
fundamentalist Moslems, and Afghan and Indian agents.
   U.S. officials have refused to make any disclosures about the
investigation, in which American experts took part, citing the
sensitivity of the case.
   Zia was a military strongman viewed as a bulwark of stability in
the volatile region.
   The Soviet Union objected to his continuing arming and support
of Afghan rebels, accusing Zia of violating the April pact for the
pullout of Soviet troops from Afghanistan. It repeatedly warned him
to cease his backing of the guerrillas, who are based in Pakistan
and also aided by the United States.
   Zia, who took power in a bloodless 1977 coup, also faced
opposition at home from Moslems who felt he was too lax in imposing
religious laws on his country and from political groups seeking
free elections.
   Pakistan is committed to holding elections on Nov. 16 for a new
leadership.
</TEXT>
