<HEAD>U.S. Army Helicopter Makes Emergency Landing In Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army helicopter made an
emergency landing in Panamanian territory after hitting a bird near
the Panama Canal, officials said Friday. No one was reported
injured.
   Vicky Boatwright, spokeswoman for the Army's press office, said
the UH60 Black Hawk helicopter made the landing at Bique Point in
Veracruz, 15 miles southwest of Panama City on the Pacific coast.
   The helicopter took off again after an hour and twenty minutes,
she said.
   ``The incident is nothing that should be considered important,''
she said.
   The pro-government newspaper Matutino called the landing of a
helicopter in Panamanian territory ``a violation'' of the 1977
canal treaty signed by Former President Jimmy Carter and the late
Gen. Omar Torrijos.
