<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Right-to-Die     10-14 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Right-to-Die,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court: Hospital Can Feed Patient With Tube Over Daughters'
Objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state's highest court said Friday
that a woman debilitated by a series of strokes should be fed
despite objections of her daughters who said their mother didn't
wish to be kept alive by artificial means.
   The 5-2 ruling, which reversed decisions by two lower state
courts, gives doctors at the Westchester County Medical Center in
Valhalla the authority to feed Mary O'Connor, 77, through a tube.
   Lawyers for Mrs. O'Connor's two daughters, Helen Hall and Joan
Fleming, had fought attempts to use the tube, arguing that the
woman made it clear she didn't want to be kept alive by artificial
or mechanical means prior to a series of incapacitating strokes
starting in 1985.
   But the majority of Court of Appeals judges said it wasn't clear
what Mrs. O'Connor had in mind when she talked about disliking
life-support systems. They said she may well have meant the
mechanical means used to keep alive people facing terminal
illnesses such as the cancer that killed two of her brothers and
her husband.
   The prospect of dying of starvation or dehydration by
intentionally not getting proper nutrition is something the woman
probably didn't envision, the court said.
   In the absence of proof that ``clearly and convincingly''
indicates what a patient's preferences would be in such cases, the
court said, artificially feeding the woman is the right thing to do.
   Mrs. O'Connor, a former hospital administrator, was said in
court papers to be able to respond to ``simple commands'' and to
``carry on limited conversations.'' However, she is unable to care
for herself and is largely paralyzed.
   Doctors familiar with her case testified that she has also
become mentally incapacitated by her strokes and will ``never
regain sufficient mental ability to care for herself.''
   The medical center proposed using a feeding tube in June when
the woman's gag reflex failed and she lost the ability to eat on
her own. She has been receiving intravenous feeding since her
daughters challenged that move, but doctors said they cannot keep
that method up indefinitely because it doesn't provide sufficient
nutrition and because patients' veins tend to deteriorate over time.
   Wayne Spector, an attorney who helped represent Mrs. O'Connor's
daughters, said the women were ``very disappointed and distraught''
Friday, but would not comment on the substance of the decision
because he hadn't read it.
   Barry Bowman, a spokesman for the Westchester County Medical
Center, applauded the ruling.
   Bowman, who reported that O'Connor was ``awake and alert,'' said
the decision by the court to allow feeding through a tube meant
that ``we can provide more nutrients and it should minimize any
risk of infection.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
