<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Rape-Libel     10-14 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape-Libel,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Says Women's Group Libeled Man In Assault Accusation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group called Women Against Rape
libeled a man when it circulated a flier that falsely accused him
of assaulting and trying to rape a co-worker, a jury ruled.
   Steve Carney, who was never charged, was awarded $7,500 for pain
and suffering and $25,000 in punitive damages Thursday.
   ``I feel a lot better, but I can't say I really won because
there may be people out there who saw it (the flier) and formed
their own opinions,'' said Carney, 23.
   Carney, of Scotts Valley, sued Women Against Rape of Santa Cruz,
claiming the group publicly humiliated him in a 1984 leaflet that
named him as having assaulted and attempted to rape a co-worker.
   Testimony indicated during the libel trial that the woman never
went to police and swore in a deposition that she didn't know what
happened the night she went out drinking with Carney and another
co-worker.
   Representatives of Women Against Rape testified that they based
their information solely on the woman's word and by observing her
behavior, which they said was consistent with a profile of women
who have been sexually assaulted.
   Women Against Rape directors Deanne Pernell and Jan Shirchild
said they would discuss an appeal with the organization's lawyers.
   ``They (WAR) stated over and over again that the effect of the
publication on Steve Carney was not considered. We found that to be
wanton disregard for his rights,'' said jury foreman Ken Fein.
   Jurors felt that associating someone's name to such a crime
without investigation was ``absolutely ... despicable,'' he added.
</TEXT>
