<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ContraCoalition     10-14 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Coalition,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Nicaraguan Resistance Coalition Formed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan rebel leader on Friday
said it is impossible to defeat the leftist Sandinista government
militarily, and announced formation of a new group to push for
peaceful alternatives.
   Alfredo Cesar said the new coalition, called the Democratic
Center, will try to persuade other members of the Nicaraguan
Resistance, known as the Contras, that the military solution will
not bring peace to their Central American nation.
   ``The military fight is not viable, what is viable is the
political battle,'' Cesar said at a news conference.
   He said the coalition was formed because right-wing Contra
leaders have have not shown the capacity or imagination to generate
a quick solution to the Nicaraguan conflict. The leftist Sandinista
government has been in power since 1979.
   Cesar said the coalition _ made up of the Nicaraguan
Conservative Party, the Nicaraguan Democratic Movement, the
Nicaraguan Democratic Christian Party and the Social Democratic
Party _ plans to present a peace plan within 30 days to the
Sandinistas, other Central American governments involved in the
peace process and the United States.
   ``Once the proposal is accepted, including the release of
political prisoners, the coalition will return to Nicaragua and,
within less than 120 days, reincorporate itself into the Nicaraguan
political process and participate in elections of a Central
American parliament as well as municipal, legislative and
presidential elections,'' Cesar said, reading a statement.
   ``One of our biggest fears is that whatever new U.S.
administration (takes office in 1989) will reach an agreement with
the Sandinistas, and we will be left out of the political
picture,'' said a coalition source, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The source also said coalition members perceived guarded
interest in the Sandinista government when they spoke with
government representatives during a meeting at the United Nations.
   Cesar said the new Democratic Center coalition is not breaking
away from the Nicaraguan Resistance, but will try to win other
members over to its ideas.
</TEXT>
