<DOCNO> AP881014-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NuclearPlant-Drugs     10-14 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Plant-Drugs,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Edison Finds Marijuana at San Onofre, Announces Drug Test Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of the San Onofre nuclear power
plant said Friday it found 20 instances of workers using marijuana
and will begin performing random drug tests on its employees.
   The testing plan announced by Southern California Edison Co.
closely matches one under consideration by the federal Nuclear
Regulatory Commission for imposition industrywide.
   At San Onofre _ the first plant in the nation where a reactor
operator was suspended by the NRC because of a positive drug test _
trained dogs found marijuana residue in four spots, Edison said in
a news release. The utility said follow-up sweeps found drugs or
residue in 16 more spots around the plant, which is on the coast
north of San Diego.
   The searches took place after the remains of marijuana
cigarettes turned up in little-used rooms in reactor buildings
where security clearances are required, said NRC spokesman Greg
Cook.
   There was no way to determine if anyone who actually operates
the reactors was high on drugs, he said.
   ``They couldn't identify who brought it on site,'' Cook said.
``There's a heck of a lot of employees who work out there, and a
lot of contractor personnel.''
   Edison released few details of the searches, other than to say
they had been conducted ``in recent weeks.''
   Edison said it didn't believe drug use at the plant had ever
endangered the public. Multiple levels of control and other
safeguards protect plant operations from miscalculations by a
single employee, the company said.
   Edison, which since 1984 has been testing potential hires for
drug use, said that on Nov. 7, it would begin random, unannounced
drug tests of most workers at San Onofre. After one positive test,
an employee will be offered a choice of dismissal or counseling. A
second positive test will result in dismissal.
   The Edison plan is nearly identical to one that will be
considered by the NRC at a public hearing Monday in Maryland, Cook
said. No specific timetable has been set for adoption of the
national plan.
   Under the NRC proposal, an employee who fails a second drug test
would be barred from sensitive areas of nuclear plants for a
minimum of three years and a third positive test would bring
permanent denial of access.
   ``We have good reason to believe that the rate of illegal drug
use among nuclear plant employees is well below the level of the
entire population,'' Cook said. ``I don't think we'll consider it
satisfactorily low until it is zero.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
