<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Frank     10-14 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Frank,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writer-Director-Producer Melvin Frank Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melvin Frank, a comedy
writer-director-producer who helped create ``White Christmas,''
``Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House,'' and ``A Touch of Class,''
has died of complications from heart surgery. He was 75.
   Frank died Thursday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.
   Frank teamed with his partner of 38 years, Norman Panama, for
eight films, including a string of successful comedies that
included ``The Court Jester'' and ``My Favorite Blonde'' and the
Broadway musical ``Li'l Abner,'' which they later filmed.
   Born in Chicago, Frank met Panama in 1933, and two years later
they collaborated on comedy material for Milton Berle and Bob Hope.
They would go on to earn three Oscar nominations together. Frank
got his fourth nomination for ``A Touch Of Class'' for his writing
with Jack Rose.
   Among the films Frank produced were ``Prisoner of Second
Avenue'' and ``Lost and Found.''
   He was working on his autobiography when he was hospitalized,
said his son, James Frank.
   Besides his son, he is survived by his wife, Juliet; daughter,
Elizabeth; son, Andrew; and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
