<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0836,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed Colonel Shot Trying To Escape, Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Baula dead. PICKS up 4th
graf pvs bgng, Baula was arrested ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air force colonel arrested for his
role in last year's attempted coup was shot and killed early
Saturday while trying to escape from a military prison, it was
announced.
   Military officials said Lt. Col. Francisco Baula died at a
military hospital about nine hours after guards at the suburban
Camp Crame stockade shot him when he refused to halt and ignored
warning shots.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano, commander of the Philippine
Constabulary, said Baula was shot and wounded three times.
   Officials at the Armed Forces of the Philippines Medical Center
said earlier that Baula underwent surgery and was expected to
recover. The stockade commandant later said the renegade officer
succumbed to his wounds.
   ``I was informed that at 9:10 this morning he died of his
wounds,'' Col. Percival Adiong said in a telephone interview. ``We
were hoping that he would survive.''
   Baula was arrested Oct. 3 along with two other military men
sought in connection with the Aug. 28, 1987, coup attempt against
President Corazon Aquino's government.
   The uprising was led by former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan. Baula was operations officer of the air force's 420th
Supply Wing and directed the takeover of the Villamor air base in
Manila.
   At least 53 people were killed and more than 300 wounded in the
revolt _ the most serious of about six armed attemps to oust Mrs.
Aquino since she took office Feb. 25, 1986.
   Baula fled after the coup attempt and remained at large until he
was arrested with the two other suspects while having lunch at a
restaurant in suburban Pasay City this month.
   Montano said Baula slipped into a ``dark corner'' of the
stockade shortly after midnight and tried to climb over the wall
with a makeshift ladder.
   Guards saw him, ordered him to halt and fired warning shots,
Montano said. They then fired at the colonel and he fell to the
ground, according to Montano.
   ``Our investigation shows that there were no others who tried to
help him,'' Montano said.
   He added that security would be reinforced at the stockade,
located at the headquarters of the Philippine Constabulary.
   Last June mutineers attacked the Camp Crame stockade in an
effort to free former Gov. Orlando Dulay, jailed in connection with
the killings of several volunteers who had worked for Mrs. Aquino
during her 1986 election campaign against President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   The raiders failed to free Dulay but fled with a large number of
weapons.
   Mrs. Aquino became president after Marcos was ousted by a
civilian-military uprising in February 1986.
   At the time of Baula's arrest, the military reported police
found $5,000 in his car and said the money was to be used to
finance a new coup attempt.
   Arrested with Baula were Constabulary Capt. Roque Maranon and
trainee Inocencio Cuyuca.
   They are among nearly 80 military rebels and right-wing
militants reported to have been arrested in recent weeks. Manila
newspapers, citing unidentified intelligence sources, have said
there is a new conspiracy agains the government.
   Still being sought is Honasan. He was jailed last December but
escaped from a prison ship in Manila Bay the following April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
