   Iranian warships have continued interrogating vessels by radio,
demanding to know their cargoes and destinations, but even those
symbolic interceptions are now down to one-third of what they were
immediately after the cease-fire took hold, said shipping monitors,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Both countries have reported efforts to reopen ports closed by
the Iran-Iraq war, and Iraq said about a dozen of the 18 vessels
trapped in the the ports of Umm Qasr and Khor al-Zubair since the
start of the war have been able to sail out.
</TEXT>
