<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv17   10-14 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 17,0552</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday, Oct. 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Politics and Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attempting to forecast the stock market on the
basis of which candidate is elected and which policies will be
followed may be a futile exercise.
   The reason: What the candidates say is not always what they
might do.
   In 1980, Ronald Reagan campaigned against the budget deficits of
Jimmy Carter's administration and promised to reduce and finally
eliminate deficit spending.
   But events didn't follow the script. Whereas Carter's deficits
averaged around $63 billion for four years, Reagan's rose to $175
billion a year for the next eight years.
   In 1978, Carter proposed an increase in the capital gains tax,
but a Congress dominated by his own party cut the tax instead.
Earlier, Richard Nixon had expressed his belief in free markets,
and then instituted a price freeze.
   In short, positions taken in pursuit of power aren't always used
in its exercise. Documentation can be found in the careers of
almost all leaders, including such agents of change as Franklin
Roosevelt and Mikhail Gorbachev.
   But if patterns of recent history have meaning, there is an
indicator that does offer some guidance. That indicator suggests
that no matter who is elected, the stock market isn't inclined to
surge in the following year.
   Since 1948, the market has suffered a median loss of 8.2 percent
in the year following a presidential election, the result of
declines in five years and advances in four.
   It doesn't seem to matter which party wins. While Republicans
usually are viewed as pro-business, the stock market doesn't offer
clear substantiation.
   Democratic victories in 1948, 1960 and 1964 led to stock market
advances in the following year. (In 1976, Democratic victory
preceded a decline.) Republican victories in 1952, 1956, 1968, 1972
and 1980 preceded declines in the Standard & Poor's 500-stock index.
   Did such movements have everything to do with politics, very
little, or perhaps nothing at all? Nobody really can say, but what
is certain is that the stock market has its own cycle, one that
doesn't always coincide with politics.
   Securities prices, that is, are as cyclical as the economy. Bull
markets follow and precede bear markets, just as the larger economy
grows and shrinks in a series of recessions and expansions.
   While sometimes the cycles seem to have little relationship to
politics, that doesn't mean there is no cause and effect at all.
   Wright Investors' Service, which supplied these figures,
believes that recent stock market strength may be linked with the
assumption that George Bush will be elected the next president.
   Expectations of Republican victories, it seems, do have a
positive impact on the market. At least the figures show that the
market has risen every year in which the Republicans have won since
1952.
   It's the year after in which the Republicans have done poorly
for the stock market, and that leaves a puzzling question:
   In those post-election years, did the market decline because of
the Republicans? Or had it risen so much in anticipation of a
Republican victory that it really had no other direction to go but
down?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, Oct 17.</NOTE>
</DOC>
