<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Bush'sRecord ADV16-1stAdd   10-14 1058</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bush's Record, ADV 16-1st Add,1086</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: very dramatic.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush came to the White House with a background as a Texas
oilman, congressman, U.N. ambassador, Republican Party chairman,
envoy to China and CIA director.
   Over eight years, Reagan entrusted Bush with several
high-profile assignments.
   At the Republican National Convention in August, Reagan cited
Bush for two achievements: leading a task force to reduce excessive
government regulations and red tape, and traveling to Europe in
1983 on a mission to persuade NATO leaders to deploy Pershing
missiles.
   The deployment of the Pershings, agreed to during the Carter
administration and executed during the Reagan administration, is
usually regarded as the crucial factor in the series of events that
led to the landmark 1987 agreement between the United States and
Soviet Union to abolish intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   The regulatory task force's recommendations resulted in a sharp
cutback in the growth rate of new regulations and the weakening of
many existing rules, resulting in what the administration says is a
more productive and efficient economy.
   Reagan boasts that the paperwork burden imposed by government on
citizens, businesses and other levels of government has been
reduced by 600 million man-hours a year.
   Overall, the administration estimates the savings in regulatory
costs will total $150 billion by 1993.
   Critics argue that the savings are exaggerated.
   Michael Fix, senior research associate for the Urban Institute,
said the administration overstates the savings by one-third to
one-half, because the panel takes credit for achievements that
belong to others or because regulatory costs sometimes were merely
shifted from one group to another.
   For example, Fix said, the task force claimed consumers saved $3
billion when the government cut in half the 5-mph bumper collision
standard for automobiles.
   Although the material costs for bumpers was lower and fuel
consumption was reduced by using lighter bumpers, Fix said, ``We
contend that consumers paid higher insurance costs as a result.''
   Others charge that Bush's task force also endangered Americans
by weakening or eliminating safety regulations.
   ``In only eight years, George Bush has undermined a system of
health and safety standards that has taken America over 80 years to
achieve,'' said Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen, a
consumer group founded by Ralph Nader.
   Public Citizen charges that Bush's group was responsible for
eliminating or obstructing 20 ``life-saving safety standards.''
Among them was a proposal to relax or rescind the program to reduce
lead in gasoline lead, the chief source of a poison that stunts
mental and physical growth of children and can raise blood pressure
in adults. The proposal eventually was dropped after protests from
the medical community and the Environmental Protection Agency.
   Public Citizen says that ``40,000 deaths and 1 million injuries
can be tied directly to a decision'' by Bush's task force in 1981
to revoke a rule requiring installation of air bags and automatic
safety belts in cars.
   Insurance and consumer groups challenged the revocation in
court. As a result, the standard was reissued in July 1984, to be
fully effective in 1990.
   On another front, Reagan named Bush to lead the battle against
illegal drugs as head of the South Florida Task Force and later the
National Narcotics Border Interdiction System. His mission was to
coordinate the strategies and resources of government agencies
against drug smugglers.
   The administration says the budget for combating drug
trafficking has tripled to $3.5 billion, and Reagan says 4,000 new
drug enforcement agents and prosecutors have been hired.
   In his most optimistic assessment, the president said this year
that ``the tide of the battle has turned and we're beginning to win
the crusade for a drug-free America.'' Yet the same day Reagan made
that statement, his wife, Nancy, declared that ``drugs are tearing
our community apart.''
   Bush's running mate, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, recently
acknowledged he wasn't even aware of Bush's role in the drug fight.
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Select
Committee on Narcotic Abuse and Control, said, ``I'm not surprised
that Dan Quayle didn't know that George Bush was in charge of
protecting the borders. The American people didn't know, either. It
is no record to be proud of since drugs have tripled coming across
our borders in the time George Bush has been in charge of them.''
   Rangel said Bush had ``requested no additional resources,
offered no creative new ideas and generally, personally was
ineffective on the issue as drugs poured in over the borders and
deaths and overdoses mounted.''
   The vice president also was chief of a task force on terrorism
that in February 1986 recommended the United States refuse to grant
concessions to terrorists.
   At that point, the administration already was involved in
shipping anti-tank and anti-aircraft missiles to Iran in the hope
of winning the release of American hostages. The shipments
continued long after Bush's report was published.
   In the vice president's office, the irreverent motto of his
staff the past eight years has been ``You die, we fly.'' Indeed,
among Bush's official visits to 76 countries have been three trips
to Moscow for the funerals of Soviet leaders Leonid Brezhnev, Yuri
Andropov and Konstantin Chernenko.
   Bush's staff says that even the funeral trips have deepened the
vice president's experience. He was the first high-level U.S.
official to meet with Mikhail S. Gorbachev before he became the top
Soviet leader.
   ``You can set the tone for your relationship in your first
meeting,'' said Bush press secretary Steve Hart. ``You can bring
back some intelligence. You can go to a funeral, but there's a lot
more that happens. You're generally meeting with the new head of
government.''
   Richard Viguerie, the conservative direct-mail leader, has been
one of Bush's toughest and most persistent critics but he's
softening as Election Day approaches.
   ``In 20 years I haven't said three nice things about George but
I'm trying hard,'' Viguerie said.
   ``I think he's been good for Ronald Reagan,'' he said. ``Ronald
Reagan never wanted to implement the conservative agenda, so from
that standpoint he (Bush) was an effective vice president for the
Republican establishment. He advanced the causes of the Eastern,
Republican establishment.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Terence Hunt, chief AP White House
correspondent, covered the Republican national campaigns in 1980
and 1984 and is covering George Bush's presidential campaign this
year.
</TEXT>
