<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-BabySwap ADV16-1stAdd   10-14 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Baby Swap, ADV 16 - 1st Add,0577</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WAUCHULA: living with.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dale Swope, one of the attorneys for the Sarasota father, says
Arlena Twigg was taken to two other hospitals within days of her
discharge from Hardee Memorial for studies of the congenital heart
disease that left her blood starving for oxygen.
   Swope said these were larger hospitals that did not necessarily
have the same precautions for identifying babies, and the risk of a
mistake would be higher in them than at Hardee.
   Further, Mrs. Twigg's credibility has been challenged by
accounts from three people in Florida who were quoted in the
Orlando Sentinel as saying that she told them as far back as 1985
that Arlena's blood type differed from that of her parents and
mentioned the possibility of a baby switch.
   Both Mrs. Twigg and her attorney, Post, said the first
confirmation came when the Twiggs received the genetic test results
from Johns Hopkins.
   But Mrs. Twigg recalled that on the second day in the hospital
when a nurse brought Arlena in, she had a darker complexion and the
mother remarked, ``This doesn't look like the same baby.'' She
quoted the nurse as saying, ``Oh, yes, this is your child. Why
wouldn't it be? She has your band.''
   ``I thought, well, maybe it's a mother's imagination. Maybe it's
me,'' said Mrs. Twigg. ``Then we just totally accepted it and after
that we were not questioning, never at all until May, until we got
the results of the blood test.''
   Post acknowledged that Mrs. Twigg may have discussed the
differences in blood types in 1985, wondering how Arlena's could be
B-positive when the Twiggs had O-type bood.
   ``She was searching for an answer,'' the lawyer said. ``It was
suggested to her, whoever she talked to, that possibly the
medication gave a false reading. She came to believe it was a false
reading. She never went to any testing facility to substantiate the
fact because Arlena didn't need surgery then.''
   Mrs. Twigg told the St. Petersburg Times that she withheld the
information from her husband three years ago because she feared he
might think she had been unfaithful even though she hadn't.
   Her husband said that as far back as last February and March he
still believed erroneously that Arlena's blood type was O-positive,
as her birth certificate showed. Even then, he was lining up donors
among workers at Amtrak in Fort Washington, Pa., where he is a
reservation clerk.
   Exactly when Mrs. Twigg knew of the alleged switch has become a
factor in the Twiggs' malpractice suit.
   Florida law generally imposes a statute of limitations of two
years from the date the wrong is found out. Arguing that that
deadline has passed, some of the defendants have asked that the
suit be dismissed.
   As the case drags on in the courts, fixed in Mrs. Twigg's mind
are her last moments with Arlena just after surgery had restored
the pink to her lips.
   ``Her color was perfect,'' recalled Mrs. Twigg. ``I said,
`Honey, you look so pretty. All those boys up on that floor are
going to be just crazy about you.' She gave me a smile that will be
with me until the day I die.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Esper is the AP Northeast regional
reporter, based in Boston.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Oct. 16</NOTE>
