<1ST_LINE>s w BC-PearyControversy ADV16-2Takes   10-14 1073</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Peary Controversy, ADV 16-2 Takes,1097</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Peary: Did He Reach the North Pole or Didn't He</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The controversy over who was first to reach
the North Pole erupted even before Adm. Robert E. Peary returned
from his famous 1909 trek. And the only person who really knows the
answer has been dead for nearly 70 years.
   But that hasn't discouraged periodic waves of speculation, the
most recent touched off last week by Baltimore historian and
astronomer Dennis Rawlins.
   ``He was the finest of the U.S. polar explorers, and he'll also
have the credit of the most successful scientific hoax of this
century. I think that's terrific for one man to pull off,'' Rawlins
said of Peary's expedition.
   According to Rawlins, notes kept by Peary show the explorer
claimed to be the first person to reach the North Pole even though
he knew he hadn't come closer than 121 miles.
   ``My reaction is primarily one of deja vu. This has been going
on now since 1909, and his observations at the pole have been
studied and restudied and analyzed and reanalyzed over and over,''
responded Edward Peary Stafford, grandson of the explorer.
   ``What is implied here is that a man who was an officer in the
armed services of the United States, a commander in the Navy, of
unwavering integrity, suddenly at age 53 changed his spots and
became a crook,'' said Stafford.
   ``I don't think you'll ever convince anybody in the Peary family
that that man was not where he said he was when he said he was
there, and that that point was not the north pole of the Earth,''
he concluded.
   ``My estimate is that we will never know conclusively'' whether
Peary actually stood at the pole or not, said Philip Lundeberg,
curator emeritus at the Smithsonian Institution's Museum of
American History.
   ``In terms of the history of exploration, these were major feats
of exploration at the time, and they were accepted at the time. ...
My opinion is that these are culturally with us as achievements of
exploration. We can't disprove them in terms of artifacts,''
Lundeberg said.
   Peary wasn't even back from the trip when the first dispute
erupted. Explorer Frederick Cook had reported reaching the pole
ahead of Peary.
   ``I would say there had been considerable doubt raised all the
way back to the original Cook controversy. Various societies, the
National Geographic Society and so forth, bought the Peary
report,'' said Lundeberg.
   Cook's claims were eventually rejected, being termed ``a type of
circumstantial fiction'' by the late arctic explorer Vilhjalmur
Stefansson, but they forced Peary into a battle to defend his own
effort.
   And the resulting confusion found its way to the halls of
Congress and produced lingering doubts that refuse to be put to
rest.
   Even the staid National Geographic Society, an early and fervent
supporter of Peary, published an extensive study in September that
perpetuates the questions.
   ``Whether he actually got to the pole or not, I don't think
should detract from his bravery and spirit and his desire to make a
lasting contribution to the people of this earth,'' said William R.
Anderson, who commanded the Nautilus, the first submarine to sail
beneath the ice at the pole in 1958.
   ``Having dealt with the ice pack to a certain extent ... he had
a very tough undertaking. If he didn't get to the pole it wouldn't
surprise me an awful lot, it really is a tough thing to do with
what he had to do it with,'' said Anderson.
   Ralph Plaisted's 1968 snowmobile trip to the pole would make him
the first person to reach the spot overland if Peary failed to get
there.
   And Plaisted, of Wyoming, Minn., said he has suspected Peary's
claims for years.
   ``You've got to picture this man ... he's got frozen feet, a few
of his toes are missing, and he's 54 years old. The man got up
there, and he knew it was his last trip, and he probably thought,
`Why not?'' Plaisted said.
   ``I don't blame Peary, I blame people like the National
Geographic and The New York Times, who were supposed to investigate
this,'' Plaisted added.
   Will Steger, who reached the North Pole two years ago, is
skeptical, however, of the evidence being used to discredit Peary.
   Steger said he is suspicious of the new reports, but added:
``It's his last crack at the pole, everything's on the line. He's
freezing in an igloo, doesn't have any toes, he's totally
exhausted. Did he really think he was there, or did he make it up?
That, we'll never know.''
   Key to the lingering debate is the fact that Peary's arrival at
the pole _ or his northernmost point if it wasn't the pole _ was
witnessed by four Eskimos and his aide, Matthew Henson, but no one
trained to independently calculate the exact location.
   ``In the cross-examination he was subjected to later, Peary was
criticized for having no man with him who could vouch for his solar
observations confirming the latitude. Peary's answer was that he
wasn't about to share the glory with someone who had not earned the
right to be there as he had _ and there was no one, in his view,''
wrote Barry Lopez in his book ``Arctic Dreams.''
   The notes taken by Peary himself to support his location can be
interpreted in more than one way by professional astronomers and
navigators. Peary, the only person who could fully explain the
notes he kept, died in 1920.
   ``As to whether or not Peary reached the North Pole, the answer,
by nature of the subjective elements within it, can never be
anything more than probability,'' concluded Wally Herbert, an
arctic explorer asked by the National Geographic Society to study
Peary's notes.
   The admiral's diary lacks essential data that a modern
researcher could use to determine the exact location, Hebert
reported, and any one of several possible errors could have led the
explorer in the wrong direction. Indeed, a 10 minute error in his
watch _ which he was unaware of at the time _ might have placed him
18 miles away from the pole, Herbert concluded.
   Herbert concluded that although Peary crisscrossed the area to
make sure he passed over the pole, he could well have missed the
spot by 30 to 60 miles.
</TEXT>
