<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-14 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0507</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's merchandise trade deficit surged
to $12.18 billion in August as a record flood of imported products
swamped a continued boom in exports, the government reports.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the August imbalance was
$2.7 billion higher than the July figure, which had been the lowest
monthly deficit in 3{ years.
   Exports were up $1.03 billion to $27.55 billion as America sold
more cars, capital goods and farm products to foreigners, but
imports rose even faster, surging by $3.73 billion to an all-time
high of $39.72 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell but other markets reacted calmly
to a report that the nation's persistent trade deficit widened in
August.
   One year ago, an unexpected rise in the trade deficit served as
one of the catalysts for the stock market crash.
   The report Thursday confirmed fears that had pushed stocks,
bonds and the dollar down earlier in the week. While the dollar
moved lower, stock and bond markets took the news in stride.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three U.S. automakers have reported early
October car sales rose 38.7 percent compared with the same period
last year, when the flurry over big incentives ended with the new
model year.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
Thursday they sold 173,156 U.S.-made cars during the Oct. 1-10
period this year, compared with 140,408 cars in early October last
year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior tax negotiators from the House and
Senate have reached agreement on legislation imposing limited
economic sanctions against Iraq and seizing a portion of a historic
battlefield in northern Virginia, aides said.
   The amendments agreed to Thursday had been attached by the
Senate to a miscellaneous tax bill, whose compromise version is
being negotiated by House and Senate tax-writers.
   Tax-writers hope to complete the compromise tax bill in time for
the House and Senate to give it final approval next week before
adjourning for the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American manufacturers need to install
more automated machinery or lose jobs and sales to efficient
foreign competitors that share technology with their peers,
according to a Harvard University study.
   The survey of more than 1,300 U.S. metalworking plants concluded
that American industry is clinging to an outdated notion that big
firms should not share technological advances with potential
competitors. The study, released Thursday, found more than half of
the plants have not installed any computer-controlled machinery.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four years after the $4.5 billion federal bailout
of its flagship bank, Continental Illinois Corp. is changing its
name.
   Pending stockholder approval, Continental Illinois will become
Continental Bank Corp. and the Continental Illinois National Bank &
Trust Co. of Chicago will become simply the Continental Bank,
Chairman Thomas C. Theobold said Thursday. The company also plans a
dividend increase and an employee stock-ownership plan.
</TEXT>
