<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0544</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Philip Anschutz has completed a $1.8
billion acquisition of the Southern Pacific Railroad, one of the
nation's oldest rail lines with track stretching from Oregon to
Louisiana.
   The railroad, combined with his Denver & Rio Grande Railroad,
puts Anschutz at the head of the nation's fifth-largest rail
company in terms of track mileage. The deal closed Thursday.
   Anschutz reportedly paid $1.02 billion in cash and assumed $760
million of the railroad's debt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 100 highest paid executives in high-technology
companies earned an average of $785,000 last year, and 17 were paid
more than $1 million, according to a magazine's survey.
   Heading the list is Apple Computer Chief Executive John Sculley,
whose 1987 cash compensation was $2.14 million, Electronic Business
magazine reported Thursday.
   The average pay was up 23.5 percent from 1986, reflecting a good
year for the industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by Hospital
Corporation of America's senior management has made a new,
sweetened offer to buy the hospital chain for more than $3.6
billion.
   The new offer of $51 a share in cash and securities for all of
HCA's 70.6 million outstanding shares came Thursday, a week after a
special committee of the company's board of directors rejected the
group's initial, $47 a share cash offer.
   HCA stock closed at $44.50 a share Thursday, unchanged from
Wednesday's close in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. management, under
attack from an investor group, says it is seeking alliances with
other companies to reverse the losses of its consumer electronics
unit.
   Jerry K. Pearlman, Zenith's chairman and president, on Thursday
urged shareholders not to support a drive by Brookhurst Partners,
which wants to take over half the seats on Zenith's board and sell
the company.
   New York-based Brookhurst has launched its attack on management
through a consent solicitation, which requires the votes of 50
percent of all outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The acne drug Accutane is as dangerous a
cause of birth defects as thalidomide, causing 40 percent of women
to miscarry and 25 percent to have children with severe birth
defects if taken early in pregnancy, a study reports.
   Thalidomide, a sedative, caused an epidemic of birth defects in
Europe in the late 1950s and early 1960s before it was withdrawn
from the market.
   Since Accutane was approved in the United States in late 1982,
it has been linked to cases of miscarriage or birth defects in 25
states, study author Dr. Edward Lammer of the California Birth
Defects Monitoring Program said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market weathered the wider-than-expected August trade
deficit report to post scattered gains Thursday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials rose 7.12 to 2,133.36.
   The dollar fell 1.2 percent against the Japanese yen and 1
percent against the West German mark in domestic trading, its
lowest level since late June, following the trade report.
   Bond prices finished mostly lower.
   Oil prices rose, while grain and soybean futures closed mostly
higher.
</TEXT>
