<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SteelImports     10-14 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel Imports,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>August Steel Imports Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased steel imports in August boosted
total shipments for the first eight months of 1988 to 14.4 million
tons, up 8.5 percent from the year before, according to the
American Iron and Steel Institute.
   Exports reached 139,000 tons for the highest monthly total since
September 1982.
   The American Institute for Imported Steel, which represents
importers, stated Thursday that when semi-finished imports bound
for U.S. mills are excluded, the eight-month figure shrinks to 12.4
million tons. That represents 17.9 percent of the domestic market,
below the 18.5 percent target of import quotas, the importers'
group said.
   ``Steel imports are being restrained at the very moment domestic
demand and U.S. exports are dramatically expanding,'' said Erwin L.
Klein, president of the importers' group and vice chairman of the
import firm STEELINTER USA Inc.
   ``It is...essential U.S. leaders in government and industry
carefully assess advantages of steel imports in cost-cutting and
shortage relief even though American steelmakers now urge
continuation of quotas,'' Klein said in a prepared statement.
   The quotas are due to expire in September 1989, and it is
uncertain whether the next president will renew them.
   The figures released by both groups were based on Commerce
Department data released Thursday.
   Both organizations reported August imports of 1.78 million tons.
   The importers said the August figure included nearly 185,000
tons of semi-finished steel ordered by American mills as a raw
material for further processing.
   The domestic industry association said the August figure was up
from 1.6 million tons in July and 1.58 million tons in August 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
