<DOCNO> AP881014-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   10-14 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Way Up, But Buyers May Be Waiting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers posted a 31.5 percent increase in
early October car and truck sales this year compared with the same
period last year, when car makers briefly gave up buyer incentives.
   ``You were heading into the nothingness stage last year, where
all the programs were expiring and inventories were getting down to
a very low level,'' said analyst Charles Brady of the investment
firm Oppenheimer & Co. of New York.
   Now, with inventories at an acceptable 60-day level, ``their
comparison looks phenomenal,'' Brady said.
   During the Oct. 1-10 period this year, U.S. car makers sold
278,932 cars and light trucks, compared with 238,707 vehicles
during the same time last year.
   There were eight selling days in the period this year compared
with nine last year, so percentage changes between the two periods
are based on a daily sales rate.
   The early October period was the first sales period of the 1988
and 1989 model years.
   During August and September last year, automakers offered buyer
incentives, including cash and low-financing rates. Because many of
the incentives expired Sept. 30, some car buyers speeded up their
purchase plans to meet the deadline.
   Incentives, which have become part of car buying in the United
States, are back on some 1989 models and are continuing to pull
consumers to dealers.
   ``We're going in (to the new model year) with some incentives
that aren't all that costly, just attractive enough to keep the
consumers coming into the showroom,'' Brady said. ``You can't
expect too much from this 10-day period.
   ``This is a time to look at cars rather than buy them.''
   Sales of U.S.-made cars rose 36.8 percent in early October of
this year compared to the same period last year, going to 183,652
cars from 151,043.
   Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. said
because of accelerated buying plans last September, it is tough to
spot a year-to-year sales trend.
   But Heaney said some of the big increase can be attributed to
incentives automakers put on some cars shortly after the 1989 model
year began two weeks ago.
   Ford Motor Co. showed the largest increase among U.S.
automakers, with its car sales jumping 70 percent to 58,407 this
year from 38,662 in the same period last year. Light truck sales
for Ford increased 23.1 percent on a daily basis to 33,574 in 1988
from 30,681 the year before.
   General Motors Corp. showed a 31.7 percent rise in daily sales
to 90,183 cars in early October this year from 77,032 cars during
the year-earlier period. GM's light truck sales rose 29.3 percent
in the Oct. 1-10 period this year to 41,010 vehicles from 35,693
last year.
   Chrysler Corp.'s U.S.-made car sales rose 11.8 percent on a
daily basis to 24,566 vehicles in early October, compared with
24,714 cars during the same period last year. Its light trucks
sales went to 19,297 during this year's 10-day period from 19,667
last year _ a 10.4 percent increase in the daily sales rate.
</TEXT>
