<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Zenith-Brookhurst     10-14 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zenith-Brookhurst,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Responds To Brookhurst Challenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp., the last U.S.-based
maker of televisions, is seeking alliances with other companies to
reverse the losses of its consumer electronics unit and ward off
unfriendly advances from an investor group.
   Jerry K. Pearlman, Zenith's chairman and president, urged
shareholders in an open letter released Thursday not to support a
drive by Brookhurst Partners, which wants to take over half the
seats on Zenith's board and sell the company.
   New York-based Brookhurst Partners, an investor group controlled
by Herbert B. Abelow and Nicholas L. Ihasz, has launched its attack
on management through a consent solicitation, which requires the
votes of 50 percent of all outstanding shares.
   Brookhurst Partners originally said it wanted Zenith to get out
of its consumer electronics business. Later it said it had found a
possible buyer for Zenith's computer operation. Now it says it
wants to arrange a sale of the entire company.
   Zenith said that with the help of the investment banker Lazard
Freres and Co. it has contacted other consumer electronics
companies and was considering such steps as joint ventures, sharing
of certain electronics designs, licensing Zenith technology and
know-how, and selling other companies' products under the Zenith
label.
   Brookhurst Partners took out full-page newspaper advertisements
on Thursday, asking, ``What's Wrong With Zenith Electronics
Corporation?'' and pointing out the company's persistent losses in
consumer electronics.
   It wants to lower the number of Zenith directors from 10 to six
and have three of its own people named to the board. That would
involve dumping seven current directors, including Pearlman and
Robert B. Hansen, president of the consumer products group.
   Zenith said Brookhurst Partners has been trading Zenith stock in
a way that suggests its only goal is short-term profits. It said
Ihasz worked as a trader in the now-defunct arbitrage firm of
imprisoned speculator Ivan Boesky from 1976 to 1980.
   ``They may be experienced in the world of arbitrage and stock
speculation, but we believe they have no experience in any of our
own businesses,'' Zenith spokesman John Taylor said.
</TEXT>
