<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-14 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After several days of large losses, the dollar
inched up against the Japanese yen in Tokyo today, while stocks
rose slightly.
   Following the announcement Thursday of worse-than-expected U.S.
trade figures for August, the dollar opened in Tokyo at 127.66 yen,
its lowest level since June 22, when it started trading at 126.70
yen.
   After ranging between 127.60 and 128.33 yen, the U.S. currency
closed the week at 128.25 yen, up 0.27 yen from Thursday's finish
of 127.98 yen.
   It was the first time the dollar has gained in Tokyo since
Tuesday, when the currency began its dramatic decline, losing more
than five yen.
   During today's trading the dollar recovered gradually as traders
covered short-dollar positions before the weekend, said a dealer
with the Bank of Tokyo.
   Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank said some investors also ``began
buying the dollar for profit-taking, and the dollar gradually
recovered.''
   He said investors also were reluctant to keep selling the dollar
due to fears the central bank might intervene in the market to
support the U.S. currency.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average,
which lost 136.07 points Thursday, gained 33.27 points or 0.12
percent to finish trading at 27,306.57.
   ``Although the stronger yen is considered favorable for the
stock market, the yen rose too rapidly this time and made
participants too cautious,'' said a dealer with Daiwa Securities,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``Trading became active as the dollar-yen rate stabilized and
released some of the uncertainty in the market,'' he said.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at a moderate
700 million shares. Among issues attracting participants were
high-tech and finance-related shares.
</TEXT>
