<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-14 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Moderate Trading, Gold Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most currencies in
moderate European trading today in what dealers said was a reaction
to the previous day's aggressive sell-off following news of a
sharply wider U.S. trade deficit.
   Gold prices were slightly weaker in calm trading.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar's recovery was also
partially due to banks squaring their positions ahead of the
weekend.
   One trader in Rome said market sentiment generally has turned
against the dollar. But another said the dollar was likely to
remain ``fairly stable'' between now and the U.S. presidential
election on Nov. 8 provided there weren't any major news
developments.
   The dollar rebounded in Asian trading earlier in the day.
Traders said the rise was sparked by remarks in Tokyo by U.S.
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan who said the group of seven
major industrialized nations remained committed to its policy of
currency stability.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.27 yen to a closing 128.25 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted lower at 127.98 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8211 West German marks, up from 1.8193; 1.5405
Swiss francs, up from 1.5390; 6.2170 French francs, up from 6.1995;
2.0505 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0475; 1,358.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,354.00; and 1.2065 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2084.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.7435 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7470 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $406.30 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $406.50. Both were down from late Thursday's
bid of $406.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $406.30, down from $406.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.40 to close at a bid $409.82.
   Silver was quoted in London Friday at a bid price of $6.265 a
troy ounce, down from late Thursday's $6.29.
</TEXT>
