<DOCNO> AP881014-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 0944EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     10-14 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Inflation,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Rises to 5.9 Percent from 5.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annual inflation rate rose to 5.9
percent in September from 5.7 percent the previous month, pushed up
partly by higher mortgage rates, the government announced Friday.
   The government has increased interest rates significantly in
recent months to curb inflation, which has risen from an annual
rate of 3.3 percent in January.
   But that action has had the initial effect of boosting the price
index, because of the inclusion of the mortgage rates, which stand
at around 13 percent.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson on Thursday reiterated
``interest rates will have to stay high for quite some time'' in
order to combat inflation, but he said the inflation rate will come
down next year.
   The September rate, which was within the financial markets'
expectations, also was boosted by a wide range of price increases
among other goods and services, particularly clothing, footwear,
household goods and alcoholic drinks, the Department of Employment
said. The price of seasonal foods fell, it said.
   The department's retail price index rose 0.5 percent in
September from August, when the index rose 1.1 percent from the
previous month.
   The index, which uses a January 1987 base of 100, stood at 108.4
in September, up from 107.9 in August, and up from 102.4 September
1987.
</TEXT>
