<DOCNO> AP881014-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SoybeanOutlook     10-14 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soybean Outlook,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Leader Assures Europeans Of Supply, Challenges Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the American Soybean
Association says he has assured European agricultural officials
this year's U.S. soybean crop suffered little damage from the
drought.
   Ken Bader, the trade group's chief executive officer, said
Thursday he told European officials, including soybean processors,
the drought left only a few beans shriveled and green.
   ``I told them from our estimates this was not a problem any
longer,'' said Bader, ``and at best, only 5 percent of our crop was
impacted.''
   He also said he assured Europeans that the United States will
have soybeans to exportal though the drought reduced the harvest,
and he urged them to end internal subsidies that hurt U.S. sales.
   Bader said the high prices guaranteed to farmers in the European
Economic Community for their oil seeds make it more attractive to
grow those crops than to import U.S. soybeans.
   Bader met with agricultural industry officials at the ASA's
annual European Outlook Conference in London, and discussed the
meeting with reporters in a telephone news conference Thursday.
   ``I reassured them that the short supply in U.S. soybeans
(because of the drought) did not mean an embargo,'' said Bader.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture has estimated that farmers
will harvest 1.5 billion bushels of soybeans this fall _ down 22
percent from a year ago.
   Bader said the United States continues to press the EEC on its
high internal subsidies to farmers who produce oil seed crops like
sunflowers, rapeseed and soybeans.
   Production of those crops in the EEC has increased 400 percent
since 1981, ASA said, while the volume of U.S. soybean and meal
shipments to its member nations has declined 35 percent. The value
of exports to the EEC dropped from $3.5 billion to $2 billion
between 1982 and 1986, ASA said.
   Bader said the Europeans tried to blame increased production in
South America for the declining U.S. sales.
   ``When their internal oil subsidy scheme is guaranteeing two or
three times the world price ... can we look at South America as the
cause of our problem?'' asked Bader.
   The association official said he stressed that governments still
could help farmers, but they should do it with payments that do not
affect the acreage or price of specific crops.
   He also said Argentina and Brazil have stepped up soybean
production and might try to take advantage of the 1988 drought and
U.S. bean shortfall as they plant their next crops.
   ``Keep your eye on South America as the fall and winter
progresses,'' said Bader. ``It will become a South
American-controlled market price.''
   But analyst Bruce Henrikson of Adams & Associates in Champaign
said there now is some concern about dry conditions in Argentina
and Brazil, and planting has been delayed.
   Bader said agricultural products have helped ease the United
States' foreign trade deficit, but he was not optimistic about
soybean exports in the short term.
   ``Because of our supply, our export figures are going to be
down,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
