<DOCNO> AP881014-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Greenspan     10-14 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Greenspan,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Chairman Predicts Downward Trend In U.S. Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite recent fluctuations, the U.S. trade deficit
is on a downward trend, U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan said Friday.
   Greenspan also said international monetary coordination had not
changed in recent months and that the major world financial powers
still hold a policy of currency stability.
   Greenspan, in Tokyo for meetings with Japanese central bank
directors and government officials, made his comments at a news
conference against a background of a sharp drop in the exchange
value of the U.S. dollar this week, aggravated by a
larger-than-projected U.S. trade deficit for August.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo Friday at 128.25 yen, about 5 yen
below the level it held most of last week.
   Greenspan agreed that the $12.18 billion August trade deficit
was higher than most predictions but said it was better to use an
average of trade figures than one month's figure because ``they are
by nature highly erratic.''
   ``The trade adjustment process seems to be moving appropriately,
that is, the trend is clearly downward in the American trade
deficit,'' he said.
   He said he suspected most forecasts of the August deficit were
too low because oil-import data published earlier by the U.S.
Department of Energy were lower than the final statistics, causing
forecasters to underestimate an important sector of the trade
figures.
   Asked about international coordination to stabilize exchange
rates, Greenspan said, ``The agreements in recent months are
essentially unchanged.''
   At meetings in Berlin in late September, monetary officials made
no fundamental change in the policy of the seven major industrial
nations, he said. ``We seek stability in exchange rates.''
   Asked whether movements in exchange rates this year have been
within the limits of stability envisioned by the seven industrial
powers, Greenspan replied, ``Broadly, yes.''
   The Fed chairman declined to answer several questions about
specifics of exchange rates and about whether more coordinated
support was needed in view of the dollar's slide this week.
   Asked whether his meetings here had included discussion of
adding Special Drawing Rights, a basket-type international
currency, or the Japanese yen as international reserve currencies,
Greenspan replied no.
   Recently there have been some suggestions that the increasingly
strong yen could become a reserve currency, lifting some of the
pressure from the U.S. dollar.
   Greenspan said international holdings of yen are not large, and
there was a tendency for there to be only one major world currency.
   Although he had meetings Thursday and Friday with Bank of Japan
Governor Satoshi Sumida, the Japanese central bank declined to
comment on them.
   Greenspan also was meeting with Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa
Friday, then returning to the United States on Saturday, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
