<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury     10-14 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts Order; SEC Reportedly Investigating Trading In
Pillsbury Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has lifted a restraining order that
blocked Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC from acquiring an interest
in Pillsbury Co. and blocked Pillsbury from taking steps to thwart
Grand Met's $5.2 billion takeover bid.
   The lifting of the day-old order on Thursday, at Pillsbury's
request, frees the company to make an acquisition or take other
defensive action.
   Separately, officials of both companies said the Securities and
Exchange Commission has launched an inquiry into trading of
Pillsbury stock prior to the Oct. 4 announcement of Grand
Metropolitan's $60-a-share tender offer for the food and restaurant
giant.
   Pillsbury's trading volume was extremely high, and there were
heavy purchases of options to buy Pillsbury shares in the future at
$40 each in the week before the tender offer was announced.
   In Washington, Chiles Larson, the SEC's deputy director of
public affairs, said he could not confirm or deny the existence of
any investigation of trading in Pillsbury stock.
   Grand Met attorney Allen Finkelson said the British company
considers the investigation ``routine.''
   Pillsbury stock closed at $57.25 a share, up 37{ cents in New
York Stock Exchange trading Thursday.
   On Wednesday, Hennepin County District Court Judge Thomas Carey
issued the order blocking Grand Met from acquiring any Pillsbury
stock and preventing Pillsbury from altering the status quo until
Oct. 27.
   On that date, the judge is to hear further arguments in
Pillsbury's lawsuit seeking to block the Grand Met tender offer on
the grounds that it violated state statutes that prevent liquor
distillers from selling liquor in retail outlets.
   Pillsbury's retail liquor outlets include the full-service
restaurant chains of Steak & Ale and Bennigan's. Grand Met is
seeking waivers from the law in Minnesota and other states, saying
it will immediately sell Pillsbury's liquor retail outlets if the
takeover is successful.
   Federal securities law already prevents Grand Met from acquiring
Pillsbury stock until its tender offer expires Nov. 1.
   Analysts note that Pillsbury is now free to defend itself
against the bid. Possible defenses could include selling off its
restaurants to raise money to go private or taking on additional
debt.
   Pillsbury has been fighting the bid but has not yet officially
rejected the offer. Under federal securities laws, Pillsbury has
until Wednesday to respond to the offer.
   Pillsbury has sued in 14 states to block the tender offer on
grounds it violates state statutes.
</TEXT>
