<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-NewsSale 1stLd-Writethru f0064 10-14 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-News Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0064,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami News For Sale, Could Close At Year's End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with three grafs with News staff informed, picks up 3rd
graf, ``Daily circulation ...;' INSERTS three grafs before last
graf with details on agreement with Knight-Ridder, picks up last
graf, `The business ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede ATLANTA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miami News, a struggling afternoon newspaper,
will be shut down if no buyer is found by the end of the year, Cox
Enterprises said today.
   The staff of the News was informed of the decision this morning
in the newsroom.
   ``Quite simply, The Miami News, despite an outstanding editorial
presentation, is not supported by advertisers or readers,'' David
Easterly, president of the Cox newspaper division, said in a
statement released in Atlanta.
   ``Daily circulation has declined from 112,000 in 1966 to below
48,000 today while Dade County households have grown by 80 percent
in the same period. This means that The Miami News now serves fewer
than 8 percent of Dade County households.''
   The Miami News has had a joint operating agreement with The
Miami Herald, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., since 1966.
   The Herald, a morning newspaper with daily circulation of more
than 400,000, is responsible for providing advertising,
circulation, production and promotion services to the News.
Atlanta-based Cox owns the newspaper and manages only the editorial
department of the News.
   Cox shares in the profits of the Miami Herald Publishing
Company, and until last year Knight-Ridder had shared in the losses
at the News.
   James C. Kennedy, chairman and chief executive officer of Cox,
made the announcement that the News will cease publication if no
buyer is found by year's end.
   ``It is with a deep sense of sorrow and regret that we make this
announcement,'' Kennedy said, noting that the News has published
since 1896 and won five Pulitzer Prizes.
   Among its staff is editorial cartoonist Don Wright, a Pulitzer
Prize winner whose work is syndicated in newspapers across the
country.
   Easterly said that since 1966, Knight-Ridder and Cox have spent
more than $90 million in operating the News. He said the net cost
of publishing the News is now running about $9 million annually and
would be expected to worsen over time.
   Several years ago, Cox proposed to Knight-Ridder an extension of
the joint operating agreement, Kennedy said. After numerous
meetings, Knight-Ridder and Cox entered into an agreement in
January 1987, which permitted Cox to continue sharing in the
profits of The Miami Herald at a reduced rate until 2021.
   However, the new agreement required Cox to fund all losses from
the operation of the News, and Kennedy said months of study
determined there was not way to reverse the circulation and
advertising declines and keep the newspaper alive.
   Under the new agreement, Knight-Ridder will pay Cox Enterprises
a percentage of the Herald's profits, based on a sliding scale,
through the year 2021, even if the News ceases publication.
   The profit percentage, which was 15 percent under the old
agreement, will decline to 10 percent over the next five years and
will remain at that level until 2021, said Easterly.
   That means Cox could earn $165 million from the Herald, by
conservative estimates based on current figures, over the next 33
years, Easterly said.
   ``The business facts and market conditions in Miami have left us
with only one conclusion _ that The Miami News is not a viable,
general interest newspaper for the future,'' Kennedy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SouthernPacificSale     10-14 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Southern Pacific Sale,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anschutz Completes Southern Pacific Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Philip Anschutz has completed a $1.8
billion acquisition of the Southern Pacific Railroad, one of the
nation's oldest rail lines with track stretching from Oregon to
Louisiana.
   The historic railroad, combined with his Denver & Rio Grande
Railroad, puts Anschutz at the head of the nation's fifth-largest
rail company in terms of track mileage.
   The purchase ``ends years of uncertainty and opens the door to
robust competition in the western rail corridors,'' said Rio Grande
Chariman W. J. Holtman at the deal's closing in New York on
Thursday.
   ``This historic combination brings together two railroads which
hold an important place in the pioneering of the West,'' he noted.
   Anschutz's new railroad has 15,046 miles of track and is ranked
sixth nationally based on revenues estimated at $2.5 billion. The
Rocky Mountain News reported that he paid $1.02 billion in cash and
assumed $760 million in debt.
   The Interstate Commerce Commission approved the combination in
August. Last year the ICC rejected a proposal that Chicago-based
Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. merge the Southern Pacific and
Santa Fe railroads and ordered the company to divest one of the
lines.
   The company chose to sell the Southern Pacific, but had to
overcome the objections of another rail company before it could
proceed. Southern Pacific's stock has been held in a trust for
nearly five years pending the outcome of the battle over who should
own the railroad.
   Anschutz, who made his fortune in oil, gas and real estate, will
become chairman of Southern Pacific.
   Mike Mohan, now executive vice president of Southern Pacific,
will become the chief executive of both lines, which will operate
from Southern Pacific's San Francisco headquarters. D&RG had been
headquartered in Denver.
   Anschutz has said 400 to 800 jobs will be lost through the
consolidation of the two companies. The cuts likely will be split
evenly between San Francisco and Denver.
   The two lines will remain separate entities, although both will
be held by Rio Grande Industries Inc., said Anschutz's attorney,
Bob Starzel.
   D&RG mainly carries coal on about 2,500 miles of track between
Kansas City, Mo., and Colorado and Utah and rents track to other
railroads. Three times a week runs the Rio Grande Zephyr from Salt
Lake City to Denver.
   ``This creates the only western railroad with two rail
corridors. ... Now, Southern Pacific and Rio Grande will be in both
the southern and central corridors,'' Starzel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0303 </DOCNO>
