<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Up 9.9 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished higher Friday, helped by a
strong start on Wall Street and some new purchases at the start of
the new two-week trading account on London's Stock Exchange late in
the afternoon.
   A late buying surge in the oil sector also gave the overall
market a boost, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 9.9
points, or 0.5 percent, higher at 1,840.6, near the day's best
level of 1,841.2.
   The index opened at its lowest level, down 3.6 points.
   Overall volume was moderately healthy, with 567 million shares
traded, compared with 466 million shares Thursday.
   For most of the day trading remained calm, with the 100-share
index hardly moving from a 3-point range. Dealers said the market
had little inspiration to wander, especially because the latest
two-week trading account wound to a close and the new one began in
the afternoon.
   The exchange divides trading into two-week and three-week
periods for accounting purposes.
   Then, Wall Street opened up strongly, with the Dow Jones
industrial average shooting 15 points higher shortly after the
opening bell. By the close of London trading, Wall Street was up
9.78 points at 2,143.14.
</TEXT>
