<1ST_LINE>r f BC-DavisBankruptcy     10-14 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Davis Bankruptcy,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Trustee Moves To Gain Control of Oil Heir's Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trustee in Cullen Davis' bankruptcy
proceeding has filed a motion to gain control of the oilman's
earnings in a deal that made $4 million in 1986 for Davis and his
brother.
   Twalla Dupriest, the court-appointed guardian of Cullen Davis'
assets, said she should have control of his share of the earnings,
believed to be about $2 million.
   In her motion filed Thursday, Ms. Dupriest asked U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Massie Tillman to order the two Davis brothers and
representatives of the Kendavis Holding Co. and CS&S Liquidating
Co., once known as Cummins Sales and Service Inc., to appear in
court and reveal Cullen Davis' earnings in the 1986 deal.
   Officials said the $4 million is in an escrow account, pending
the outcome of an unrelated dispute in Dallas federal court.
   Once one of the world's wealthiest men, Davis filed Chapter 7
bankruptcy last July, listing debts of $865 million and assets of
$1.8 million.
   In December, Tillman wiped out $850 million in debts for Davis.
The judge restored the debts in February, after Dupriest said Davis
had hidden or improperly transferred assets.
   Attorneys said the $4 million in dispute was to be paid to Davis
and his brother, Kenneth W. Davis, in a deal involving Kendavis
Industries and Kendavis Holding Co. for the sale of Cummins Sales
and Service Inc. to Cummins Red River Diesel for about $58 million
in 1986.
   But several banks, owed money by the Davises, argued that the
funds should not be paid to the brothers. That case is now pending
in a Dallas federal court.
   In 1986, the Davises lost control of Kendavis Industries after
it was involuntarily thrust into bankruptcy court by 21 banks owed
about $500 million. The downturn in the energy industry crippled
the conglomerate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
