<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-14 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Moves Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growing pessimism about the dollar dragged it
lower Friday in moderate European trading, one day after the
currency slumped because of the wider U.S. trade gap.
   Gold prices were slightly higher.
   Dollar-buying picked up in foreign exchange markets Friday
morning in what dealers termed a reaction to the selloff Thursday.
But the U.S. currency lost its early gains once New York markets
opened, dealers said.
   ``We have been bearish here for a while,'' said one London-based
dealer, ``but New York has finally gotten the idea the dollar is
going down.''
   The U.S. currency plunged Thursday on American government
figures showing an August trade deficit of $12.8 billion compared
with a revised July shortfall of $9.47 billion.
   Marginal U.S. economic indicators released Friday provided no
help. Retail sales fell 0.2 percent in September from a revised
fall of 0.1 percent in August, while producer prices rose 0.4
percent in September from an unrevised figure of 0.6 percent in
August.
   ``They were nothing numbers, but nothing numbers in bearish
markets are sell numbers,'' a London dealer said.
   Dealers in Frankfurt predicted the dollar's decline will
continue next week.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.27 yen to a closing 128.25 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted lower at 127.985 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7550 to buy one pound, more than $1.7470 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
1.8128 West German marks, down from 1.8193; 1.5305 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5390; 6.1945 French francs, down from 6.1995; 2.0470
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0475; 1,352.50 Italian lire, down from
1,354.00; 1.2048 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2084
   Gold climbed in London to a late bid price of $409.10 a troy
ounce, copared with late Thursday's $406.70.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $408.60 compared
with $406.50 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.40 to close at a bid $409.82.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.33 a troy ounce, compared
with Thursday's $6.29.
</TEXT>
