<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Lower On Lack Of Grain Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed modestly lower
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting disappointment
over the failure of U.S. and Soviet negotiators to produce a new
long-term grain agreement.
   Negotiators ended two days of talks Friday in London with no
agreement and no date for the next round of talks.
   The latest five-year agreement expired on Sept. 30 and although
the Soviet Union has made some large purchases of U.S. grains since
then, the two nations are believed to be wide apart on terms for a
new long-term deal, analysts said.
   Expectations for good harvesting weather this weekend provoked
additional selling of corn and soybean futures.
   ``We're far enough along in the harvesting where you've got to
think we'll be in the 65 percent completion range come Monday, said
Dale Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in
Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.30\ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 2 cents lower with December at $2.95\ a bushel; oats were 2
cents to 2{ cents lower with December at $2.55{ a bushel; soybean
were 1{ cents to 4{ cents lower with November at $8.08{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
