<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WickesBuyout     10-14 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wickes Buyout,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Group Withdraws Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Wickes Companies Inc.
managers on Friday withdrew their $598 million buyout offer for the
home and industrial products company, citing deteriorating earnings.
   The group, led by Wickes Chairman Sanford Sigoloff, announced
the decision along with a report that warned the company might lose
money on continuing operations in the third and fourth quarters and
the fiscal year.
   Operating income for the year could be $40 million less than
what was forecast at the time the buyout offer was made on Aug. 21,
the company said. Operating income for August and September was $15
million below projections, the company said.
   Future earnings are critical to a leveraged buyout transaction
because the acquiror must rely on cash flow to help repay loans
used to finance the purchase.
   The management group offered to pay $12 for each Wickes share in
a leveraged buyout. But the offer included a 60-day wait before the
group could begin buying shares in order to give other bidders a
chance to surface.
   Last week, as the Oct. 20 deadline approached, the company
announced that it hadn't received any offers although it had
discussed selling all or part of the company with a number of
potential buyers.
   Wickes is involved in a number of diverse businesses that some
analysts have said are more attractive individually than as a
group. The company's main businesses include Wickes Furniture and
Builders Emporium do-it-yourself stores in Southern California. The
company also manufactures auto fabrics, wallpaper, carpet and
aircraft and missile parts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0314 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     10-14 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegheny Says Yearend Still Goal For Reorganizing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny Internatinal Inc. said Friday it
still intends to emerge from Chapter 11 reorganization by year's
end or early in 1989 even though the parties in the case have asked
for a month's delay in a key hearing.
   Allegheny officials told Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti on
Thursday that they need time to study $2.5 billion in claims
pending against the Pittsburgh-based consumer products company.
   ``It's very common for large claims to be made, but they are
ultimately settled for significantly less,'' said company spokesman
Edward Romanoff.
   Cosetti scheduled a hearing for Thursday to disclose financial
details needed by creditors to judge the merits of any
reorganization plan. The judge did not immediately decide whether
to postpone the hearing, although he said he was losing patience
with the case.
   Meanwhile in New York, a private investment firm that holds a 7
percent stake in Allegheny International, sued the company's
accountant and its investment adviser, claiming securities laws
were violated in the 1987 financial statements.
   The shareholder, Spear, Leeds & Kellogg filed separate federal
suits against Peat Marwick Main & Co. and Dillon Read & Co.
   Allegheny International has said an unspecified number of
potential investors are showing interest in infusing the company
with cash needed to get back on its feet.
   They are reported to be Remington Products Co. owner Victor
Kiam, Los Angeles Industrialist David H. Murdock, the New York
investment house Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette, the New York leveraged
buyout firm Odyssey Partners, and Paul Levy, former investment
banker at Drexel Burnhan Lambert.
</TEXT>
