<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Farm-Biotechnology 1stLd-Writethru   10-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Farm-Biotechnology, 1st Ld-Writethru,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Science Will Drive Farmers From Farms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to correct name of congressional office to
`technology' assessment, sted `policy' assessment; picks up 3rd
graf pvs, ``The early ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Biotechnology will boost agricultural
output in the 1990s, but the new science will drive a lot of
farmers out of business, says an expert in the field.
   Michael Phillips, senior associate for the congressional Office
of Technology Assessment, said the steady decline in the number of
farmers since the 1930s will increase in the 1990s because of the
higher investments and keen management skills needed to thrive in
the biotechnology age.
   ``The early adapters will benefit the most and the laggards will
be left behind,'' Phillips said Thursday at a meeting of top farm
policy and agribusiness leaders at a two-day farm conference ending
Friday.
   Middle-sized farmers _ full-time farmers who annually sell less
than a quarter million dollars worth of crops and livestock _ will
feel the biggest squeeze from the gains made in biotechnology
during the 1990s, Phillips predicted.
   Biotechnology is the use of data and techniques of engineering
and technology to study and solve problems involving living
organisms.
   Small farmers with off-farm income can almost ignore the
revolution, Phillips said, but medium-sized farmers will have to
scramble to keep up with farmers who will have an easier time
adopting the new biotechnology processes.
   The squeeze on the middle-sized farms means that by the year
2000, 86 percent of the nation's food will be produced by only 14
percent of the farmers, Phillips predicted.
   He predicted that the first wave of agricultural biotechnology
breakthroughs will come in livestock production, while most of the
advances in plant agriculture will not be available to farmers
until the late 1990s.
   Walter Hobgood Jr., director of animal nutrition and health for
Monsanto Agricultural Co., said a new hormone which will be
injected into cows every two weeks to boost milk production could
be on the market as early as next year and will be adopted by most
dairy farmers in the next five years.
   Phillips predicted a genetically engineered hormone that will
make hogs grow faster and leaner will be approved and ready for
sale to farmers by about 1995.
</TEXT>
