<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 1716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Computer     10-14 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Reports 3.2 Percent Gain In Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.'s profit
rose 3.2 percent in the third quarter, the world's largest computer
maker said Friday in a report that lifted its stock.
   Revenue climbed 5.3 percent, an indication that IBM is
succeeding in switching customers to new large and mid-sized
computers without a big drop in sales of older models, analysts
said.
   IBM's stock was up $1.37{ a share at $120 in late trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   ``They (earnings) were pretty decent,'' said Steven Cohen, an
analyst for Soundview Financial Group, formerly Gartner Securities,
in Stamford, Conn.
   The July-September quarter was the seventh consecutive one in
which revenue and shipments surpassed levels of a year earlier,
John F. Akers, IBM's chairman and chief executive, said in a
written statement.
   ``We are pleased with our customers' response to our recently
announced products and services,'' Akers said.
   IBM said it earned $1.25 billion in the quarter, or $2.10 a
share, up from $1.21 billion, or $2 a share, in the year-earlier
period. Revenue rose to $13.4 billion from $12.7 billion.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, IBM said its
profit rose 9.1 percent to $3.46 billion, or $5.83 a share, from
$3.17 billion, or $5.25 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 7
percent to $38.7 billion from $36.2 billion.
   Results in the 1988 nine-month period were depressed by a $600
million second-quarter charge for costs of manufacturing and
headquarters consolidations.
   The cost-cutting efforts showed signs of paying off, as IBM
managed to post an improvement in the ratio of operating profits to
total revenue.
   ``The fact that they can show margin improvement on only a 5
percent revenue gain shows that they're getting their costs under
control,'' Cohen said.
   During the third quarter IBM began shipments of a major new line
of mid-sized computers, the Application System-400, and an upgraded
version of its 3090 family of mainframe computers.
   The success of those shipments contributed to a 9.3 percent gain
in sales, the largest component of revenue. In contrast,
maintenance services fell 4.5 percent, an unexpected development,
said Don Young, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein & Co.
</TEXT>
