<2ND_LINE>AM-Jockey Expansion,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jockey Will Buy Bloomsburg Mills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABBEVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jockey International Inc. will buy the
Bloomsburg Mills facility in Abbeville County and will increase
employment by as many as 100 people, officials announced Friday.
   ``Each announcement brings us one step closer to broad economic
prosperity in Abbeville County, and I want to thank the Jockey
Company for choosing a South Carolina home for one of their
facilities,'' Gov. Carroll Campbell said in a news release.
   Campbell said his office had committed up to $250,000 in
Community Development Block Grant funds to Abbeville County to
assist Jockey in opening a plant in the county.
   Bloomsburg Mills currently operates a 50-person spinning
operation in the 200,000-square-foot plant that once housed a much
larger spinning and weaving operation. Jockey, which will take over
operations at the facility in April, will be acquiring equipment
and modifying the building in the interim, said company President
Howard Cooley.
   ``We are working with Bloomsburg Mills to maintain a continuity
of employment at the plant during the change-over period,'' he
said, adding the company would eventually have a work force of 150
people.
   The plant will produce cotton yarn for Jockey knitting
operations in North Carolina, Georgia, Mississippi and Kentucky, he
said. The company has another yarn facility in North Carolina.
   Campbell said it took months of hard work, ``behind the
scenes,'' to bring the deal to fruition. ``The people of Abbeville
County and state government have formed a partnership to make this
decision a success for the county and for Jockey.''
</TEXT>
