<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Canada-Election     10-14 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Election,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Support For Free-Trade Pact With US Grows To 44 percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Canadians support a free trade agreement
with the United States, but people remain sharply split over the
dominant issue in the election campaign, according to a poll
published Friday.
   The poll by the Environics Research Group and the independent
Globe and Mail newspaper show 44 percent of Canadians support and
42 percent oppose the agreement signed by President Reagan and
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney in January.
   Support increased by 7 percentage points from the last poll
conducted in June, but opposition also increased by 2 percentage
points. The number of undecided Canadians dropped to 14 percent.
   The poll was based on 1,515 interviews conducted throughout
Canada between Oct. 2 and 10. The margin of error was 2.5 percent.
   A victory for Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party in the
Nov. 21 election would remove any stumbling blocks from
parliamentary approval of the agreement, scheduled to take effect
Jan. 1.
   Both opposing parties, the Liberals and the socialist New
Democrats, say they would tear up the agreement.
   The most recent Gallup poll, taken last week, shows the
Conservatives ahead with 43 percent, the Liberals with 33 percent
and the New Democrats with 22 percent.
   An Environics poll published Tuesday found the Conservatives
ahead with 42 percent of decided voters, the New Democrats in what
would be a stunning second-place finish with 29 percent and the
Liberals trailing with 25 percent.
   Such an outcome would preserve the Conservatives' majority in
the House of Commons.
   The free-trade deal would eliminate all tariffs between Canada
and the United States and eventually put Canada's 26 million people
in open competition with the 245 million people of its more
powerful and wealthier southern neighbor.
   It would mean the dismantling of a system of high tariffs that
date back to the 19th century.
   Opponents charge Canada's very existence as a sovereign nation
could be endangered by the agreement, but supporters scoff at that
idea and say the agreement would ensure future prosperity.
   The free trade agreement has raised few hackles in the United
States, where the Senate approved it 83-9 last month. At least 70
percent of the $150 billion in trade each year between the
countries already is tariff-free.
   Mulroney, 49, a former corporate lawyer, led a landslide victory
for his party in 1984. John Turner leads the Liberals and Ed
Broadbent the New Democrats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881014-0322 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NavyContract     10-14 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Contract,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lockheed Wins Contract To Build New Sub-Hunting Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Friday tapped the Lockheed Corp.
to build a new submarine-hunting patrol plane, providing the
California contractor the opportunity to extend a quarter-century
monopoly on such work.
   The initial contract is worth only $200,000, the Navy said
Friday, but ``a full-scale engineering development contract will be
awarded after formal review of the program by the Department of
Defense,'' the Navy said.
   Ultimately, the selection decision could be worth up to $5
billion since the Navy hopes to buy 125 of the new planes.
   The Navy, in a brief statement, said Lockheed had bested two
large competitors and been awarded a contract to develop a new,
modernized version of its P-3C Orion sub-hunter.
   The P-3, a military version of Lockheed's four-propeller Electra
passenger airplane of the 1950s, has been used by the Navy as its
long-range submarine patrol craft since 1962.
   The four-turboprop Orion carries a crew of 10, an array of
sonobuoys and other detection equipment and MK-46 torpedoes. It
operates from shore bases and has a range of more than 2,700 miles.
   Despite the plane's longevity and various upgrades through the
decades, the Navy has been trying to replace the Orion for more
than five years. The service argues it needs a more reliable and
more capable airplane based on the latest technology in order to
counter Soviet gains in submarine warfare.
   Until last year, the Navy's efforts to start a new program had
been blocked either by Defense Department officials or
congressional leaders, mainly on cost grounds.
   But the service finally won authorization in 1987 to launch a
program and solicit bids on an entirely new anti-submarine airplane
that it designated the LRAACA _ or Long-Range Air Anti-submarine
warfare Capability Aircraft.
   Eventually, the Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas Corp. decided
to challenge Lockheed and submit proposals. Boeing proposed a
military derivative of its twin-jet 757 transport, while McDonnell
Douglas proposed a derivative of an MD-87 airliner with a new
technology engine known as the ultra high bypass, unducted fan.
   Industry officials had said before Friday's announcement that
McDonnell Douglas would have difficulty winning because the new
propfan engine wasn't expected to be ready early enough to suit the
Navy's schedule, narrowing the real competition to Boeing and
Lockheed.
   Lockheed, which has built more than 500 Orions for the Navy over
the years and dozens more for foreign allies, responded with what
it described as a ``modernized version of the P-3'' that would be
equipped with a new, more fuel efficient turbo prop engine and
five-bladed, non-metal propellers.
   The new engines, built by the General Electric Co., will cut
fuel consumption by 25 percent, Lockheed said. The company also
argued that by sticking with the basic P-3, the Navy could ``take
advantage of commonality with (the) existing P-3 support structure
to reduce program cost.''
   The Navy did not offer any explanation on Friday why it selected
Lockheed over Boeing and McDonnell Douglas.
   The Navy did say that Lockheed had submitted the lowest bid, but
added it also had considered such factors as life-cycle costs;
compliance with technical requirements; and logistic support in
judging the bids.
   The Navy said it expected the Defense Acquisition Board to
review the program in December, hopefully clearing the way for
full-scale development. The Navy expects the first prototype to fly
in September 1991, with production deliveries beginning in 1994.
   The ``fly-away cost estimate'' for each plane is $39.1 million,
the Navy said.
   ``We're delighted with the Navy's selection,'' said Jim
Ragsdale, a Lockheed spokesman in Burbank, Calif.
   ``It represents a program that Lockheed has worked very hard to
win over the past year, and it represents an opportunity to
continue a long history of more than 50 years of pioneering
maritime patrol aircraft.''
   Despite the Navy's announcement, the future of the new patrol
aircraft is anything but certain. Congress still could withhold an
appropriation to start full-scale production, or the Navy may have
to shift its weapon priorities because of expected budget cuts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
