<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-14 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Retreats, Gold Heads Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gloomy trade report continued to take its toll
on the dollar Friday, as dealers shed more of the U.S. currency in
favor of other foreign money.
   Gold prices headed higher. Republic National Bank in New York
quoted gold at $409 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, up from $406.70
Thursday.
   Traders said that Thursday's trade report, which showed a
widening $12.18 billion gap in August, vs. a revised $9.47 billion
July shortfall, prolonged the bearish sentiment toward the dollar.
   Economic indicators released Friday also provided no help,
traders said. Retail sales fell 0.2 percent in September from a
revised fall of 0.1 percent in August, while producer prices rose
0.4 percent in September from an unrevised figure of 0.6 percent in
August.
   Traders said reports of soft economic growth, coupled with the
upcoming election, make the dollar a lot less attractive these days.
   ``I don't find any reasons to buy dollars and I believe most of
the market feels that way, too,'' said Earl I. Johnson, a trader
for Harris Trust & Co. in Chicago.
   Dan Holland, a trader at Discount Corp. in New York, said the
absence of any central-bank intervention to prop up the dollar also
contributed to its decline Friday.
   ``It seems the central banks would prefer it lower,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.27 yen to a closing 128.25 yen. It was
quoted lower at 127.985 yen in London. Later, in New York, the
dollar stood at 127.53 yen, up from 127.425.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7550 to buy one pound, more than $1.7470 late Thursday. Sterling
fetched $1.75975 in New York, up from $1.7505 Thursday.
   Other later dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.80395 West German marks, down from 1.81525;
1.5243 Swiss francs, down from 1.5318; 1.2048 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.20745; 6.1765 French francs, down from 6.1880; and
1,344.75 Italian lire, down from 1,351.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, vs. late Thursday: 1.8128 West
German marks, down from 1.8193; 1.5305 Swiss francs, down from
1.5390; 6.1945 French francs, down from 6.1995; 2.0470 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.0475; 1,352.50 Italian lire, down from
1,354.00; 1.2048 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2084
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
rose to $409.10 a troy ounce from $406.90 Thursday. Earlier in
London it rose $2.40 to $409.10; in Zurich it rose $2.10 to
$406.50; and in Hong Kong it fell $1.40 to $409.82.
   Silver prices were higher. On the New York Comex silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $6.365 a troy ounce from $6.303
Thursday. In London it gained 4 cents to $6.33 an ounce.
</TEXT>
