<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-14 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Surges On Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices roared to new life-of-contract highs
across the board Friday on New York's Commodity Exchange on fears
that unrest in South America could exacerbate an already tight
supply situation.
   On other markets, precious metals also advanced; energy futures
surged; grains and soybeans moved lower; livestock and meat were
mixed; and stock-index futures retreated.
   Copper for delivery in December shot up 5.75 cents to $1.2535 a
pound and analysts said prices could reach or exceed last year's
all-time high of $1.46 if the demand for tight supplies remained
strong.
   ``Copper continues to explode,'' said Craig Sloane, metals
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``It's in an
accelerating phase right now; you've got everything working for
you.''
   Major factors in the sharp rally included the possiblity of a
general strike Monday in Peru, the world's 7th largest copper
producer, and of civil unrest in Chile, the No. 1 copper country,
due to the election defeat of General Augusto Pinochet, analysts
said.
   The Commodity Exchange reported warehouse stocks of copper at
11,529 tons, down 846 tons from last week and sharply below the
approximately 80,000 tons in Comex warehouses a year earlier.
   Traders and analysts expected the London Metal Exchange to
report a drop of about 8,000 metric tons in its warehouse stocks on
Monday, Sloane said.
   Although worldwide demand from copper consumers remains strong,
the market has not seen the sort of panic buying that marked last
year's dramatic rally, Sloane said. Copper prices more than doubled
during last year but rarely have fallen below 90 cents a pound this
year.
   ``I think the market is a little bit accustomed to it, so it's
not the same kind of situation we had last year,'' Sloane said.
   Other copper contracts settled $4.35 to $4.50 higher.
   Platinum futures rose sharply on the New York Mercantile
Exchange but the other precious metals posted only moderate gains
in response to higher oil prices.
   The platinum market faces fairly tight supplies and was boosted
Friday by strong technical signals, Sloane said.
   Platinum settled $9.80 to $11.30 higher with October at $527.20
a troy ounce.
   On the Comex, gold was $2.10 to $2.20 higher with December at
$412.50 a troy ounce; silver was 6 cents to 6.2 cents higher with
December at $6.435 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures soared on the New York Mercantile Exchange on ideas
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was nearing
agreement on new production quotas to stabilize crude oil prices.
   Rumors suggested the overall OPEC quota would be increased,
analysts said. But if all OPEC members abided by their new quotas _
something they have not been doing recently _ total production
would be below the amount of OPEC crude oil currently being
produced.
   ``It's possible this could come to pass and, if it does, we will
see the market rally sharply, said Peter Beutel, energy analyst in
New York with Elders Futures Inc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 59 cents to 71 cents
higher with November at $14.92 a barrel; heating oil was 1.46 cents
to 1.72 cents higher with November at 43.21 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .80 cent to 1.27 cents higher with November
at 45.42 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures settled moderately lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting disappointment over the failure
of U.S. and Soviet negotiators to produce a new long-term grain
agreement.
   Negotiators ended two days of talks Friday in London with no
agreement and no date for the next round of talks.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 7{ cents lower with December at $4.28}
a bushel; corn was unchanged to 3{ cents lower with December at
$2.93} a bushel; oats were 5{ cents lower to { cent higher with
December at $2.52{ a bushel; soybeans were 9 cents lower to { cent
higher with November at $8.04 a bushel.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, pressured by sluggish demand from packing houses and
retailers, analysts said.
   Hogs advanced in line with higher cash prices while frozen pork
bellies declined on profit-taking.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .47 cent lower with October at
72.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .53 cent lower to .03 cent
higher with October at 82 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent
lower to .65 cent higher with October at 40.42 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .27 cent to .45 cent lower with February
at 49 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures were nearly unchanged on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the December Standard & Poor's 500
contract settled .10 point lower at 276.90.
</TEXT>
