<2ND_LINE>AM-Xidex Layoffs,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Disk Maker Closing Plant, Laying Off 825</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xidex Corp. is closing a plant in suburban
Irvine that makes computer disks, putting 825 employees out of
work, a spokeswoman said Friday.
   The company laid off 180 workers last week and furloughed 645
Thursday and Friday, said Jo McKee, a spokeswoman for Anacomp Inc.,
Xidex's parent company in Indianapolis.
   Xidex, a maker of hard disks used to store information in
computers, is consolidating production of rigid oxide disks _ the
type made at Irvine _ at its 1,800-employee Santa Clara plant,
McKee said.
   She said about 40 of the Irvine employees would be offered
transfers to Santa Clara.
   The move was made in view of softening demand for the rigid
oxide disks and forecasts they will be replaced by newer
technology, McKee said.
   Xidex was bought six weeks ago by Anacomp, which produces
computer equipment and software.
</TEXT>
