<HEAD>Eastern Union Seeks Documents Related To Shuttle Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union representing machinists at Eastern
Airlines filed a request Friday to examine all documents related to
the planned $365 million sale of the carrier's Northeast air
shuttle to developer Donald Trump.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers asked U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker to reopen
discovery in a suit in which the union charges that Eastern's sale
of various assets is part of an effort to undermine the strength of
organized labor.
   ``Eastern's present plan to dispose of the air shuttle
constitutes its latest effort to undermine the status of its
unions,'' the machinists said in papers filed in U.S. District
Court.
   The union said it needed to examine the sale documents in order
to prepare a request for a preliminary injunction to stop the deal
from being completed.
   The motion noted that the shuttle operation, which serves New
York, Boston and Washington, is the only profitable section of
ailing Eastern.
   Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of Texas Air Corp., Eastern's
parent, said earlier this week he expects the sale to be completed
by Dec. 15. Besides the planned court challenge by the machinists,
the acquisition also must undergo scrutiny by the Department of
Transportation.
