<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-88 2240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SeafoodSeized     10-14 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seafood Seized,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marshals Throw Legal Net over Big Haul Of Rotting Seafood</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal marshals threw a legal net over more than
1.3 million pounds of rotting and rodent-infested seafood at a
northwest suburban warehouse, the U.S. attorney's office said
Friday.
   Marshals sealed freezers containing about $2.5 million worth of
seafood at Impex Shrimp and Fish Co. after U.S. Food and Drug
Administration inspectors found rodent feces and infestation, as
well as decomposition, according to Assistant U.S. Attorney
Frederick Branding.
   Impex distributes seafood nationally, he said.
   The seafood, seized under a warrant, included scallops, lobster
tails, shrimp, frog legs, cod, sole and red snapper, Branding said.
   There had been no reports of the tainted seafood's reaching
consumers, he said.
   FDA District Director Raymond Mlecko said there was no health
hazard involved.
   ``You cannot get sick from eating it,'' Mlecko said.
   The owner of Impex, Bernard Kane, was not available immediately
for comment Friday afternoon, his office manager said.
   According to a complaint filed before U.S. District Judge John
Nordberg, the seized items ``consist in part of a filthy substance
because they contain rodent fecal pellets, and consist in whole or
in part of a putrid or decomposed substance.''
   FDA investigators discovered unsanitary conditions in a
30,000-square-foot freezer warehouse during a recent inspection,
Branding said.
   If the company protests the seizure, a court hearing will be
held so the company can present evidence that the fish is not
contaminated and is salvageable, he said.
   Impex cannot sell or move any of the alleged contaminated
products without court permission, Branding said.
   Some of the seafood was imported from Mexico, but the products
``came from all over,'' he said.
   Investigators believe the seafood might have been decomposing
when it arrived in Elk Grove Village, Branding said.
   The federal court complaint seeks to have th fish destroyed at
Impex's expense.
</TEXT>
