<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     10-14 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Request To Block Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge in Delaware on Friday
denied an attempt by Polaroid Corp. to block a hostile takeover bid
by the Disney family-owned Shamrock Holdings Inc.
   U.S. District Judge Caleb Wright ruled that Polaroid had proven
no ``reasonable probability of success'' if the case had gone to
trial or irreparable damage from Shamrock's $42-a-share offer. He
refused to issue a temporary injunction against the bid.
   The decision keeps alive the takeover effort by Shamrock, the
Burbank, Calif.-based television and radio concern wholly owned by
the family of Roy E. Disney, nephew of the late animator.
   Rumors circulated on Wall Street Friday that Forstmann Little &
Co., a New York leveraged buyout concern, was about to make its own
offer for Polaroid for $46 a share. Forstmann Little was rebuffed
in August when it approached Polaroid about a friendly takeover.
   Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips declined to comment on the
new rumor.
   ``We are delighted that the federal court has ruled in our
favor,'' Shamrock president Stanley P. Gold said in a statement.
   ``Now that one of the roadblocks Polaroid sought to erect to
prevent Polaroid stockholders from accepting our premium cash
tender offer has been eliminated, we are hopeful that Polaroid will
reconsider its decision not to meet with us,'' he said.
   The instant camera pioneer filed the suit last month seeking to
block Shamrock from acquiring any additional shares of the company
that introduced instant snapshots in 1948 and compel it to divest
of its current 5 million shares.
   ``Polaroid attorneys are studying the decision of Judge Wright
to deny the company's motion for a preliminary injunction against
Shamrock's tender offer and will determine the next steps,''
Polaroid said in a statement.
   The decision does not affect a trial scheduled to begin
Wednesday in Delaware Court of Chancery on Shamrock's lawsuit
against Polaroid's recently issued employee stock ownership plan.
Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware.
   Shamrock on Friday also extended its $42 a share tender offer
for Polaroid until October 27. The offer was to expire on Monday.
   Shamrock was rebuffed in an unsolicited takeover bid before
making a sweetened hostile offer last month that values Polaroid at
$2.6 billion. Polaroid said the offer was too low and advised
shareholders to reject it.
   Polaroid stock rose $2.12{ to $40 in consolidated New York Stock
Exchange trading Friday.
   A major point of controversy between the companies is Polaroid's
employee stock ownership plan, or ESOP, which places 14 percent of
company stock in employee hands. Shamrock has refused to recognize
the ESOP.
   Employees are paying for the shares with a 5 percent pay cut.
Polaroid had to borrow $285 million to fund the $300 million ESOP.
   Polaroid asked the federal court in Wilmington, Del., to issue a
temporary injunction against what it called a ``manipulative,
deceptive and materially false'' tender offer.
   Attorneys for Polaroid maintained Shamrock violated securities
laws because its offer was not extended to all valid shares, and
did not include its investment bankers, Wertheim, Schroder & Co.
and Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., as co-bidders.
   Polaroid attorneys said the investment houses would obtain $100
million in stock, or 21 percent control of Polaroid, for $46
million. But Shamrock said the investment bankers only brought the
deal to Shamrock's attention and the 21 percent stake was part of a
fee arrangement.
   Analysts were not surprised by the judge's decision.
   ``I think that was basically expected. That was a normal move
for Polaroid or any company under attack to do _ to accuse a
pursuer of securities violations,'' said Polaroid analyst Eugene
Glazer of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.

</TEXT>
