<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed into law a bill aimed
at spurring the manufacture of vehicles that can run on fuels other
than gasoline.
   ``This bill is a landmark in the quest for alternative forms of
energy,'' Reagan said Friday.
   The legislation has been billed by its supporters as providing a
means of lowering U.S. dependence on foreign oil, cutting pollution
and curbing the nation's trade deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miami News, an afternoon newspaper that has won
five Pulitzer prizes, will be closed by the end of the year if no
buyer can be found, parent Cox Enterprises said.
   The staff of The News, which was founded in 1896, was informed
of the decision Friday.
   Cox officials said The News was losing too much money. The
newspaper has operated since 1966 under a joint operating agreement
with The Miami Herald, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese yen is strong and the dollar is
weak, and salmon fanciers in the Northwest are paying for this
lesson in international economics at the fish counter.
   ``It's outrageous,'' said John Russell of Pure Food Fish in
Seattle's Pike Place Market. Fresh chinook, or king, salmon steaks
and filets that sold a year ago for $4.95 and $5.95 a pound now run
$7.95 to $8.95, Russell said Friday.
   The bad news for consumers has been good news for Northwest
fishermen, who have been netting many more dollars for the same
amount of work.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has signaled that
the new hope for producing more food is in the hands of farmers,
not the collective system built with the blood of millions of
Soviets.
   In a major speech published Friday on the front pages of Soviet
newspapers, Gorbachev didn't say outright that collectivization was
a mistake and should be scrapped.
   But his stress was no longer on the collectively run farms or on
those owned and operated by the state. They have been the backbone
of Soviet agriculture since the late 1920s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Harding is a different kind of tailor,
crafting clothing that conveys a message about the environment _ a
message that grows because his fashions are made of grass growing
on fabric.
   Harding, an artist, began growing grass on clothing and other
objects about nine years ago. Now, he has decided to see if there's
a market for grass clothing.
   ``I'll be selling long grass-covered robes'' for $150, he says.
``And I'm putting together an $85 grass-growing kit.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ended little changed Friday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials closed with an 0.18 loss at 2,133.18.
   Bonds finished unchanged to slightly higher, the dollar mostly
weakened, gold rose, and other commodities were mixed.
</TEXT>
